{"title_page": "Armas Ralph Gustaf Gr\u00e4sbeck", "text_new": "'''Armas Ralph Gustaf Grasbeck''' (July 6, 1930, [[Helsinki]] \u2013 January 22, 2016),<ref>[https://laboratoriolaaketiede.yhdistysavain.fi/?x118281=200732 Professori Ralph Gr\u00e4sbeck in memoriam] {{in lang|fi}}</ref> best known as  Ralph Gr\u00e4sbeck, was a Finnish physician and clinical [[biochemist]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=wrzkAAAAMAAJ&q=Armas+Ralph+Gustaf+Gr%C3%A4sbeck&dq=Armas+Ralph+Gustaf+Gr%C3%A4sbeck&hl=en&ei=l07mTKKqJ8qXhQepqbn9DA&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CCoQ6AEwAA \"Gr\u00e4sbeck,  Ralph Gustaf Armas\"]. ''Who's Who in the World 2012. Who's Who, Berkeley Heights NJ 2012</ref> He was best known for his contribution to the identification and naming of the [[Imerslund-Gr\u00e4sbeck syndrome]].<ref>Bartolucci, Susan L. and Forbis, Pat (eds). [https://books.google.com/books?id=isqcnR6ryz0C&pg=PA289&dq=Grasbeck,+Ralph+imerslund&hl=en&ei=dlTmTJ3HEYjJhAeQueSNDQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CCUQ6AEwADgK#v=onepage&q=Grasbeck%2C%20Ralph%20imerslund&f=false ''Stedman's Medical Eponyms'']. Lippincott Williams & Wilkins (2005) p. 289. {{ISBN|0-7817-5443-7}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | author=Grasbeck R | title=Imerslund-Gr\u00e4sbeck syndrome (selective vitamin B12 malabsorption with proteinuria | journal=Orphanet Journal of Rare Diseases | doi=10.1186/1750-1172-1-17 | year=2006 | volume=1 | page=17 | pmid=16722557 |pmc=1513194}}</ref><ref>Wintrobe, Maxwell Myer. [https://books.google.com/books?id=eExrAAAAMAAJ&q=Grasbeck,+Ralph+imerslund&dq=Grasbeck,+Ralph+imerslund&hl=en&ei=rFPmTMC5NtSxhAeht7j_DA&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=4&ved=0CDIQ6AEwAw ''Hematology, the blossoming of a science'']. Lea & Febiger (1985) p. 227</ref>\n\nHe made numerous other observations on the vitamin B12 metabolism including studies on fish tapeworm anemia, the purification and isolation of intrinsic factor from gastric juice (1965) and the description of R-protein (today called haptocorrin).<ref>http://www.whonamedit.com/bibliography{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> He is also known for the introduction of the concept of reference values.<ref>{{cite journal|title=The evolution of the reference value concept|author=Gr\u00e4sbeck R|journal=[[Clinical Chemistry and Laboratory Medicine]]|year= 2004|volume=42|issue=7|pages=692\u2013697|doi=10.1515/cclm.2004.118}}</ref>\nHe graduated as an MD from Helsinki University in 1953 and subsequently trained in the 1950s in biochemistry at Johns Hopkins University in Baltimore and at Medical Nobel Institute, Karolinska Institute, Stockholm. His PhD (DMSci) dissertation was presented in 1956 and in 1959 he became docent at Helsinki University and the years 1960-1990 he was Chief Physician of the Laboratory Department of Maria Hospital, Helsinki.He was one of the founders of the Minerva Foundation Institute for Medical Research at the [[University of Helsinki]] and served as its director from 1971\u20131993.<ref>Minerva Foundation and Minerva Foundation Institute for Medical Research. [http://www.helsinki.fi/minerva/images/stories/english/documents/MINERVA_vuosikertomus.pdf 50th Anniversary 1959 -2009]. p. 25</ref> He became Professor in 1982. He has been board member and chairman of many Finnish, Scandinavian and International organizations and received numerous honors including Charter Member, Johns Hopkins Society of Scholars, the junior Jahre prize of Oslo University, the silver medal of the Finnish Society (Academy) of Sciences and Letters, and Doctor honoris causa of Poincar\u00e9 University, Nancy, France.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Grasbeck, Armas Ralph Gustaf}}\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:2016 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Helsinki]]\n[[Category:Finnish biochemists]]\n[[Category:University of Helsinki]]\n\n\n{{Biochemist-stub}}\n{{Finland-scientist-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Armas Ralph Gustaf Grasbeck''' (July 6, 1930, [[Helsinki]] \u2013 January 22, 2016),<ref>[https://laboratoriolaaketiede.yhdistysavain.fi/?x118281=200732 Professori Ralph Gr\u00e4sbeck in memoriam] {{in lang|fi}}</ref> best known as  Ralph Gr\u00e4sbeck, was a Finnish physician and clinical [[biochemist]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=wrzkAAAAMAAJ&q=Armas+Ralph+Gustaf+Gr%C3%A4sbeck&dq=Armas+Ralph+Gustaf+Gr%C3%A4sbeck&hl=en&ei=l07mTKKqJ8qXhQepqbn9DA&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CCoQ6AEwAA \"Gr\u00e4sbeck,  Ralph Gustaf Armas\"]. ''Who's Who in the World 2012. Who's Who, Berkeley Heights NJ 2012</ref> He was best known for his contribution to the identification and naming of the [[Imerslund-Gr\u00e4sbeck syndrome]].<ref>Bartolucci, Susan L. and Forbis, Pat (eds). [https://books.google.com/books?id=isqcnR6ryz0C&pg=PA289&dq=Grasbeck,+Ralph+imerslund&hl=en&ei=dlTmTJ3HEYjJhAeQueSNDQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CCUQ6AEwADgK#v=onepage&q=Grasbeck%2C%20Ralph%20imerslund&f=false ''Stedman's Medical Eponyms'']. Lippincott Williams & Wilkins (2005) p. 289. {{ISBN|0-7817-5443-7}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | author=Grasbeck R | title=Imerslund-Gr\u00e4sbeck syndrome (selective vitamin B12 malabsorption with proteinuria | journal=Orphanet Journal of Rare Diseases | doi=10.1186/1750-1172-1-17 | year=2006 | volume=1 | page=17 | pmid=16722557 |pmc=1513194}}</ref><ref>Wintrobe, Maxwell Myer. [https://books.google.com/books?id=eExrAAAAMAAJ&q=Grasbeck,+Ralph+imerslund&dq=Grasbeck,+Ralph+imerslund&hl=en&ei=rFPmTMC5NtSxhAeht7j_DA&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=4&ved=0CDIQ6AEwAw ''Hematology, the blossoming of a science'']. Lea & Febiger (1985) p. 227</ref>\n\nHe made numerous other observations on the vitamin B12 metabolism including studies on fish tapeworm anemia, the purification and isolation of intrinsic factor from gastric juice (1965) and the description of R-protein (today called haptocorrin).<ref>http://www.whonamedit.com/bibliography{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> He is also known for the introduction of the concept of reference values.<ref>{{cite journal|title=The evolution of the reference value concept|author=Gr\u00e4sbeck R|journal=[[Clinical Chemistry and Laboratory Medicine]]|year= 2004|volume=42|issue=7|pages=692\u2013697|doi=10.1515/cclm.2004.118}}</ref>\nHe graduated as an MD from Helsinki University in 1953 and subsequently trained in the 1950s in biochemistry at Johns Hopkins University in Baltimore and at Medical Nobel Institute, Karolinska Institute, Stockholm. His PhD (DMSci) dissertation was presented in 1956 and in 1959 he became docent at Helsinki University and the years 1960-1990 he was Chief Physician of the Laboratory Department of Maria Hospital, Helsinki.He was one of the founders of the Minerva Foundation Institute for Medical Research at the [[University of Helsinki]] and served as its director from 1971-1993.<ref>Minerva Foundation and Minerva Foundation Institute for Medical Research. [http://www.helsinki.fi/minerva/images/stories/english/documents/MINERVA_vuosikertomus.pdf 50th Anniversary 1959 -2009]. p. 25</ref> He became Professor in 1982. He has been board member and chairman of many Finnish, Scandinavian and International organizations and received numerous honors including Charter Member, Johns Hopkins Society of Scholars, the junior Jahre prize of Oslo University, the silver medal of the Finnish Society (Academy) of Sciences and Letters, and Doctor honoris causa of Poincar\u00e9 University, Nancy, France.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Grasbeck, Armas Ralph Gustaf}}\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:2016 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Helsinki]]\n[[Category:Finnish biochemists]]\n[[Category:University of Helsinki]]\n\n\n{{Biochemist-stub}}\n{{Finland-scientist-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Majavah", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: 1971-1993 \u2192 1971\u20131993", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Armas_Ralph_Gustaf_Gr%C3%A4sbeck"}
{"title_page": "Antibiotic use in livestock", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n'''Antibiotic use in livestock''' is the use of [[antibiotics]] for any purpose in the [[animal husbandry|husbandry]] of [[livestock]], which includes treatment when ill ([https://www.medicinenet.com/script/main/art.asp?articlekey=18811 therapeutic]), treatment of a group of animals when at least one is diagnosed with clinical infection (metaphylaxis<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=Bousquet-Melou|first=Alain|last2=Ferran|first2=Aude|last3=Toutain|first3=Pierre-Louis|date=May 2010|title=Prophylaxis & Metaphylaxis in Veterinary Antimicrobial Therapy|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/281440602|journal=Conference: 5TH International Conference on Antimicrobial Agents in Veterinary Medicine (AAVM)At: Tel Aviv, Israel|volume=|pages=|via=ResearchGate}}</ref>), and [[preventive healthcare|preventative treatment (prophylaxis)]]. Antibiotics are an important tool to treat animal as well as human disease, safeguard animal health and welfare, and support food safety.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.bva.co.uk/media/1161/bva-policy-position-on-the-responsible-use-of-antimicrobials-in-food-producing-animals-1.pdf|title= BVA policy position on the responsible use of antimicrobials in food producing animals|last=British Veterinary Association, London |date=May 2019|accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref> However, used irresponsibly, this may also have impacts on human, animal and environmental health in a [[One Health]] context, as up to 90% of the antibiotic parent compounds can be directly excreted and this can lead to antibiotic resistance developing in the environment.<ref name=\"Mass\u00e9 et al 2004\">{{cite journal |last1=Mass\u00e9 |first1=Daniel |last2=Saady |first2=Noori |last3=Gilbert |first3=Yan |title=Potential of Biological Processes to Eliminate Antibiotics in Livestock Manure: An Overview |journal=Animals |date=4 April 2014 |volume=4 |issue=2 |pages=146\u2013163 |doi=10.3390/ani4020146 |pmid=26480034 |pmc=4494381 |url=https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/fb5a763e94860b1eab74b3661cde875127196b76}}</ref><ref name=\"Sarmah et al 2006\">{{cite journal |last1=Sarmah |first1=Ajit K. |last2=Meyer |first2=Michael T. |last3=Boxall |first3=Alistair B. A. |title=A global perspective on the use, sales, exposure pathways, occurrence, fate and effects of veterinary antibiotics (VAs) in the environment |journal=Chemosphere |date=1 October 2006 |volume=65 |issue=5 |pages=725\u2013759 |doi=10.1016/j.chemosphere.2006.03.026 |pmid=16677683 |bibcode=2006Chmsp..65..725S}}</ref><ref name=\"Kumar et al 2005\">{{cite journal |last1=Kumar |first1=Kuldip |last2=C. Gupta |first2=Satish |last3=Chander |first3=Yogesh |last4=Singh |first4=Ashok K. |title=Antibiotic Use in Agriculture and Its Impact on the Terrestrial Environment |journal=Advances in Agronomy |date=1 January 2005 |volume=87 |pages=1\u201354 |doi=10.1016/S0065-2113(05)87001-4 |isbn=9780120007851}}</ref><ref name=\"VanBoeckel2017\">{{cite journal |last1=Boeckel |first1=Thomas P. Van |last2=Glennon |first2=Emma E. |last3=Chen |first3=Dora |last4=Gilbert |first4=Marius |last5=Robinson |first5=Timothy P. |last6=Grenfell |first6=Bryan T. |last7=Levin |first7=Simon A. |last8=Bonhoeffer |first8=Sebastian |last9=Laxminarayan |first9=Ramanan |title=Reducing antimicrobial use in food animals |journal=Science |date=29 September 2017 |volume=357 |issue=6358 |pages=1350\u20131352 |doi=10.1126/science.aao1495 |pmid=28963240 |pmc=6510296 |bibcode=2017Sci...357.1350V |url=https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/5c647b3baf054be90bb5a0fb4cef016b71748723}}</ref> [[File:Ar-infographic-950px.jpg|thumb|A [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]] infographic on the spread of antibiotic-resistant bacteria from farm animals]] While levels of use vary dramatically from country to country, for example some Northern European countries use very low quantities to treat animals compared with humans,<ref name=ESVACreport2019>{{cite web|url= https://www.ema.europa.eu/en/documents/report/sales-veterinary-antimicrobial-agents-31-european-countries-2017_en.pdf|title= Sales of veterinary antimicrobial agents in 31 European countries in 2017: Trends from 2010 to 2017 |last=ESVAC (European Medicines Agency) |date=October 2019|accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref> worldwide an estimated 73% of [[antimicrobial]]s (mainly antibiotics) are consumed by farm animals.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Boeckel|first=Thomas P. Van|last2=Pires|first2=Jo\u00e3o|last3=Silvester|first3=Reshma|last4=Zhao|first4=Cheng|last5=Song|first5=Julia|last6=Criscuolo|first6=Nicola G.|last7=Gilbert|first7=Marius|last8=Bonhoeffer|first8=Sebastian|last9=Laxminarayan|first9=Ramanan|date=20 September 2019|title=Global trends in antimicrobial resistance in animals in low- and middle-income countries|journal=Science|language=en|volume=365|issue=6459|pages=eaaw1944|doi=10.1126/science.aaw1944|issn=0036-8075|pmid=31604207|url=https://dipot.ulb.ac.be/dspace/bitstream/2013/296867/3/vanboeckel.pdf}}</ref> Furthermore, a 2015 study also estimates that global agricultural antibiotic usage will increase by 67% from 2010 to 2030, mainly from increases in use in developing [[BRIC]] countries.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/d04c/774cc6a90f9da0072f7fa81450373bc98bd4.pdf |title=Global trends in antimicrobial use in food animals}}</ref> This is a matter of concern as [[antibiotic resistance]] is considered to be a serious threat to human and animal welfare in the future, and growing levels of antibiotics or antibiotic-resistant bacteria in the environment could increase the numbers of drug-resistant infections in both.<ref name=pmid22048738>{{cite journal |last1=Bush |first1=Karen |last2=Courvalin |first2=Patrice |last3=Dantas |first3=Gautam |last4=Davies |first4=Julian |last5=Eisenstein |first5=Barry |last6=Huovinen |first6=Pentti |last7=Jacoby |first7=George A. |last8=Kishony |first8=Roy |last9=Kreiswirth |first9=Barry N. |last10=Kutter |first10=Elizabeth |last11=Lerner |first11=Stephen A. |last12=Levy |first12=Stuart |last13=Lewis |first13=Kim |last14=Lomovskaya |first14=Olga |last15=Miller |first15=Jeffrey H. |last16=Mobashery |first16=Shahriar |last17=Piddock |first17=Laura J. V. |last18=Projan |first18=Steven |last19=Thomas |first19=Christopher M. |last20=Tomasz |first20=Alexander |last21=Tulkens |first21=Paul M. |last22=Walsh |first22=Timothy R. |last23=Watson |first23=James D. |last24=Witkowski |first24=Jan |last25=Witte |first25=Wolfgang |last26=Wright |first26=Gerry |last27=Yeh |first27=Pamela |last28=Zgurskaya |first28=Helen I. |title=Tackling antibiotic resistance |journal=Nature Reviews Microbiology |date=2 November 2011 |volume=9 |issue=12 |pages=894\u2013896 |doi=10.1038/nrmicro2693 |pmid=22048738 |pmc=4206945 |url=https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/2a244a95db85ac10c1a67791ef1b8d5890574285}}</ref> Infectious diseases are the third leading cause of death in Europe and a future without effective antibiotics would fundamentally change the way modern human as well as veterinary medicine is practised.<ref name=pmid22048738/><ref name=\"Tang et al\">{{cite journal| last1=Tang |first1=Karen L |last2=Caffrey |first2=Niamh P |last3=N\u00f3brega |first3=Diego| last4=Cork |first4=Susan C |last5=Ronksley |first5=Paul C |last6=Barkema |first6=Herman W |last7=Polachek |first7=Alicia J |last8=Ganshorn |first8=Heather |last9=Sharma |first9=Nishan |last10=Kellner |first10=James D |last11=Ghali |first11=William A|title=Restricting the use of antibiotics in food-producing animals and its associations with antibiotic resistance in food-producing animals and human beings: a systematic review and meta-analysis|journal=The Lancet Planetary Health |date= November 2017|volume=1|issue=8|pages=e316\u2013e327|doi=10.1016/S2542-5196(17)30141-9|pmid=29387833 |pmc=5785333}}</ref><ref name=pmid25918440/> However, legislation and other curbs on antibiotic use in farm animals are now being introduced across the globe.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.ema.europa.eu/en/veterinary-regulatory/overview/implementation-new-veterinary-medicines-regulation|title= Implementation of the new Veterinary Medicines Regulation in the EU|last=European Medicines Agency}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.oecd.org/officialdocuments/publicdisplaydocumentpdf/?cote=TAD/CA/APM/WP(2018)19/FINAL&docLanguage=En|title= Working Party on Agricultural Policies and Markets: Antibiotic Use and Antibiotic Resistance in Food Producing Animals in China|last=OECD, Paris|date=May 2019| accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.fda.gov/animal-veterinary/antimicrobial-resistance/timeline-fda-action-antimicrobial-resistance|title= Timeline of FDA Action on Antimicrobial Resistance|last=US Food & Drug Administration |date=July 2019| accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref> In 2017, the [[World Health Organization]] strongly suggested reducing antibiotic use in animals used in the food industry.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web|url=https://apps.who.int/iris/bitstream/handle/10665/258970/9789241550130-eng.pdf?sequence=1 |title=WHO guidelines on use of medically important antimicrobials in food-producing animals}}</ref> The use of antibiotics for growth promotion purposes was banned in the European Union from 2006,<ref name=\":7\">{{cite web |url=https://ec.europa.eu/commission/presscorner/detail/en/IP_05_1687 |title=Ban on antibiotics as growth promoters in animal feed enters into effect|last=European Commission, Brussels |date=December 2005}}</ref> and the use of sub-therapeutic doses of medically important antibiotics in [[animal feed]] and water<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{Cite journal|url=https://www.fda.gov/downloads/AnimalVeterinary/GuidanceComplianceEnforcement/GuidanceforIndustry/UCM216936.pdf|title=The Judicious Use of Medically Important Antimicrobial Drugs in Food-Producing Animals|last=|first=|date=2012|journal=Guidance for Industry|pages=|via=|issue=#209}}</ref> to promote growth and improve [[feed conversion ratio|feed efficiency]] became illegal in the United States on 1 January 2017, through legislative change enacted by the Food and Drug Administration (FDA), which sought voluntary compliance from drug manufacturers to re-label their antibiotics.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.avma.org/KB/Resources/Pages/VFD123.aspx|title=Veterinary Feed Directive (VFD) Basics|website=AVMA|accessdate=14 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170415174849/https://www.avma.org/KB/Resources/Pages/VFD123.aspx|archive-date=15 April 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://beef.unl.edu/veterinary-feed-directive-questions-and-answers|title=Veterinary Feed Directive Questions and Answers|last=University of Nebraska, Lincoln|date=October 2015|website=UNL Beef|accessdate=14 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe 2018 book 'Pharming animals: a global history of antibiotics in food production (1935\u20132017)'<ref name=\"Kirchhelle C\">{{cite journal| last1=Kirchelle |first1=Claas|title= Pharming animals: a global history of antibiotics in food production (1935\u20132017) |journal= Palgrave Communications |date= 7 August 2018|volume=4|issue= |doi= 10.1057/s41599-018-0152-2}}</ref> summarises the central role antibiotics have played in agriculture: \"Since their advent during the 1930s, antibiotics have not only had a dramatic impact on human medicine, but also on food production. On farms, whaling and fishing fleets as well as in processing plants and aquaculture operations, antibiotics were used to treat and prevent disease, increase feed conversion, and preserve food. Their rapid diffusion into nearly all areas of food production and processing was initially viewed as a story of progress on both sides of the Iron Curtain.\"\n\nTo retrace, while natural antibiotics or antibacterials were known to ancient man, [[antibiotic]]<nowiki/>s as we know them came to the fore during World War II to help treat war time casualties. It is recorded that antibiotics were first used in farming towards the end of the war, in the form of intra-mammary penicillin preparations to treat bovine mastitis.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite journal|last=Gustafson|first=R. H.|last2=Bowen|first2=R. E.|date=1997|title=Antibiotic use in animal agriculture|journal=Journal of Applied Microbiology|language=en|volume=83|issue=5|pages=531\u2013541|doi=10.1046/j.1365-2672.1997.00280.x|pmid=9418018|issn=1365-2672}}</ref> At that time, milk was seen as an agricultural product which was highly susceptible to bacterial contamination, and farmers welcomed the opportunity to 'purify' their produce for the safety of consumers; it was only later that concern switched from the bacterial load of the product to the residues that might result from untimely or unregulated treatment.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=SMITH-HOWARD|first=KENDRA|date=2010|title=Antibiotics and Agricultural Change: Purifying Milk and Protecting Health in the Postwar Era|journal=Agricultural History|volume=84|issue=3|pages=327\u2013351|doi=10.3098/ah.2010.84.3.327|jstor=27868996|issn=0002-1482}}</ref>\n\nThe use of antibiotics to treat and prevent disease has followed a similar path to that used in human medicine in terms of [https://www.medicinenet.com/script/main/art.asp?articlekey=18811 therapeutic] and metaphylactic<ref name=\":4\" /> applications to treat and manage disease and improve population health, and the application of case-by-case strategic preventative treatments when animals are deemed at particular risk. However, in the late 1940s, studies examining the supplementation of B12 in chicks' diets found that B12 produced from the fermentation of ''Streptomyces aureofaciens'', an antibiotic for use in human medicine, produced a better weight gain for chicks than B12 supplied from other sources, and a reduced amount of feed to bring the birds to market weight.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stokstad|first=ELR|last2=Jukes|first2=TH|last3=Pierce|first3=J|last4=Page|first4=AC Jnr|last5=Franklin|first5=AL|date=1949|title=The multiple nature of the animal protein factor|url=https://www.cabdirect.org/cabdirect/abstract/19491403454|journal=Journal of Biological Chemistry|volume=180|pages=647\u2013654|pmid=18135798|via=CAB Direct}}</ref> Further studies on other livestock species showed a similar improved growth and feed efficiency effect with the result that as the cost of antibiotics came down, they were increasingly included at low ('[https://www.collinsdictionary.com/dictionary/english/subtherapeutic sub-therapeutic')] levels in livestock feed as a means of increasing production of affordable animal protein to meet the needs of a rapidly-expanding post-war population.<ref name=\":8\" /> This development coincided with an increase in the scale of individual farms and the level of confinement of the animals on them, and so routine preventative antibiotic treatments became the most cost-effective means of treating the anticipated disease that could sometimes arise as a result.<ref name=\":8\" /> Veterinary medicine increasingly embraced the therapeutic, metaphylactic and strategic preventative use of antibiotics to treat disease. The routine use of antibiotics for growth stimulation and disease prevention also grew.\n\n==Growth stimulation==\nIn 1910 in the United States, a meat shortage resulted in protests and boycotts.<ref name=\"Ogle2013\">{{cite web|url=http://blogs.scientificamerican.com/guest-blog/2013/09/03/riots-rage-and-resistance-a-brief-history-of-how-antibiotics-arrived-on-the-farm/|title=Riots, Rage and Resistance: A Brief History of How Antibiotics Arrived on the Farm|last=Ogle|first=Maureen|date=3 September 2013|work=[[Scientific American]]|accessdate=5 November 2013}}\n</ref><ref>Reported locally in these:\n*\"To Become Vegetarians\", Mansfield (O.) ''News'', 17 January 1910, p2\n*\"150,000 at Cleveland Stop the Use of Meat\" Syracuse ''Herald-Journal'', 25 January 1910, p1\n*\"Boycott on Meat is Rapidly Spreading; Men Who Are Blamed For High Price\", Atlanta ''Constitution'', 25 January 1910, p1</ref> After this and other shortages, the public demanded government research into stabilization of food supplies.<ref name=\"Ogle2013\"/> Since the 1900s, livestock production on United States farms has had to rear larger quantities of animals over a short period of time to meet new consumer demands. It was discovered in the 1940s that feeding subtherapeutic levels of antibiotics improved feed efficiency and accelerated animal growth.<ref>{{cite book |doi=10.1109/CONIIN.2018.8489822 |chapter=A review of hot and sweet pepper added in animal nutrition: Alternative against the use of antibiotics |title=2018 XIV International Engineering Congress (CONIIN) |pages=1\u20136 |year=2018 |last1=Flores-Tejeida |first1=L.B |last2=Soto-Zarazua |first2=G.M |last3=Guevara-Gonzalez |first3=R.G |last4=Escamilla-Garcia |first4=A. |last5=Gomez-Soto |first5=J.G |isbn=978-1-5386-7018-7}}</ref> Following this discovery, [[American Cyanamid]] published research establishing the practice of using antibiotic growth promoters.<ref name=\"Ogle2013\"/> By 2001, this practice had grown so much that a report by the [[Union of Concerned Scientists]] found that nearly 90% of the total use of antimicrobials in the United States was for non-therapeutic purposes in agricultural production.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hogging It!: Estimates of Antimicrobial Abuse in Livestock |year=2001|publisher=Union of Concerned Scientists|url=https://www.ucsusa.org/food_and_agriculture/our-failing-food-system/industrial-agriculture/hogging-it-estimates-of.html#.Wycey1MvzEY}}</ref>\nCertain antibiotics, when given in low, subtherapeutic doses, are known to improve [[feed conversion efficiency]] (more output, such as muscle or milk, for a given amount of feed) and may promote greater growth, most likely by affecting [[gut flora]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.merckvetmanual.com/pharmacology/growth-promotants-and-production-enhancers/antimicrobial-feed-additives|title=Antimicrobial Feed Additives|last=Reinhardt|first=Christopher|work=Merck Veterinary Manual}}</ref> The drugs listed below can be used to increase feed conversion ratio and weight gain, but are not legally allowed to be used for such purposes any longer in the United States. Some drugs listed below are [[ionophore]]s, which are [[coccidiostat]]s and not classified as antibiotics in many countries; they have not been shown to increase risk of antibiotic-resistant infections in humans.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"5\" style=\"background-color: #CCEEEE;\" | Antibiotic Growth Promoters historically used in Livestock Production in some countries\n|-\n! Drug\n! Class\n! Livestock\n|-\n|[[Bacitracin]]\n|[[Peptide]]\n| Beef cattle, chickens, swine, and turkeys; promotes egg production in chickens<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"MerckReinhardt\"/>\n|-\n|[[Bambermycin]]\n|\n|Beef cattle, chickens, swine, and turkeys.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|title = Altered egos: antibiotic effects on food animal microbiomes|journal = Annual Review of Microbiology|date = 1 January 2014|issn = 1545-3251|pmid = 25002091|pages = 297\u2013315|volume = 68|doi = 10.1146/annurev-micro-091213-113052|first = Heather K.|last = Allen|first2 = Thad B.|last2 = Stanton|url = https://zenodo.org/record/1235023}}</ref><ref name=\"MerckReinhardt\">{{Citation |last=Reinhardt |first=Christopher D. |year=2012 |title=Merck Veterinary Manual | chapter=Antimicrobial Feed Additives | chapter-url=http://www.merckmanuals.com/vet/pharmacology/growth_promotants_and_production_enhancers/antimicrobial_feed_additives.html |publisher=[[Merck & Co.]] and [[Merial]] |location= | editor1-last=Aiello | editor1-first =Susan E.| editor2-last=Moses | editor2-first =Michael A. |page= |title-link=Merck Veterinary Manual}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Carbadox]]\n|\n|Swine<ref name=\":0\" />\n|-\n|[[Laidlomycin]]\n|\n|Beef cattle<ref name=\":0\" />\n|-\n|[[Lasalocid]]\n|[[Ionophore]]\n|Beef cattle<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"MerckReinhardt\"/>\n|-\n|[[Lincomycin]]\n|\n|Chickens and swine<ref name=\":0\" />\n|-\n|[[Monensin]]\n|Ionophore\n|Beef cattle and sheep; promotes milk production in dairy cows<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"MerckReinhardt\"/>\n|-\n|[[Neomycin]]/ Oxytetracycline\n|\n|Beef cattle, chickens, swine, and turkeys<ref name=\":0\" />\n|-\n|[[Penicillin]]\n|\n|Chickens, swine, and turkeys<ref name=\":0\" />\n|-\n|[[Roxarsone]]\n|\n|Chickens and turkeys<ref name=\":0\" />\n|-\n|[[Salinomycin]]\n|Ionophore\n|\n|-\n|[[Tylosin]]\n|\n|Chickens and swine<ref name=\":0\" />\n|-\n|[[Virginiamycin]]\n|Peptide\n|Beef cattle, chickens, swine, turkeys<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"MerckReinhardt\"/>\n|}\nThe practice of using antibiotics for growth stimulation has been deemed problematic for these following reasons:<ref name=\"Silbergeld\">{{Cite journal|last1=Silbergeld|first1=E. K.|last2=Graham|first2=J.|last3=Price|first3=L. B.|year=2008|title=Industrial Food Animal Production, Antimicrobial Resistance, and Human Health|url=|journal=Annual Review of Public Health|volume=29|pages=151\u2013169|doi=10.1146/annurev.publhealth.29.020907.090904|pmc=|pmid=18348709|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\n*It is the largest use of antimicrobials worldwide\n*Subtherapeutic use of antibiotics results in bacterial resistance\n*Every important class of antibiotics are being used in this way, making every class less effective\n*The bacteria being changed harm humans\n\n==Antibiotic resistance==\n\n=== Mechanisms for the development of resistance ===\nAntibiotic resistance - often referred to as [[antimicrobial resistance]] (AMR) although this term covers anti-virals, anti-fungals and other products - can occur when antibiotics are present in concentrations too low to inhibit bacterial growth, triggering cellular responses in the bacteria that allow them to survive. These bacteria can then reproduce and spread their antibiotic-resistant genes to other generations, increasing their prevalence and leading to infections that cannot be healed by antibiotics.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ben|first=Yujie|last2=Fu|first2=Caixia|last3=Hu|first3=Min|last4=Liu|first4=Lei|last5=Wong|first5=Ming Hung|last6=Zheng|first6=Chunmiao|date=February 2019|title=Human health risk assessment of antibiotic resistance associated with antibiotic residues in the environment: A review|journal=Environmental Research|volume=169|pages=483\u2013493|doi=10.1016/j.envres.2018.11.040|issn=1096-0953|pmid=30530088|bibcode=2019ER....169..483B|url=https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/c46b56253afd303cb0f561aedb3113573cd129e5}}</ref> This is a growing matter of concern as antibiotic resistance is considered to be a serious future threat to human welfare.<ref name=pmid22048738/> Infectious diseases are the third leading cause of death in Europe and a future without effective antibiotics would fundamentally change the way modern medicine is practised.<ref name=pmid22048738/><ref name=pmid25918440>{{cite journal |last1=Shallcross |first1=Laura J. |last2=Howard |first2=Simon J. |last3=Fowler |first3=Tom |last4=Davies |first4=Sally C. |title=Tackling the threat of antimicrobial resistance: from policy to sustainable action |journal=Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society B: Biological Sciences |date=5 June 2015 |volume=370 |issue=1670 |pages=20140082 |doi=10.1098/rstb.2014.0082 |pmid=25918440 |pmc=4424432 |url=https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/89772d0ac83159bdc04737d8b8db9cc099b2b4f9}}</ref> \n[[File:Hartsock Genetic Engineering Bacteria Cell Division.png|thumb|Bacterial conjugation|333x333px]]\nBacteria can alter their genetic inheritance through two main ways, either by mutating their genetic material or acquiring a new one from other bacteria. The latter being the most important for causing antibiotic-resistant bacteria strains in animals and humans. One of the methods bacteria can obtain new genes is through a process called conjugation which deals with transferring genes using plasmids. These conjugative plasmids carry a number of genes that can be assembled and rearranged, which could then enable bacteria to exchange beneficial genes among themselves ensuring their survival against antibiotics and rendering them ineffective to treat dangerous diseases in humans, resulting into multi-drug resistant organisms.<ref>Bennett P. M. (2008). Plasmid encoded antibiotic resistance: acquisition and transfer of antibiotic resistance genes in bacteria. British journal of pharmacology, 153 Suppl 1(Suppl 1), S347-57.</ref>\n\nHowever, it is important to note that antibiotic resistance also occurs naturally, as it is a bacterium's response to any threat. As a result, antibiotic-resistant bacteria have been found in pristine environments unrelated to human activity such as in the frozen and uncovered remains of woolly mammoths,<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Perry |first1=Julie |last2=Waglechner |first2=Nicholas |last3=Wright |first3=Gerard |title=The Prehistory of Antibiotic Resistance |journal=Cold Springs Harbor Perspectives in Medicine |date=June 2016 |volume=6 |issue=6 |page=a025197 |doi=10.1101/cshperspect.a025197 |pmid=27252395 |pmc=4888810}}</ref> in the polar ice caps<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Nesme |first1=Joseph |last2=Cecillon |first2=Sebastien |last3=Delmont |first3=Tom |last4=Monier |first4=Jean-Michel |last5=Vogel |first5=Timothy |last6=Simonet |first6=Pascal |title=Large-Scale Metagenomic-Based Study of Antibiotic Resistance in the Environment |journal=Current Biology |date=May 2014 |volume=24 |issue=10 |pages=1096\u2013100 |doi=10.1016/j.cub.2014.03.036 |pmid=24814145}}</ref> and in isolated caves deep underground.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Bhullar |first1=K |last2=Waglechner |first2=N |last3=Pawlowski |first3=A |last4=Koteva |first4=K |last5=Banks |first5=ED |last6=Johnston |first6=MD |last7=Barton |first7=HA |last8=Wright |first8=GD |title=Antibiotic resistance is prevalent in an isolated cave microbiome |journal=PLOS One |date=2012 |volume=7 |issue=4 |page=e34953 |doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0034953 |pmid=22509370 |pmc=3324550 |bibcode=2012PLoSO...734953B}}</ref>\n\n=== High priority antibiotics ===\nThe [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) published a revised list in 2019 of 'Critically Important Antimicrobials for Human Medicine, 6th revision'<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apps.who.int/iris/bitstream/handle/10665/312266/9789241515528-eng.pdf?ua=1|title=Critically Important Antimicrobials for Human Medicine, 6th Revision|last=World Health Organization|date=2018|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref> with the intent that it be used \"as a reference to help formulate and prioritise risk assessment and risk management strategies for containing antimicrobial resistance due to human and non-human antimicrobial use to help preserve the effectiveness of currently available antimicrobials. It lists its Highest Priority Critically Important Antimicrobials as: 3rd, 4th and 5th generation cephalosporins, glycopeptides, macrolides and ketolides, polymyxins including colistin, and quinolones including fluoroqinolones.\n\nThe [[European Medicines Agency]] (EMA) Antimicrobial Advice Ad-Hoc Expert Group (AMEG) also published an updated categorisation<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ema.europa.eu/en/veterinary-regulatory/overview/antimicrobial-resistance/advice-impacts-using-antimicrobials-animals|title=Advice on impacts of using antimicrobials in animals|last=European Medicines Agency|date=January 2020|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref> of different antibiotics in veterinary medicine by the antibiotic resistance risk to humans of using them alongside the need to treat disease in animals for health and welfare reasons. The categorisation specifically focuses on the situation in Europe. Category A (\u2018Avoid\u2019) antibiotics are designated as \u2018not appropriate for use in food producing animals\u2019. Category B (\u2018Restrict\u2019) products, also known as Highest Priority Critically Important Antibiotics, are only to be used as a last resort. These include quinolones (such as fluoroquinolones), 3rd and 4th generation cephalosporins, and polymyxins, including colistin. A new intermediate Category C (\u2018Caution\u2019) has been created for antibiotics which should be used when there is no available product in Category D (\u2018Prudence\u2019) that would be clinically effective. Category C includes macrolides and aminoglycosides, with the exception of spectinomycin, which remains in Category D.\n\nEvidence for the transfer of [[macrolide]]-resistant microorganisms from animals to humans has been scant,<ref name=\"pmid15151237\">{{cite journal|last1=Hurd|first1=H. Scott|last2=Doores|first2=Stephanie|last3=Hayes|first3=Dermot|last4=Mathew|first4=Alan|last5=Maurer|first5=John|last6=Silley|first6=Peter|last7=Singer|first7=Randall S.|last8=Jones|first8=Ronald N.|date=1 May 2004|title=Public Health Consequences of Macrolide Use in Food Animals: A Deterministic Risk Assessment|journal=Journal of Food Protection|volume=67|issue=5|pages=980\u2013992|doi=10.4315/0362-028X-67.5.980|issn=0362-028X|pmid=15151237}}</ref><ref name=\"pmid18643826\">{{cite journal|last1=Hurd|first1=H. Scott|last2=Malladi|first2=Sasidhar|date=June 2008|title=A stochastic assessment of the public health risks of the use of macrolide antibiotics in food animals|url=https://www.sandersonfarms.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/PDF-5-Hurd_et_al-2008-Risk_Analysis.pdf|journal=Risk Analysis|volume=28|issue=3|pages=695\u2013710|doi=10.1111/j.1539-6924.2008.01054.x|issn=1539-6924|pmid=18643826|ref=harv}}</ref> and most evidence shows that pathogens of concern in human populations originated in humans and are maintained there, with rare cases of transference to humans. Macrolides are also extremely useful in the effective treatment of some ''Mycoplasma'' species in poultry, ''Lawsonia'' in pigs, respiratory tract infections in cattle and in some circumstances, lameness in sheep.<ref name=\":11\" />\n\n=== Sources of antibiotic resistance ===\n\n==== Summary ====\nWhile the human medical use of antibiotics is the main source of antibiotic resistant infections in humans,<ref>{{cite web |last1=UK Government |title=UK 5 Year Antimicrobial Resistance Strategy 2013 |date=10 September 2013 |page=Paragraph 2.1 |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/uk-5-year-antimicrobial-resistance-strategy-2013-to-2018 |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=The European Medicines Agency Committee for Medicinal Products for Veterinary Use |title=CVMP Strategy on Antimicrobials 2016-2020 |date=6 October 2016 |page=Page 4 |url=https://www.ema.europa.eu/en/documents/scientific-guideline/cvmp-strategy-antimicrobials-2016-2020_en.pdf |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Shea K.M. 2003\">{{cite journal|last=Shea|first=Katherine M.|date=1 July 2003|title=Antibiotic Resistance: What Is the Impact of Agricultural Uses of Antibiotics on Children's Health?|url=http://pediatrics.aappublications.org/content/112/Supplement_1/253|journal=Pediatrics|volume=112|issue=Supplement 1|pages=253\u2013258|issn=0031-4005|pmid=12837918|via=|doi-access=}}</ref> it is known that humans can acquire antibiotic resistance genes from a variety of animal sources, including farm animals, pets and wildlife.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Graham |first1=David W |last2=Bergeron |first2=Gilles |last3=Bourassa |first3=Megan W |last4=Dickson |first4=James |last5=Gomes |first5=Filomena |last6=Howe |first6=Adina |last7=Kahn |first7=Laura H |last8=Morley |first8=Paul S |last9=Scott |first9=H Morgan |last10=Simjee |first10=Shabbir |last11=Singer |first11=Randall S |last12=Smith |first12=Tara C |last13=Storrs |first13=Carina |last14=Wittum |first14=Thomas E |title=Complexities in understanding antimicrobial resistance across domesticated animal, human, and environmental systems |journal=Annals of the New York Academy of Sciences |date=April 2019 |volume=1441 |issue=1 |pages=17\u201330 |doi=10.1111/nyas.14036 |pmid=30924539 |pmc=6850694 |bibcode=2019NYASA1441...17G}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Marshall|first1=Bonnie M|last2=Levy|first2=Stuart B|date=October 2011|title=Food Animals and Antimicrobials: Impacts on Human Health|journal=Clinical Microbiology Reviews|volume=24|issue=4|pages=718\u2013733|doi=10.1128/CMR.00002-11|pmc=3194830|pmid=21976606}}</ref><ref name=\":32\">{{Cite journal|last=Economou|first=Vangelis|last2=Gousia|first2=Panagiota|date=1 April 2015|title=Agriculture and food animals as a source of antimicrobial-resistant bacteria|url=https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/791ac5a1f47bf034b4971bd5014b3e17312d0355|journal=Infection and Drug Resistance|volume=8|pages=49\u201361|doi=10.2147/IDR.S55778|issn=1178-6973|pmc=4388096|pmid=25878509}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Swartz|first=Morton N.|date=1 June 2002|title=Human Diseases Caused by Foodborne Pathogens of Animal Origin|journal=Clinical Infectious Diseases|volume=34|issue=Supplement_3|pages=S111\u2013S122|doi=10.1086/340248|issn=1058-4838|pmid=11988881|ref=harv|doi-access=free}}</ref> Three potential mechanisms by which agricultural antibiotic use could lead to human disease have been identified as: 1 - direct infection with resistant bacteria from an animal source; 2 - breaches in the species barrier followed by sustained transmission in humans of resistant strains arising in livestock; 3 - transfer of resistance genes from agriculture into human pathogens.<ref name=\":10\">{{cite journal|last1=Chang|first1=Qiuzhi|last2=Wang|first2=Weike|last3=Regev-Yochay|first3=Gili|last4=Lipsitch|first4=Marc|last5=Hanage|first5=William P.|date=March 2015|title=Antibiotics in agriculture and the risk to human health: how worried should we be?|url=https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/341d7f7cd9948ade51820a9ba30167190555e8df|journal=Evolutionary Applications|volume=8|issue=3|pages=240\u2013247|doi=10.1111/eva.12185|pmc=4380918|pmid=25861382|ref=harv}}</ref> While there is evidence of transmission of resistance from animals to humans in all three cases, either the scale is limited or causality is hard to establish. As Chang ''et al'' (2014)<ref name=\":10\" /> state: \"The topic of agricultural antibiotic use is complex. As we noted ...many believe that agricultural antibiotics have become a critical threat to human health. While the concern is not unwarranted, the extent of the problem may be exaggerated. There is no evidence that agriculture is \u2018largely to blame\u2019 for the increase in resistant strains and we should not be distracted from finding adequate ways to ensure appropriate antibiotic use in all settings, the most important of which being clinical medicine.\"\n\n==== Direct contact with animals ====\nIn terms of direct infection with resistant bacteria from an animals source, studies have shown that direct contact with livestock can lead to the spread of antibiotic-resistant bacteria. The risk appears greatest in those handling or managing livestock, for example in a study where resistant bacteria were monitored in farm labourers and neighbours after chickens receiving an antibiotic in their feed.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Levy |first1=SB |last2=FitxGerald |first2=GB |last3=Macone |first3=AB |title=Changes in intestinal flora of farm personnel after introduction of a tetracycline-supplemented feed on a farm |journal=New England Journal of Medicine |date=September 1976 |volume=295 |issue=11 |pages=583\u20138 |doi=10.1056/NEJM197609092951103 |pmid=950974}}</ref> Manure may also be contain antibiotic-resistant ''Staphylococcus aureus'' bacteria which can infect humans.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Zhang|first=Sarah|year=2013|title=Pig-manure fertilizer linked to human MRSA infections|journal=Nature News|doi=10.1038/nature.2013.13752|ref=harv|doi-access=free}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Casey|first1=Joan A.|last2=Curriero|first2=Frank C.|last3=Cosgrove|first3=Sara E.|last4=Nachman|first4=Keeve E.|last5=Schwartz|first5=Brian S.|date=25 November 2013|title=High-Density Livestock Operations, Crop Field Application of Manure, and Risk of Community-Associated Methicillin-Resistant Staphylococcus aureus Infection in Pennsylvania|journal=JAMA Internal Medicine|volume=173|issue=21|pages=1980\u201390|doi=10.1001/jamainternmed.2013.10408|pmc=4372690|pmid=24043228}}</ref> In 2017, the [[WHO]] included methicillin-resistant ''S. aureus'' (MRSA) in its priority list of 12 antibiotic-resistant bacteria, urging the need to search for new and more effective antibiotics against it. There also has been an increase in the number of bacterial pathogens resistant to multiple antimicrobial agents, including MRSA, which have recently emerged into different lineages. Some of them are associated with livestock and companion animals that are then able to be transmitted to humans, also called livestock-associated methicillin-resistant ''Staphylococcus aureus'' (LA-MRSA). These new lineages can be found on soft tissues of livestock workers, for example in their noses. A study looked at the association between exposure to livestock and the occurrence of LA-MRSA infection and observed that LA-MRSA infection was 9.64 times as likely to be found among livestock workers and veterinarians compared to their unexposed families and community members, showing that exposure to livestock significantly increases the risk of developing methicillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus (MRSA) infection.<ref>Chen, C., & Wu, F. (2018). Livestock-Associated Methicillin-Resistant Staphylococcus Aureus (LA-MRSA) Colonization and Infection Among Livestock Workers and Veterinarians: A Systematic Review and Meta-Analysis. Available at SSRN 3208968.</ref><ref>{{cite journal | author1 = Nadimpalli M. | author2 =Rinsky J. L. | author3 =Wing S. | author4 =Hall D. | author5 =Stewart J. | author6 =Larsen J. | author7 =Strelitz J. | year = 2015 | title = Persistence of livestock-associated antibiotic-resistant Staphylococcus aureus among industrial hog operation workers in North Carolina over 14 days | url = https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/c17bce5f715ae79bf241be768f7ed1c877c1a963| journal = Occup Environ Med | volume = 72 | issue = 2| pages = 90\u201399 | doi=10.1136/oemed-2014-102095| pmid = 25200855 | pmc = 4316926}}</ref> While total numbers colonised by LA-MRSA remain low, and fewer still suffer infection,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Anjum|first=Muna F.|last2=Marco-Jimenez|first2=Francisco|last3=Duncan|first3=Daisy|last4=Mar\u00edn|first4=Clara|last5=Smith|first5=Richard P.|last6=Evans|first6=Sarah J.|date=2019-09-12|title=Livestock-Associated Methicillin-Resistant Staphylococcus aureus From Animals and Animal Products in the UK|journal=Frontiers in Microbiology|volume=10|pages=2136|doi=10.3389/fmicb.2019.02136|issn=1664-302X|pmc=6751287|pmid=31572341}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/4fca/b9277652e3d8cc34a8150b31de865a838e67.pdf|title=Risk Assessment on Methicillin-Resistant Staphylococcus aureus (MRSA), with a focus on Livestock-associated MRSA, in the UK Food Chain|last=Food Standards Agency|date=February 2017|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref> the condition is nonetheless rising in prevalence, difficult to treat, and has become a public health concern.<ref>Livestock-associated Staphylococcus Aureus (LA-MRSA), Research topic. Retrieved from: https://www.frontiersin.org/research-topics/6689/livestock-associated-staphylococcus-aureus-la-mrsa</ref>\n\n==== Foodborne antibiotic resistance ====\nAnother way humans can be exposed to antibiotic-resistant bacteria is by pathogens on food.<ref name=\"cdc.gov\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/drugresistance/pdf/ar-threats-2013-508.pdf|title=Antibiotic Resistance Threats in the United States|publisher=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|accessdate=30 December 2016}}</ref> In particular, If resistant bacteria are ingested by humans via food and then colonise the gut, they can cause infections which are unpleasant enough in themselves, but can be even harder to treat if they are serious enough to require antibiotic treatment but are also resistant to commonly-used antibiotics.<ref name=\":32\" /><ref>{{cite journal|author=Bortolaia V|displayauthors=etal|date=Feb 2016|title=Human health risks associated with antimicrobial-resistant enterococci and Staphylococcus aureus on poultry meat|url=|journal=Clinical Microbiology and Infection|volume=22|issue=2|pages=130\u201340|doi=10.1016/j.cmi.2015.12.003|pmid=26706616|doi-access=free}}</ref>''[[Campylobacter]]'', ''[[Salmonella]],'' ''[[Escherichia coli|E. coli]]'' and ''[[Listeria]]'' species are the most common foodborne bacteria.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.foodauthority.nsw.gov.au/consumer/food-poisoning/foodborne-illness-pathogens|title=Foodborne illness pathogens|last=New South Wales Government|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> ''Salmonella'' and ''Campylobacter'' alone account for over 400,000 Americans becoming sick from antibiotic-resistant infections every year.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/drugresistance/food.html|title=Antibiotic Resistance and Food are Connected|last=CDC|date=10 September 2018|website=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|language=en-us|accessdate=29 March 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"NARMS 2013\">{{Cite report|url=https://www.cdc.gov/narms/pdf/2013-annual-report-narms-508c.pdf|title=Human Isolates Final Report|last=Center for Disease Control and Prevention|first=|date=2013|issue=|doi=|volume=|pmid=|accessdate=|work=National Antibiotic Resistance Monitoring System: Enteric Bacteria}}</ref> Dairy products, ground minced beef and poultry are among the most common foods that can harbour pathogens both resistant and susceptible to antibiotics,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cspinet.org/sites/default/files/attachment/outbreaks_antibiotic_resistance_in_foodborne_pathogens_2013.pdf|title=Antibiotic Resistance in Foodborne Pathogens|last1=DeWaal|first1=J.D.|last2=Grooters|first2=Susan Vaughn|date=May 2013|work=Center for Science in the Public Interest}}</ref> and surveillance of retail meats such as turkey, chicken, pork and beef have found Enterobacteriaceae. While some studies have established connections between antibiotic resistant infections and food-producing animals,<ref name=\"Molbak K 2005\">{{cite journal|last1=Angulo|first1=F. J.|last2=Molbak|first2=K.|date=1 December 2005|title=Human Health Consequences of Antimicrobial Drug--Resistant Salmonella and Other Foodborne Pathogens|journal=Clinical Infectious Diseases|volume=41|issue=11|pages=1613\u20131620|doi=10.1086/497599|pmid=16267734|ref=harv}}</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceB\">{{cite journal|last1=M\u00f8lbak|first1=K\u00e5re|last2=Baggesen|first2=Dorte Lau|last3=Aarestrup|first3=Frank M\u00f8ller|last4=Ebbesen|first4=Jens Munk|last5=Engberg|first5=J\u00f8rgen|last6=Frydendahl|first6=Kai|last7=Gerner-Smidt|first7=Peter|last8=Petersen|first8=Andreas Munk|last9=Wegener|first9=Henrik C.|date=4 November 1999|title=An Outbreak of Multidrug-Resistant, Quinolone-Resistant Salmonella enterica Serotype Typhimurium DT104|journal=New England Journal of Medicine|volume=341|issue=19|pages=1420\u20131425|doi=10.1056/NEJM199911043411902|pmid=10547404|doi-access=free}}</ref> others have struggled to establish causal links, even when examining plasmid-mediated resistance.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=McCrackin|first=M.A.|last2=Helke|first2=Kristi L.|last3=Galloway|first3=Ashley M.|last4=Poole|first4=Ann Z.|last5=Salgado|first5=Cassandra D.|last6=Marriott|first6=Bernadette p.|date=2016-10-02|title=Effect of Antimicrobial Use in Agricultural Animals on Drug-resistant Foodborne Campylobacteriosis in Humans: A Systematic Literature Review|journal=Critical Reviews in Food Science and Nutrition|language=en|volume=56|issue=13|pages=2115\u20132132|doi=10.1080/10408398.2015.1119798|pmid=26580432|issn=1040-8398}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mather|first=A. E.|last2=Reid|first2=S. W. J.|last3=Maskell|first3=D. J.|last4=Parkhill|first4=J.|last5=Fookes|first5=M. C.|last6=Harris|first6=S. R.|last7=Brown|first7=D. J.|last8=Coia|first8=J. E.|last9=Mulvey|first9=M. R.|last10=Gilmour|first10=M. W.|last11=Petrovska|first11=L.|date=2013-09-27|title=Distinguishable Epidemics of Multidrug-Resistant Salmonella Typhimurium DT104 in Different Hosts|journal=Science|language=en|volume=341|issue=6153|pages=1514\u20131517|doi=10.1126/science.1240578|issn=0036-8075|pmc=4012302|pmid=24030491|bibcode=2013Sci...341.1514M}}</ref><ref name=\":12\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Zaheer|first=Rahat|last2=Cook|first2=Shaun R.|last3=Barbieri|first3=Ruth|last4=Goji|first4=Noriko|last5=Cameron|first5=Andrew|last6=Petkau|first6=Aaron|last7=Polo|first7=Rodrigo Ortega|last8=Tymensen|first8=Lisa|last9=Stamm|first9=Courtney|last10=Song|first10=Jiming|last11=Hannon|first11=Sherry|date=2020|title=Surveillance of Enterococcus spp. reveals distinct species and antimicrobial resistance diversity across a One-Health continuum|journal=Scientific Reports|language=en|volume=10|issue=1|pages=3937|doi=10.1038/s41598-020-61002-5|issn=2045-2322|pmc=7054549|pmid=32127598|bibcode=2020NatSR..10.3937Z}}</ref> Standard precautions such as pasteurising, or preparing and cooking meat properly, [[food preservation]] methods, and effective hand washing can help eliminate, decrease, or prevent spread of and infection from these and other potentially harmful bacteria.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fsis.usda.gov/wps/portal/fsis/topics/food-safety-education/get-answers/food-safety-fact-sheets/safe-food-handling/cleanliness-helps-prevent-foodborne-illness/ct_index|title=Cleanliness Helps Prevent Foodborne Illness|last=United States Department of Agriculture|date=December 2016|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rajendran|first=Reshma|date=2018|title=Superbug infection.|journal=World Journal of Pharmaceutical Research|volume=7|pages=275\u2013287|doi=10.20959/wjpr2018-11480|doi-broken-date=2020-03-15|url=https://wjpr.net/dashboard/abstract_id/9482}}</ref>\n\n==== Other sources of resistance ====\nAs well as via food, ''E. coli'' from a variety of sources can also cause urinary and bloodstream infections. While one study suggests a large proportion of resistant ''[[Escherichia coli|E. coli]]'' isolates causing bloodstream infections in people could emanate from livestock produced for food,<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Vieira|first1=Antonio R.|last2=Collignon|first2=Peter|last3=Aarestrup|first3=Frank M.|last4=McEwen|first4=Scott A.|last5=Hendriksen|first5=Rene S.|last6=Hald|first6=Tine|last7=Wegener|first7=Henrik C.|date=December 2011|title=Association Between Antimicrobial Resistance in ''Escherichia coli'' Isolates from Food Animals and Blood Stream Isolates from Humans in Europe: An Ecological Study|journal=Foodborne Pathogens and Disease|volume=8|issue=12|pages=1295\u20131301|doi=10.1089/fpd.2011.0950|pmid=21883007}}</ref> other studies have since contradicted this, finding little commonality between resistance genes from livestock sources and those found in human infections, even when examining plasmid-mediated resistance.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dorado-Garc\u00eda|first=Alejandro|last2=Smid|first2=Joost H|last3=van Pelt|first3=Wilfrid|last4=Bonten|first4=Marc J M|last5=Fluit|first5=Ad C|last6=van den Bunt|first6=Gerrita|last7=Wagenaar|first7=Jaap A|last8=Hordijk|first8=Joost|last9=Dierikx|first9=Cindy M|last10=Veldman|first10=Kees T|last11=de Koeijer|first11=Aline|date=2018-02-01|title=Molecular relatedness of ESBL/AmpC-producing Escherichia coli from humans, animals, food and the environment: a pooled analysis|url=http://academic.oup.com/jac/article/73/2/339/4641706|journal=Journal of Antimicrobial Chemotherapy|language=en|volume=73|issue=2|pages=339\u2013347|doi=10.1093/jac/dkx397|pmid=29165596|issn=0305-7453}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ludden|first=Catherine|last2=Raven|first2=Kathy E.|last3=Jamrozy|first3=Dorota|last4=Gouliouris|first4=Theodore|last5=Blane|first5=Beth|last6=Coll|first6=Francesc|last7=de Goffau|first7=Marcus|last8=Naydenova|first8=Plamena|last9=Horner|first9=Carolyne|last10=Hernandez-Garcia|first10=Juan|last11=Wood|first11=Paul|date=2019-01-22|editor-last=Sansonetti|editor-first=Philippe J.|title=One Health Genomic Surveillance of Escherichia coli Demonstrates Distinct Lineages and Mobile Genetic Elements in Isolates from Humans versus Livestock|journal=mBio|language=en|volume=10|issue=1|pages=e02693\u201318, /mbio/10/1/mBio.02693\u201318.atom|doi=10.1128/mBio.02693-18|issn=2150-7511|pmc=6343043|pmid=30670621}}</ref><ref name=\":12\">{{Cite journal|last=El Garch|first=Farid|last2=de Jong|first2=Anno|last3=Bertrand|first3=Xavier|last4=Hocquet|first4=Didier|last5=Sauget|first5=Marl\u00e8ne|date=2018|title=mcr-1-like detection in commensal Escherichia coli and Salmonella spp. from food-producing animals at slaughter in Europe|journal=Veterinary Microbiology|language=en|volume=213|pages=42\u201346|doi=10.1016/j.vetmic.2017.11.014|pmid=29292002}}</ref>\n\nThe use of antibiotics in livestock also has the potential to introduce antibiotic-resistant bacteria to humans via environmental exposure or inhalation of airborne bacteria. Antibiotics given to livestock in sub-therapeutic concentrations to stimulate growth when there is no diagnosis of disease - a practice still permitted in some countries - may kill some, but not all, of the bacterial organisms in the animal, possibly leaving those that are naturally antibiotic-resistant in the environment. Hence the practice of using antibiotics for growth stimulation could result in selection for resistance.<ref>{{cite book|last=Wegener|first=Henrik C.|title=Antibiotic Resistance \u2014 Linking Human And Animal Health: Improving Food Safety Through a One Health Approach Workshop Summary|publisher=National Academies Press|year=2012|isbn=978-0-309-25937-8|editor=Choffnes, E.R.|location=Washington DC|pages=|chapter=A15 Antibiotic Resistance\u2014Linking Human and Animal Health|doi=10.17226/13423|pmid=23230579|id=NBK114485|editor2=Relman, D.A.|editor3=Olsen, L.|editor4=Hutton, R.|editor5=Mack, A.|chapterurl=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK114485/}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author=Wegener H|year=2003|title=Antibiotics in animal feed and their role in resistance development|journal=Current Opinion in Microbiology|volume=6|issue=5|pages=439\u2013445|doi=10.1016/j.mib.2003.09.009|pmid=14572534}}</ref> Antibiotics are not fully digested and processed in the animal or human gut, therefore, an estimated 40 to 90% of the antibiotics ingested are excreted in urine and/or faeces.<ref name=\"Prevalence\">{{cite journal |last1=Zhang |first1=X |title=Prevalence of veterinary antibiotics and antibiotic-resistant Escherichia coli in the surface water of a livestock production region in northern China |journal=PLOS One |volume=9 |issue=11 |pages=e111026 |pmid=25372873 |pmc=4220964 |year=2014 |doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0111026 |bibcode=2014PLoSO...9k1026Z |url=https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/aec867274d40c5ac7a084ae5ced227a6ff56ee5a}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Storteboom|first=Heather|last2=Arabi|first2=Mazdak|last3=Davis|first3=Jessica G.|last4=Crimi|first4=Barbara|last5=Pruden|first5=Amy|date=October 2010|title=Tracking Antibiotic Resistance Genes in the South Platte River Basin Using Molecular Signatures of Urban, Agricultural, And Pristine Sources|journal=Environmental Science & Technology|language=en|volume=44|issue=19|pages=7397\u20137404|doi=10.1021/es101657s|pmid=20809616|bibcode=2010EnST...44.7397S|issn=0013-936X}}</ref> This means that as well as finding antibiotics in human sewage and animal manure, both can also contain antibiotic-resistant bacteria which have developed ''in vivo'' or in the environment. When animal manures are stored inadequately or applied as fertiliser, this can then spread bacteria to crops and into run-off water.<ref name=\"Sarmah et al 2006\" /><ref name=\"Prevalence\" /> Antibiotics have been found in small amounts in crops grown in fertilised fields,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cimitile |first1=Matthew |title=Worried about Antibiotics in Your Beef? Vegetables May Be No Better |url=https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/vegetables-contain-antibiotics/}}</ref> and detected in runoff from animal waste-fertilised land.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Sun |first1=P |title=Detection and quantification of ionophore antibiotics in runoff, soil and poultry litter. |journal=Journal of Chromatography A |volume=1312 |pages=10\u20137 |pmid=24028934 |year=2013 |doi=10.1016/j.chroma.2013.08.044}}</ref> Composting has been shown to reduce the presence of various antibiotics by 20-99%,<ref name=\"Prevalence\" /> but one study found that chlortetracycline (CTC), an antibiotic used in livestock feed in China, degraded at different rates dependent on the animal it was fed to, and that manure composting was not sufficient to ensure the microbial degradation of CTC.<ref name=\"Depletion\">{{cite journal|last1=Bao|first1=Yanyu|last2=Zhou|first2=Qixing|last3=Guan|first3=Lianzhu|last4=Wang|first4=Yingying|date=April 2009|title=Depletion of chlortetracycline during composting of aged and spiked manures.|journal=Waste Management|volume=29|issue=4|pages=1416\u20131423|doi=10.1016/j.wasman.2008.08.022|pmid=18954968}}</ref>\n\n== Global positions on antibiotic use in farm animals ==\nIn 2017, the World Health Organization (WHO) recommended reducing antibiotic use in animals used in the food industry. Due to the increasing risk of antibiotic resistant bacteria, the WHO strongly suggested restrictions on antibiotics being used for growth promotion and antibiotics used on healthy animals. Animals that require antibiotics should be treated with antibiotics that pose the smallest risk to human health.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> [[HSBC]] also produced a report in October 2018 warning that the use of antibiotics in meat production could have \u201cdevastating\u201d consequences for humans. It noted that many dairy and meat producers in Asia and the Americas had an economic incentive to continue high usage of antibiotics, particularly in crowded or unsanitary living conditions.<ref>{{cite news |title=One of the world's largest banks has issued an alarming warning about antibiotic resistance \u2014 with big consequences for humanity |url=http://uk.businessinsider.com/hsbc-says-meat-production-creates-devastating-antibiotic-resistance-2018-10 |accessdate=13 November 2018 |publisher=Business Insider UK |date=10 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nHowever, the [[World Organisation for Animal Health]] has acknowledged the need to protect antibiotics but argued against a total ban on antibiotic use in animal production.<ref>{{cite news |title=Antibiotics for livestock vital to feed world: OIE |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-antibiotics-livestock/antibiotics-for-livestock-vital-to-feed-world-oie-idUSTRE80A1JF20120111 |work=Reuters |date=11 January 2012}}</ref> A total ban on antibiotics might drastically reduce protein supply in some parts of the world,<ref name=\":1\">Stop using antibiotics in healthy animals to preserve their effectiveness. (2017). Retrieved from https://www.who.int/news-room/detail/07-11-2017-stop-using-antibiotics-in-healthy-animals-to-prevent-the-spread-of-antibiotic-resistance</ref> and when use of antibiotics is reduced or eliminated in livestock through legislation or voluntarily, both animal health and welfare and economic impacts can be negatively affected.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Karavolias |first1=Joanna |last2=Salois |first2=Matthew Jude |last3=Baker |first3=Kristi |last4=Watkins |first4=Kevin |title=Raised without antibiotics: impact on animal welfare and implications for food policy |journal=Translational Animal Science |date=October 2018 |volume=2 |issue=4 |pages=337\u2013348 |doi=10.1093/tas/txy016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Phillips |first1=I. |last2=Casewell |first2=M |last3=Cox |first3=T |last4=De Groot |first4=B |last5=Friis |first5=C |last6=Jones |first6=R |last7=Nightingale |first7=C |last8=Preston |first8=R |last9=Waddell |first9=J |title=Does the use of antibiotics in food animals pose a risk to human health? A critical review of published data |journal=Journal of Antimicrobial Chemotherapy |date=4 December 2003 |volume=53 |issue=1 |pages=28\u201352 |doi=10.1093/jac/dkg483 |pmid=14657094 |doi-access=free}}</ref> For example, experiences from farms where antibiotic use has been cut back or eliminated in the interests of meeting a consumer demand for 'antibiotic-free' or 'reared without antibiotics' produce have been shown to have a detrimental effect on animal health and welfare.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Dee |first1=S |last2=Guzman |first2=JE |last3=Hanson |first3=D |last4=Garbes |first4=N |last5=Morrison |first5=R |last6=Amodie |first6=D |title=A randomized controlled trial to evaluate performance of pigs raised in antibiotic-free or conventional production systems following challenge with porcine reproductive and respiratory syndrome virus |journal=PLOS One |date=2018 |volume=13 |issue=12 |page=e0208430|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0208430 |pmid=30521587 |pmc=6283559 |bibcode=2018PLoSO..1308430D}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Gaucher |first1=ML |last2=Quessy |first2=S |last3=Letellier |first3=A |last4=Boulianne |first4=M |title=mpact of a drug-free 391 program on broiler chicken growth performances, gut health, Clostridium perfringens and 392 Campylobacter jejuni occurrences at the farm level |journal=Poultry Science |date=2015 |volume=94 |issue=8 |pages=1791\u2013801 |doi=10.3382/ps/pev142 |pmid=26047674}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Smith |first1=JA |title=Experiences with drug-free broiler production |journal=Poultry Science |date=2011 |volume=90 |issue=11 |pages=2670\u20138 |doi=10.3382/ps.2010-01032 |pmid=22010257}}</ref> When antibiotics are used sub-therapeutically (for animal performance, increased growth, and improved feed efficiency), then the costs of meat, eggs, and other animal products are lowered.<ref name=\"NRC\">{{cite book |author=National Research Council (US) Committee on Drug Use in Food Animals |chapter=Costs of Eliminating Subtherapeutic Use of Antibiotics |title=The Use of Drugs in Food Animals: Benefits and Risks |chapterurl=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK232579/ |date=1999 |publisher=National Academies Press}}</ref> One big argument against the restriction of antibiotic use is the potential economic hardship that would result for producers of livestock and poultry that could also result in higher cost for consumers.In a study analysing the economic cost of the FDA restricting all antibiotic use in animal livestock, it was estimated that the restriction would cost consumers approximately $1.2 billion to $2.5 billion per year.<ref name=\"NRC\" /> In order to determine the overall economic impact of restricting antibiotic use, the financial cost must be weighed against the health benefits to the population. Since it is difficult to estimate the value of potential health benefits, the study concluded that the complete economic impact of restricting antibiotic use has not yet been determined.<ref name=\"NRC\" />\n\nAlthough quantifying health benefits may be difficult, the economic impact of antibiotic restriction in animals can also be evaluated through the economic impact of antibiotic resistance in humans, which is a significant outcome of antibiotic use in animals. The World Health Organization identifies antibiotic resistance as a contributor to longer hospital stays and higher medical costs.<ref name=\"WHO AR\">{{cite web |title=Antibiotic Resistance|url=https://www.who.int/news-room/fact-sheets/detail/antibiotic-resistance |website=WHO |publisher=World Health Organization |accessdate=28 March 2019}}</ref> When infections can no longer be treated by typical first-line antibiotics, more expensive medications are required for treatment. When illness duration is extended by antibiotics resistance, the increased health care costs create a larger economic burden for families and societies.<ref name=\"WHO AR\"/> The Center for Infectious Disease Research and Policy estimates approximately $2.2 billion in antibiotic resistance- related healthcare costs each year.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Dall |first1=Chris |title=Price to Pay: Antibiotic-Resistant Infections Cost $2 billion a year |journal=The Center for Infectious Disease Research and Policy |date=22 March 2018}}</ref> So while restricting antibiotics in animals causes a significant economic burden, the outcome of antibiotic resistance in humans that is perpetuated by antibiotic use in animals carries comparable economic burdens.\n\n== Use and regulation by country ==\nThe use of medicines to treat disease in food-producing animals is regulated in nearly all countries, although some countries prescription-control their antibiotics, meaning only qualified veterinary surgeons can prescribe and in some cases dispense them.<ref name=\"Tang et al2\">{{cite journal|last1=Tang|first1=Karen L|last2=Caffrey|first2=Niamh P|last3=N\u00f3brega|first3=Diego|last4=Cork|first4=Susan C|last5=Ronksley|first5=Paul C|last6=Barkema|first6=Herman W|last7=Polachek|first7=Alicia J|last8=Ganshorn|first8=Heather|last9=Sharma|first9=Nishan|last10=Kellner|first10=James D|last11=Checkley|first11=Sylvia L|date=August 2019|title=Comparison of different approaches to antibiotic restriction in food-producing animals: stratified results from a systematic review and meta-analysis|url=https://gh.bmj.com/content/bmjgh/4/4/e001710.full.pdf|journal=BMJ Global Health|volume=2019|issue=4|pages=e001710|doi=10.1136/bmjgh-2019-001710|pmc=6730577|pmid=31543995|last12=Ghali|first12=William A}}</ref> Historically, the restrictions have existed to prevent contamination of mainly meat, milk, eggs and honey with chemicals that are in any way harmful to humans. Treating a sick animal with medicines may lead the animal product containing some of those medicines when the animal is slaughtered, milked, lays eggs or produces honey, unless withdrawal periods are adhered to which stipulate a period of time to ensure the medicines have left the animal's system sufficiently to avoid any risk.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vmd.defra.gov.uk/pdf/leaflet_residues.pdf|title=Avoiding Veterinary Residues in Food \u2013 Maintaining Consumer Confidence|last1=Veterinary Medicines Directorate|website=Defra (UK)|accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref> Scientific experiments provide data for each medicine in each application, showing how long it is present in the body of an animal and what the animal's body does to metabolise the medicine. By the use of 'drug withdrawal periods' before slaughter or the use of milk or eggs from treated animals, veterinarians and animal owners ensure that the meat, milk and eggs is safe and free of any contamination.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://healthforanimals.org/downloads/library/veterinary%20medicines%20and%20food%20safety.pdf|title=Veterinary Medicines and Food Safety|last1=IFAH|website=Health for Animals|accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref> However, some countries have also banned or heavily controlled routine use of antibiotics for growth stimulation or the preventative control of disease arising from deficiencies in management or facilities. This is not over concerns about residues, but about the growth of antibiotic resistance (also called [[Antimicrobial resistance|antimicrobial resistance/AMR]]).\n\n===Brazil===\nBrazil is the world's largest exporter of beef. The government regulates antibiotic use in the cattle production industry.<ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Millen|first1=D. D.|last2=Pacheco|first2=R. D. L.|last3=Meyer|first3=P. M.|last4=Rodrigues|first4=P. H. M.|last5=De Beni Arrigoni|first5=M.|year=2011|title=Current outlook and future perspectives of beef production in Brazil|url=|journal=Animal Frontiers|volume=1|issue=2|pages=46\u201352|doi=10.2527/af.2011-0017|pmc=|pmid=|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\n===Canada===\nBecause of concerns about antibiotics residues getting into the milk or meat of cattle, the [[Canadian Food Inspection Agency]] (CFIA) enforces standards which protect consumers by ensuring that foods produced will not contain antibiotics at a level which will cause harm to consumers. In Canada the veterinary drug regulation consists of two federal government agencies, namely [[Health Canada]] and the CFIA, which are responsible for implementing and enforcing the [[Food and Drugs Act]]. Testing samples for drug residues include three methods: monitoring, surveillance, and compliance. There are Swab Test On Premises (STOP) procedures to detect antibiotic residues in kidney tissues.<ref name=\"Seven\">{{cite web|url=http://ordercentre.beefinfo.org/ca/en/consumer/Download.aspx?FileName=150147-EN.PDF&masterNo=150147&itemType=PDF&itemUnits=EACH&catalogCode=RES_HEALTHPROFESSIONAL&subCatalogCode=RES_HEALTH_FORTHEHEALTHPRO&Language=LAN_ENGLISH&ProfileNo=462375|title=Understanding Use of Antibiotic and Hormonal Substances in Beef Cattle|author=Canadian Cattlemen's Association and Beef Information Centre|year=2003|work=Nutrition Perspective|url-status=dead|archiveurl=http://arquivo.pt/wayback/20160517162213/http://ordercentre.beefinfo.org/ca/en/consumer/Download.aspx?FileName=150147-EN.PDF&masterNo=150147&itemType=PDF&itemUnits=EACH&catalogCode=RES_HEALTHPROFESSIONAL&subCatalogCode=RES_HEALTH_FORTHEHEALTHPRO&Language=LAN_ENGLISH&ProfileNo=462375|archivedate=17 May 2016|accessdate=29 October 2009|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===China===\nChina produces and consumes the most antibiotics of all countries.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rendezvous.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/02/18/global-health-threat-seen-in-overuse-of-antibiotics-on-chinese-pig-farms/|title=Global Health Threat Seen in Overuse of Antibiotics on Chinese Pig Farms|last=Tatlow|first=Didi Kirsten|date=18 February 2013|work=IHT Rendezvous|accessdate=28 August 2013}}</ref> Antibiotic use has been measured by checking the water near factory farms in China<ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Wei|first1=R.|last2=Ge|first2=F.|last3=Huang|first3=S.|last4=Chen|first4=M.|last5=Wang|first5=R.|year=2011|title=Occurrence of veterinary antibiotics in animal wastewater and surface water around farms in Jiangsu Province, China|url=http://qnnkxjj.cast.org.cn/uploadfile/jiangxiang/2013Jul24/1374656004765.pdf|url-status=dead|journal=Chemosphere|volume=82|issue=10|pages=1408\u20131414|bibcode=2011Chmsp..82.1408W|doi=10.1016/j.chemosphere.2010.11.067|pmc=|pmid=21159362|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180817225810/http://qnnkxjj.cast.org.cn/uploadfile/jiangxiang/2013Jul24/1374656004765.pdf|archive-date=17 August 2018|accessdate=17 August 2018|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Hu|first1=X.|last2=Zhou|first2=Q.|last3=Luo|first3=Y.|year=2010|title=Occurrence and source analysis of typical veterinary antibiotics in manure, soil, vegetables and groundwater from organic vegetable bases, northern China|journal=Environmental Pollution|volume=158|issue=9|pages=2992\u20132998|doi=10.1016/j.envpol.2010.05.023|pmc=|pmid=20580472}}</ref> as well as through animal faeces.<ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Zhao|first1=L.|last2=Dong|first2=Y. H.|last3=Wang|first3=H.|year=2010|title=Residues of veterinary antibiotics in manures from feedlot livestock in eight provinces of China|journal=Science of the Total Environment|volume=408|issue=5|pages=1069\u20131075|bibcode=2010ScTEn.408.1069Z|doi=10.1016/j.scitotenv.2009.11.014|pmc=|pmid=19954821}}</ref> It was calculated that 38.5 million kg (or 84.9 million lbs) of antibiotics were used in China's swine and poultry production in 2012.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Krishnasamy|first1=Vikram|last2=Otte|first2=Joachim|last3=Silbergeld|first3=Ellen|date=28 April 2015|title=Antimicrobial use in Chinese swine and broiler poultry production|url=https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/024a405347f1bbe40e2bddb1c0faf3324d25dfb3|journal=Antimicrobial Resistance and Infection Control|volume=4|issue=1|pages=17|doi=10.1186/s13756-015-0050-y|issn=2047-2994|pmc=4412119|pmid=25922664|ref=harv|doi-access=free}}</ref> The abuse of antibiotics caused severe pollution of soil and surface water in Northern China.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Mu|first1=Quanhua|last2=Li|first2=Jin|last3=Sun|first3=Yingxue|last4=Mao|first4=Daqing|last5=Wang|first5=Qing|last6=Yi|first6=Luo|date=5 December 2014|title=Occurrence of sulfonamide-, tetracycline-, plasmid-mediated quinolone- and macrolide-resistance genes in livestock feedlots in Northern China|url=https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/806fa4931cb62c4b6c7840b4455de7a87cf11fdd|journal=Springer|volume=22|issue=6932\u20136940|pages=6932\u20136940|doi=10.1007/s11356-014-3905-5|pmid=25475616}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, [[U.S. News & World Report]] described the Chinese government's regulation of antibiotics in livestock production as \"weak\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://health.usnews.com/health-news/news/articles/2013/02/11/chinas-overuse-of-antibiotics-in-livestock-may-threaten-human-health|title=China's Overuse of Antibiotics in Livestock May Threaten Human Health|last=Salamon|first=Maureen|date=11 February 2013|work=health.usnews.com|accessdate=28 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn the UK 5-Year Antimicrobial Resistance(AMR) Strategy 2013\u20132018, the importance of addressing AMR negative effects on animal health has been considered as same as human health. Several scientific partnerships with low-middle income countries would be established.<ref>https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/662189/UK_AMR_3rd_annual_report.pdf</ref> UK-China Newton fund has started to build multi-discipline collaboration cross the border to stop the increasing global burden caused by AMR.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mrc.ukri.org/news/browse/4-5m-from-newton-fund-for-collaborations-that-will-tackle-antimicrobial-resistance/|title=\u00a34.5m from Newton Fund for collaborations that will tackle antimicrobial resistance|last=Medical Research Council|first=M. R. C.|date=29 November 2018|website=mrc.ukri.org|accessdate=6 December 2018}}</ref> To achieve the goal of citizen public health and food safety, \u201cThe National action Plan on Controlling Antibiotic-Resistance Bacteria on animal origins(2016-2020)\u201d has been published by Ministry of Agriculture and Rural Affairs of People's Republic of China since 2017. This plan is fully integrated with the concept of one health. It covers not only the research and development, but also social context.\n\nThe following aims should be achieved by 2020:<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://jiuban.moa.gov.cn/zwllm/tzgg/tz/201706/t20170623_5726086.htm|title=\u519c\u4e1a\u90e8\u5173\u4e8e\u5370\u53d1\u300a\u5168\u56fd\u904f\u5236\u52a8\u7269\u6e90\u7ec6\u83cc\u8010\u836f\u884c\u52a8\u8ba1\u5212\uff082017\u20142020\u5e74\uff09\u300b\u7684\u901a\u77e5|website=jiuban.moa.gov.cn|accessdate=6 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://resistancecontrol.info/2017/a-national-action-plan-to-contain-antimicrobial-resistance-in-china-contents-actions-and-expectations/|title=A National Action Plan to Contain Antimicrobial Resistance in China: Contents, Actions and Expectations {{!}} AMR Control|website=resistancecontrol.info|accessdate=6 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n# Implementation of Exit Plan, to encourage the drop of antibiotics as the growth promoters\n# Regulation of drug market, to strengthen the registration and management of veterinary antibiotics\n# Improvements on AMR surveillance system\n# Strengthening on the testing of antibacterial residue\n# Exemplification on effective models of decreasing the use on antibiotics\n# Education on public and professions\n\n===European Union===\n\nIn 1999, the European Union (EU) implemented an antibiotic resistance monitoring program and a plan to phase out antibiotic use for the purposes of growth promotion by 2006.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://europa.eu/rapid/press-release_IP-05-1687_en.htm|title=European Commission - PRESS RELEASES - Press release - Ban on antibiotics as growth promoters in animal feed enters into effect|last=European Union|date=2005|accessdate=22 December 2005}}</ref> The European Union banned the use of antibiotics as growth agents starting on 1 January 2006 with Regulation (EC) No 1831/2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://data.europa.eu/eli/reg/2003/1831/oj|title=EUR-Lex - 32003R1831 - EN - EUR-Lex|website=data.europa.eu}}</ref> In [[Germany]], 1,734 tons of antimicrobial agents were used for animals in 2011 compared with 800 tons for humans.{{citation needed|date=March 2017}} [[Sweden]] banned their use in 1986 and [[Denmark]] started cutting down drastically in 1994, now using 60% less.<ref>{{cite news|last=Koch|first=Julia|url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/europe/danish-pig-farmers-reduce-antibiotics-to-prevent-drug-resistance-a-933344.html|title=Cutting Antibiotics : Denmark Leads Way in Healthier Pig Farming|date=13 November 2013|work=Spiegel Online|accessdate=22 May 2014}}</ref> In [[the Netherlands]], the use of antibiotics to treat diseases increased after the ban on its use for growth purposes in 2006.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Cogliani|first1=Carol|last2=Goossens|first2=Herman|last3=Greko|first3=Christina|date=1 January 2011|title=Restricting Antimicrobial Use in Food Animals: Lessons from Europe|journal=Microbe Magazine|volume=6|issue=6|pages=274\u2013279|doi=10.1128/microbe.6.274.1|issn=1558-7452|ref=harv}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, the European Parliament voted for a non-binding resolution that called for the end of the preventative use of antibiotics in livestock.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/sides/getDoc.do?pubRef=-//EP//TEXT+IM-PRESS+20111026IPR30419+0+DOC+XML+V0//EN|title=Parliament demands smarter use of antibiotics|website=www.europarl.europa.eu}}</ref>\n\nA revised regulation on veterinary medicinal products, proposed in procedure 2014/0257/COD, proposed limiting the use of antibiotics in prophylaxis and metaphylaxis. An agreement on the regulation between the Council of the European Union and the European Parliament was confirmed on 13 June 2018,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eur-lex.europa.eu/procedure/EN/2014_257|title=EUR-Lex - 2014_257 - EN - EUR-Lex|website=eur-lex.europa.eu}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.consilium.europa.eu/en/press/press-releases/2018/06/13/veterinary-medicines-new-eu-rules-to-enhance-availability-and-fight-against-antimicrobial-resistance/|title=Veterinary medicines: new EU rules to enhance availability and fight against antimicrobial resistance - Consilium|website=www.consilium.europa.eu}}</ref> and the new Veterinary Medicines Regulation (Regulation (EU) 2019/6) is due to come into effect on 28 January 2022.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ema.europa.eu/en/veterinary-regulatory/overview/implementation-new-veterinary-medicines-regulation|title=Implementation of the new Veterinary Medicines Regulation|last=European Medicines Agency|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===India===\n\nIn 2011 the Indian government proposed a \"National policy for containment of antimicrobial resistance\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/govt-wants-to-limit-use-of-antibiotics-in-animals/775330/|title=Govt wants to limit use of antibiotics in animals \u2013 Indian Express|last=Thacker|first=Teena|date=13 April 2011|work=indianexpress.com|accessdate=28 August 2013}}</ref> Other policies set schedules for requiring that food producing animals not be given antibiotics for a certain amount of time before their food goes to market.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-11-25/science/30440181_1_antibiotic-resistance-poultry-products-livestock|title=New norm to curb antibiotic resistance \u2013 Times of India|last=Sinha|first=Kounteya|date=25 November 2011|work=indiatimes.com|accessdate=28 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-04-06/india/31300016_1_antibiotics-seafood-and-poultry-products-staphylococcus|title=In a first, antibiotics bar on food-producing animals \u2013 Times of India|last=Sinha|first=Kounteya|date=6 April 2012|work=indiatimes.com|accessdate=28 August 2013}}</ref> A study released by Centre for Science and Environment (CSE) on 30 July 2014 found antibiotic residues in chicken. This study claims that Indians are developing resistance to antibiotics \u2013 and hence falling prey to a host of otherwise curable ailments. Some of this resistance might be due to large-scale unregulated use of [[Antibiotics in poultry farming|antibiotics in the poultry industry]]. CSE finds that India has not set any limits for antibiotic residues in chicken and says that India will have to implement a comprehensive set of regulations including banning of antibiotic use as growth promoters in the poultry industry. Not doing this will put lives of people at risk.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cseindia.org/node/5487/|title=Centre For Science and Environment (CSE)|date=30 July 2014|accessdate=30 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n===New Zealand===\nIn 1999 the New Zealand government issued a statement that they would not then ban the use of antibiotics in livestock production.<ref>{{cite news|last=staff|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=1071|title=NZ holds off ban on animal antibiotics \u2013 National \u2013 NZ Herald News|date=7 January 1999|work=nzherald.co.nz|accessdate=29 August 2013}}</ref> In 2007 [[ABC Online]] reported on antibiotic use in chicken production in New Zealand.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/radionational/programs/scienceshow/antibiotics-and-intensive-chicken-farming-in-new/3222458#transcript|title=Antibiotics and intensive chicken farming in New Zealand \u2013 The Science Show|last1=Williams|first1=Robyn|last2=Cook|first2=Greg|date=11 August 2007|work=abc.net.au|accessdate=29 August 2013}}</ref>\nIn 2017, New Zealand published a new action plan to address the ongoing concern of antimicrobial resistance (AMR). The action plan outlined five objectives with each objective looking both at AMR in humans and AMR in agriculture.<ref>Ministry of Health and Ministry for Primary Industries. 2017. Antimicrobial Resistance: New Zealand\u2019s current situation and identified areas for action. Wellington: Ministry of Health and Ministry for Primary Industries. Retrieved from https://www.health.govt.nz/publication/antimicrobial-resistance-new-zealands-current-situation-and-identified-areas-action</ref>\nCompared to other countries, New Zealand has a very low prevalence of AMR in animals and plants. This is due to their low use of antibiotics in animal treatment.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Hillerton J.|author2=Irvine C.|author3=Bryan M.|author4=Scott D.|author5=Merchant S.|year=2016|title=Use of antimicrobials for animals in New Zealand, and in comparison with other countries|url=|journal=New Zealand Veterinary Journal|volume=65|issue=2|pages=71\u201377|doi=10.1080/00480169.2016.1171736|pmid=27030313}}</ref>\n\n===South Korea===\nIn 1998 some researchers reported use in livestock production was a factor in the high prevalence of antibiotic-resistant bacteria in Korea.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Kim|first1=Woo Joo|last2=Park|first2=Seung Chull|year=1998|title=bacterial Resistance to Antimicrobial Agents: An Overview from Korea|url=http://www.eymj.org/Synapse/Data/PDFData/0069YMJ/ymj-39-488.pdf|journal=[[Yonsei Medical Journal]]|volume=39|issue=6|pages=488\u2013494|doi=10.3349/ymj.1998.39.6.488|pmid=10097674|accessdate=29 August 2013}}</ref> In 2007 ''[[The Korea Times]]'' noted that Korea has relatively high usage of antibiotics in livestock production.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/special/2010/06/180_5376.html|title=Antibiotics in Livestock Harm Human Beings|last=Won-sup|first=Yoon|date=25 June 2007|work=[[The Korea Times]]|accessdate=29 August 2013}}</ref> In 2011, the Korean government banned the use of antibiotics as growth promoters in livestock.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foodsafetynews.com/2011/06/south-korea-bans-antibiotics-in-animal-feed/#.Uh99Nm2KLm0|title=South Korea Bans Antibiotics in Animal Feed|last=Flynn|first=Dan|date=7 June 2011|work=foodsafetynews.com|accessdate=29 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== United Kingdom ===\nAs with other countries in Europe, use of antibiotics for growth promotion was banned in 2006.<ref name=\":7\" /> Less than one third of all antibiotics sold in the UK are now estimated to be used to treat or prevent disease in farmed animals, following an revision to the 2017 sales data published by the UK Government's Veterinary Medicines Directorate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/775075/One_Health_Report_2019_v45.pdf|title=UK One Health Report: Joint report on antibiotic use and antibiotic resistance|date=31 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/840300/PCDOCS-_1698491-v1-VARSS_errata_2017_.pdf|title=Erratum to UK Veterinary Antibiotic Resistance and Sales Surveillance Report UK-VARSS 2017|last=Veterinary Medicines Directorate|date=29 October 2019|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Furthermore, 2018 sales data<ref name=\":13\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/veterinary-antimicrobial-resistance-and-sales-surveillance-2018|title=Veterinary Antimicrobial Resistance and Sales Surveillance UK-VARSS 2018|last=Veterinary Medicines Directorate|date=29 October 2019|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> estimated use at 29.5&nbsp;mg antibiotics per kg of animal at time of treatment during that year. This represents a 53% reduction in sales of antibiotics to treat food-producing animals over five years.<ref name=\":15\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/sales-of-veterinary-antibiotics-halved-over-the-past-four-years|title=Sales of veterinary antibiotics halved over the past four years|last=Defra|date=29 October 2019|website=|publisher=UK Government|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The reduction has largely been achieved without legislation, and has been credited to voluntary industry action coordinated by the Responsible Use of Medicines in Agriculture (RUMA) Alliance <ref>{{cite web|url=https://ruma.org.uk|title=Responsible Use of Medicines in Agriculture Alliance|accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref> through a 'Targets Task Force' comprising a prominent veterinary surgeon and farmer from each livestock enterprise.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ruma.org.uk/targets-task-force/|title=RUMA Targets Task Force|accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref> A European comparison of 2017 sales data found the UK had the fifth lowest sales in Europe during that year, with 2018 comparisons due to be released towards the end of 2020.<ref name=\"ESVACreport2019\" />\n\nWhile sales data give an overview of levels of use, products are often licensed for use in many species and therefore it is not possible to determine levels of use in different species without more specific usage data from each sector. In 2011, British Poultry Council members, representing 90% of the UK poultry meat industry, formed a stewardship programme that started recording antibiotics used to treat birds in the poultry meat sector in 2012. The first report was published in 2016 and reported a 44% reduction in antibiotic use between 2012 and 2015.<ref name=\":16\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.britishpoultry.org.uk/british-poultry-sector-reduces-antibiotic-use-by-44/|title=British Poultry Sector reduces antibiotic use by 44%|last=British Poultry Council|date=27 July 2016|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> Since then, the organisation has produced three further reports, with the 2019 report confirming that the sector is maintaining reductions of over 80% in total use since it started its stewardship group, as well as reducing use of [https://www.ruma.org.uk/high-risk-antibiotics/ Highest Priority Critically Important Antibiotics] by over 80% by stopping use of 3rd and 4th generation cephalosporins in 2012 and colistin in 2016, and only using macrolides and fluoroquinolones as a last resort. Preventative use of antibiotics has also stopped.\n\nAs many products are licensed for use in poultry and pigs, the increasing transparency around use in the UK poultry meat sector motivated the UK pig sector to set up a stewardship programme in 2016<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.farmantibiotics.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/Pig-stewardship-scheme.pdf|title=NPA Pig IndustryAntibiotic Stewardship Programme|last=National Pig Association|date=2016|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> through the [http://www.npa-uk.org.uk/ National Pig Association]. In 2017, an electronic Medicine Book for pigs (eMB-Pigs) was launched by levy body [[Agriculture and Horticulture Development Board]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pork.ahdb.org.uk/health-welfare/health/antimicrobial-usage/e-medicine-book-emb-pigs/|title=e-Medicine Book (eMB-Pigs)|last=Agriculture and Horticulture Development Board (AHDB)|date=January 2017|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> eMB-Pigs provides a centralised electronic version of the existing paper or electronic medicine book kept on farms, and allows pig producers to record and quantify their individual use of medicines for easy review with the veterinary surgeon, at the same time as capturing use on each farm so that data can be collated to provide national usage figures. After it became a requirement of [https://www.redtractor.org.uk/ Red Tractor] farm assurance for pigs<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://assurance.redtractor.org.uk/contentfiles/Farmers-6755.pdf?_=636223349546888284|title=Important Changes to Red Tractor Pig Membership, Spring/ Summer 2017|last=Red Tractor Assurance|date=2017|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> that annual, aggregated records of antibiotic use must be logged on the eMB system, data released May 2018 showed that according to records covering 87% of the UK slaughter pig population, antibiotic use had halved between 2015 and 2017,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pork.ahdb.org.uk/news/news-releases/2018/may/uk-pig-industry-halves-antibiotic-usage-in-two-years/|title=UK pig industry halves antibiotic usage in two years|last=Agriculture and Horticulture Development Board|date=May 2018|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> Data for 2018 confirms that overall antibiotic use in the UK pig sector fell further, by 60% from the estimated 2015 figure,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/837173/PCDOCS-_1691961-v1-VARSS_2016_Highlights_-_watermarked.pdf|title=UK VARSS 2016 Highlights Report|last=Veterinary Medicines Directorate|date=November 2016|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> to 110&nbsp;mg/kg. Use of [https://www.ruma.org.uk/high-risk-antibiotics/ Highest Priority Critically Important Antibiotics] also fell to 0.06&nbsp;mg/kg,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ahdb.org.uk/news/pig-industry-antibiotic-results-show-further-reduction|title=Pig industry antibiotic results show further reduction|last=Agriculture and Horticulture Development Board|date=May 2019|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> a reduction of 95% from 2015, with use of colistin almost nil.\n\nAs reported in an annual update of progress against UK targets, factors such as levels of infectious disease domestically or internationally, weather and vaccine availability can all affect antibiotic use.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ruma.org.uk/targets-update-shows-further-progress-towards-farm-antibiotic-goals-but-with-more-to-do/|title=Targets update shows further progress towards farm antibiotic goals \u2013 but with more to do|last=Responsible Use of Medicines in Agriculture (RUMA) Alliance|date=October 2019|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> For example, the Scottish salmon farming sector worked with Government and researchers to introduce a vaccine for the disease Furunculosis (''Aeromonas salmonicida'') in 1994, which significantly reduced the need for antibiotic treatments,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www2.gov.scot/Topics/marine/Fish-Shellfish/aquaculture/diseases/notifiableDisease/Furunculosis/Aeromonas|title=Aeromonas Salmonicida|last=Scottish Government|date=February 2018|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> but the trout sector is still without an effective vaccine for this disease. Lack of data can also make it difficult for farmers to know they compare with their peers or what they need to focus on, a particular problem for the sheep and cattle sectors in the UK, which are in the process of trying to set up their own electronic medicines hub to capture data.<ref name=\":9\" /> While unnecessary or inappropriate use is not acceptable, the UK takes a position that zero use is not necessarily desirable either.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ruma.org.uk/ruma-confirms-position-on-antibiotic-free-labelling/|title='Antibiotic-free' labelling|last=Responsible Use of Medicines in Agriculture (RUMA) Alliance|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===United States===\nIn 1970 the [[Food and Drug Administration|FDA]] first recommended that antibiotic use in livestock be limited but set no actual regulations governing this recommendation.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\" /> By 2001, the [[Union of Concerned Scientists]] estimated that more than 70% of the antibiotics consumed in the US were given to food animals (for example, chickens, pigs, and cattle), in the absence of disease.<ref name=\"TheRealNews-2014-05-18\">{{cite web|url=http://therealnews.com/t2/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=31&Itemid=74&jumival=11872|title=Why Are Antibiotics Becoming Useless All Over the World?|author=Martin Khor|authorlink=Martin Khor|date=18 May 2014|publisher=[[The Real News]]|accessdate=18 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ucsusa.org/food_and_agriculture/our-failing-food-system/industrial-agriculture/hogging-it-estimates-of.html#.Wycey1MvzEY|title=Executive summary from the UCS report \"Hogging It: Estimates of Antimicrobial Abuse in Livestock\"|date=January 2001|publisher=Union of Concerned Scientists|ref=harv}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004 the [[Government Accountability Office]] (GAO) heavily critiqued the FDA for not collecting enough information and data on antibiotic use in factory farms. From this, the GAO concluded the FDA did not have enough information to create effective policy changes regarding antibiotic use. In response, the FDA said more research was being conducted and voluntary efforts within the industry would solve the problem of antibiotic resistance.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gao.gov/products/GAO-11-801|title=Antibiotic Resistance: Agencies Have Made Limited Progress Addressing Antibiotic Use in Animals|date=14 September 2011|publisher=U. S. Government Accountability Office}}</ref> However, by 2011, a total of {{Convert|13.6|e6kg|e6lb|abbr=unit}} of antimicrobials were sold for use in food-producing animals in the United States,<ref name=\"FDA2013\">{{Cite report|url=https://www.fda.gov/downloads/ForIndustry/UserFees/AnimalDrugUserFeeActADUFA/UCM440584.pdf|title=Summary Report on Antimicrobials Sold or Distributed for Use in Food-Producing Animals|last=|first=|date=2013|publisher=FDA|issue=|doi=|volume=|pmid=|accessdate=}}</ref> which represented 80% of all antibiotics sold or distributed in the United States.<ref name=\"FDA 2012, Drug Use Review, Table 1\">{{Cite report|url=https://www.fda.gov/downloads/drugs/drugsafety/informationbydrugclass/ucm319435.pdf|title=Drug Use Review|last=|first=|date=2012|publisher=FDA|issue=|doi=|volume=|pmid=|accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2012, the [[United States District Court for the Southern District of New York]], ruling in an action brought by the [[Natural Resources Defense Council]] and others, ordered the FDA to revoke approvals for the use of antibiotics in livestock that violated FDA regulations.<ref name=\"MPFDA\">{{cite news|author=John Gever|url=http://www.medpagetoday.com/PublicHealthPolicy/FDAGeneral/31792|title=FDA Told to Move on Antibiotic Use in Livestock|date=23 March 2012|newspaper=MedPage Today|accessdate=24 March 2012}}</ref> On 11 April 2012 the FDA announced a voluntary program to phase out unsupervised use of drugs as feed additives and convert approved over-the-counter uses for antibiotics to prescription use only, requiring veterinarian supervision of their use and a prescription.<ref name=\"NYTPrescription\">{{cite news|author=Gardiner Harris|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/04/12/us/antibiotics-for-livestock-will-require-prescription-fda-says.html|title=U.S. Tightens Rules on Antibiotics Use for Livestock|date=11 April 2012|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=12 April 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"FDAFAQ\">{{cite web|url=https://www.fda.gov/AnimalVeterinary/GuidanceComplianceEnforcement/GuidanceforIndustry/ucm216939.htm|title=FDA's Strategy on Antimicrobial Resistance&nbsp;\u2014 Questions and Answers|date=11 April 2012|publisher=US Food and Drug Administration|accessdate=12 April 2012|quote=\"Judicious use\" is using an antimicrobial drug appropriately and only when necessary; Based on a thorough review of the available scientific information, FDA recommends that use of medically important antimicrobial drugs in food-producing animals be limited to situations where the use of these drugs is necessary for ensuring animal health, and their use includes veterinary oversight or consultation. FDA believes that using medically important antimicrobial drugs to increase production in food-producing animals is not a judicious use.}}</ref> In December 2013, the FDA announced the commencement of these steps to phase out the use of antibiotics for the purposes of promoting livestock growth.<ref name=\"TheRealNews-2014-05-18\" /><ref>{{cite news|last=Tavernise|first=Sabrina|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/12/12/health/fda-to-phase-out-use-of-some-antibiotics-in-animals-raised-for-meat.html|title=F.D.A. to Phase Out Use of Some Antibiotics in Animals Raised for Meat|date=11 December 2013|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=11 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, the FDA approved a new Veterinary Feed Directive (VFD), an updated guideline giving instructions to pharmaceutical companies, veterinarians and producers about how to administer necessary drugs through the animal's feed and water.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.fda.gov/AnimalVeterinary/GuidanceComplianceEnforcement/GuidanceforIndustry/ucm216939.htm|title=FDA's Strategy on Antimicrobial Resistance - Questions and Answers|last=Center for Veterinary Medicine, FDA|date=December 2013|website=Guidance for Industry|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=14 March 2017|ref=FDAQA}}</ref> Around the same time, the FDA published a report of antibiotics sold or distributed for food-producing animals which found that between 2009 and 2013, just over 60% were 'medically-important' drugs also used in humans;<ref name=\"FDA2013\" /> the rest were from drug classes like [[ionophores]], which are not used in human medicine.<ref name=\"Guidance for Industry: Evaluating the Safety of Antimicrobial New Animal Drugs with Regard to Their Microbiological Effects on Bacteria of Human Health Concern\">{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=2003|title=Evaluating the Safety of Antimicrobial New Animal Drugs with Regard to Their Microbiological Effects on Bacteria of Human Health Concern|url=https://www.fda.gov/downloads/AnimalVeterinary/GuidanceComplianceEnforcement/GuidanceforIndustry/ucm052519.pdf|journal=Guidance for Industry|volume=|issue=#152|pages=|via=}}</ref> Following this, the FDA asked drug companies to voluntarily edit its labels to exclude growth promotion as an indication for antibiotic usage. It subsequently reports that \u201cUnder Guidance for Industry (GFI) #213, which went into effect Jan 1, 2017, antibiotics that are important for human medicine can no longer be used for growth promotion or feed efficiency in cows, pigs, chickens, turkeys, and other food animals.\u201d<ref>Summary Report On Antimicrobials Sold or Distributed for Use in Food-Producing Animals. (2018). US Food and Drug Administration. Retrieved from https://www.fda.gov/downloads/ForIndustry/UserFees/AnimalDrugUserFeeActADUFA/UCM628538.pdf</ref> These new 2017 guidelines for instance prohibited using a drug off-label for non-therapeutic purposes, which would make using the re-labeled drug for growth enhancement illegal. In addition, some drugs were reclassified from 'Over the Counter' (OTC) to 'Veterinary Feed Directive' (VFD); VFD drugs require a veterinarian's authorization before they can be delivered in feed.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":14\">{{Cite web|url=https://ahdc.vet.cornell.edu/programs/NYSCHAP/nysvfrp/vfd.cfm#AffectedVFD|title=VFD \u2013 Veterinary Feed Directive|last=Cornell University College of Veterinary Medicine|accessdate=14 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=\":3\" /> As a result, the FDA reported a 33% decrease from 2016 to 2017 in domestic sales of medically important antibiotics for use in livestock. Despite this progress, the [[Natural Resources Defense Council]] (NRDC) remains concerned that sales of antibiotics to the beef and pork industries remain elevated in 2017 compared with the poultry industries, and their use could still primarily be for preventing diseases in healthy animals, which further increases the threat on antibiotic resistance.<ref>Dall C. (2018). FDA reports major drop in antibiotics for food animals. CIDRAP News. Retrieved from http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/news-perspective/2018/12/fda-reports-major-drop-antibiotics-food-animals</ref> However, the FDA policy remains the same as it stated in 2013:<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n{{Quote|text=The key aspect of FDA\u2019s strategy is the request that animal drug sponsors (those who own the right to market the product) voluntarily work with FDA to revise the approved use conditions for their medically important antimicrobial drug products to remove production uses (such as growth enhancement or feed efficiency), and bring the remaining therapeutic uses under veterinary oversight. Once manufacturers voluntarily make these changes, products can no longer be used for production purposes and therapeutic use of these products would require veterinary oversight.|sign=|source=|title=}}\n\nBecause of concerns about antibiotics residues getting into the milk or meat of cattle, in the United States, the government requires a withdraw period for any animal treated with antibiotics before it can be slaughtered, to allow residue to exit the animal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fsis.usda.gov/factsheets/beef_from_farm_to_table/index.asp|title=Beef...from Farm to Table|author=USDA|work=Fact Sheets|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130224010018/http://www.fsis.usda.gov/Factsheets/Beef_from_Farm_to_Table/index.asp|archivedate=24 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nSome [[grocery stores]] have policies about antibiotic use in the animal whose produce they sell. In response to consumer concerns about the [[use of antibiotics in poultry]], [[Perdue Farms|Perdue]] removed all human antibiotics from its feed in 2007 and launched the Harvestland brand, under which it sold products that met the requirements for an \"antibiotic-free\" label. In 2012 in the United States advocacy organization [[Consumers Union]] organized a petition asking the store [[Trader Joe's]] to discontinue the sale of meat produced with antibiotics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.meatwithoutdrugs.org|title=Meat Without Drugs|publisher=[[Consumers Union]]|accessdate=27 August 2013}}, which is described in the following works\n\n*{{cite book|last=Gore|first=Al|title=The Future : Six Drivers of Global Change|title-link=The Future : Six Drivers of Global Change|publisher=[[Random House]]|year=2013|isbn=9780812992946|edition=First|location=New York|pages=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780812992946/page/227 227 and citation on 475]|chapter=The Reinvention of Life and Death: Antibiotics before Swine|authorlink=Al Gore}}\n*{{cite journal|last=Hurd|first=Scott|date=26 June 2012|title=Commentary: 'Meat without Drugs' could be inhumane|url=http://www.bovinevetonline.com/news/industry/Commentary-Meat-without-Drugs-could-be-inhumane-160409875.html|journal=Bovine Veterinarian|accessdate=27 August 2013|quote=All peer-reviewed scientific risk assessments have demonstrated a negligible risk of human health harm due to livestock antibiotic use.}}\n*{{cite journal|last=Greenaway|first=Twilight|date=20 June 2012|title=Your meat on drugs: Will grocery stores cut out antibiotics?|url=http://grist.org/factory-farms/your-meat-on-drugs-can-grocery-stores-be-convinced-to-cut-out-antibiotics/|journal=[[Grist (magazine)|Grist]]|accessdate=27 August 2013}}</ref> By 2014, Perdue had also phased out ionophores from its hatchery and began using the \"antibiotic free\" labels on its Harvestland, Simply Smart, and Perfect Portions products,<ref name=\"Stephanie Strom\">{{cite news|author=Stephanie Strom|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/01/business/perdue-and-the-race-to-end-antibiotic-use-in-chickens.html|title=Perdue Sharply Cuts Antibiotic Use in Chickens and Jabs at Its Rivals|date=31 July 2015|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=12 August 2015}}</ref> and by 2015, 52% of the company's chickens were raised without the use of any type of antibiotics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://perduefarms.com/News_Room/Statements_and_Comments/details.asp?id=545&title=Antibiotics%20Position%20Statement|title=Antibiotics Position Statement|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150728182903/http://www.perduefarms.com/News_Room/Statements_and_Comments/details.asp?id=545&title=Antibiotics%20Position%20Statement|archive-date=28 July 2015|accessdate=12 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe CDC and FDA do not now support the use of antibiotics for growth promotion because of evidence suggesting that antibiotics used for growth promotion purposes could lead to the development of resistant bacteria.<ref name=\":6\" /> In addition to this, [[The Pew Charitable Trusts]] has stated that \"hundreds of scientific studies conducted over four decades demonstrate that feeding low doses of antibiotics to livestock breeds antibiotic-resistant superbugs that can infect people\".<ref name=\"pew-2012\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pewhealth.org/uploadedFiles/PHG/Content_Level_Pages/Issue_Briefs/HHIFBibliographyFinal%20with%20TOC%20_071712.pdf|title=Antibiotic Resistance and Food Animal Production: a Bibliography of Scientific Studies (1969-2012)|website=The Pew Charitable Trusts|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120811001709/http://www.pewhealth.org/uploadedFiles/PHG/Content_Level_Pages/Issue_Briefs/HHIFBibliographyFinal%20with%20TOC%20_071712.pdf|archivedate=11 August 2012}}</ref> The FDA, the U.S. Department of Agriculture and the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention have all testified before Congress that there is a definitive link between the routine, non-therapeutic use of antibiotics in food animal production and the challenge of antibiotic resistance in humans.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pewtrusts.org/news_room_detail.aspx?id=85899424573|title=Pew Comments on Proposed Antibiotics Legislation|author=The Pew Charitable Trusts|authorlink=The Pew Charitable Trusts|date=15 October 2012|accessdate=26 August 2013}}</ref> However, the [[National Pork Board]], a [[government-owned corporation]] of the United States, has said: \"The vast majority of producers use (antibiotics) appropriately.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2010/02/09/eveningnews/main6191530.shtml|title=Animal Antibiotic Overuse Hurting Humans?|last=Couric|first=Katie|date=10 February 2010|work=[[CBS News]]|publisher=[[CBS Broadcasting|CBS]]|location=New York City|accessdate=29 August 2013}}</ref> In 2011 the [[National Pork Producers Council]], an American [[trade association]], also said, \"Not only is there no scientific study linking antibiotic use in food animals to antibiotic resistance in humans, as the US pork industry has continually pointed out, but there isn't even adequate data to conduct a study.\"<ref>*{{cite web|url=http://growinggeorgia.com/news/2011/09/natl-pork-producers-council-issues-statement-about-gaos-report-antibiotic-resistance/|title=Nat'l Pork Producers Council Issues Statement About GAO's Report on Antibiotic Resistance|author=National Pork Producers Council|authorlink=National Pork Producers Council|date=15 September 2011|work=growinggeorgia.com|accessdate=29 August 2013}}\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.motherjones.com/tom-philpott/2011/09/meat-industry-antibiotic-resistance|title=Meat Industry Still Denying Antibiotic Resistance|last=Philpott|first=Tom|date=21 September 2011|work=motherjones.com|accessdate=29 August 2013}}</ref> The statement was issued in response to a [[United States Government Accountability Office]] report that asserts: \"Antibiotic use in food animals contributes to the emergence of resistant bacteria that may affect humans\".<ref name=\"gao-2011\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gao.gov/products/GAO-11-801|title=Antibiotic Resistance: Agencies Have Made Limited Progress Addressing Antibiotic Use in Animals|last1=Office|first1=U. S. Government Accountability|date=7 September 2011|publisher=[[Government Accountability Office|U.S. Government Accountability Office]]|quote=Antibiotics have saved millions of lives, but antibiotic use in food animals contributes to the emergence of resistant bacteria that may affect humans.|issue=GAO-11-801}}</ref>\n\nIt is difficult to set up a comprehensive surveillance system for measuring rates of change in antibiotic resistance.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Bax|first1=R.|last2=Bywater|first2=R.|last3=Cornaglia|first3=G.|last4=Goossens|first4=H.|last5=Hunter|first5=P.|last6=Isham|first6=V.|last7=Jarlier|first7=V.|last8=Jones|first8=R.|last9=Phillips|first9=I.|last10=Sahm|first10=D.|last11=Senn|first11=S.|date=June 2001|title=Surveillance of antimicrobial resistance \u2014 what, how and whither?|journal=Clinical Microbiology and Infection|volume=7|issue=6|pages=316\u2013325|doi=10.1046/j.1198-743x.2001.00239.x|pmid=11442565|doi-access=free|last13=Taylor|first13=D.|last14=White|first14=A.|first12=M.|last12=Struelens}}</ref> The US [[Government Accountability Office]] published a report in 2011 stating that government and commercial agencies had not been collecting sufficient data to make a decision about best practices.<ref>{{Cite report|url=https://www.gao.gov/products/GAO-11-801|title=Agencies Have Made Limited Progress Addressing Antibiotic Use in Animals|last=U.S. Government Accountability Office|first=|date=7 September 2011|issue=GAO-11-801|doi=|volume=|pmid=|author-link=U.S. Government Accountability Office|accessdate=27 August 2013}}</ref> There is also no regulatory agency in the United States that systematically collects detailed data on antibiotic use in humans and animals, which means it is not clear which antibiotics are prescribed for which purpose and at what time. While this may be lacking at a regulatory level, the US poultry meat sector has been working on the issue of data collection itself, and has now reported comparative data showing significant reductions in antibiotic use.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/news-perspective/2019/08/us-poultry-data-show-big-reductions-key-antibiotics|title=US poultry data show big reductions in key antibiotics|last=CIDRAP|date=August 2019|website=Center for Infectious Disease Research and Policy, University of Minnesota|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref> Among the highlights in the report<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mindwalkconsultinggroup.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/Poultry_On-Farm_Antimicrobial_Use_Report_2013-2017.pdf|title=Estimates of On-Farm Antimicrobial Usage in Broiler Chicken and Turkey Production in the United States, 2013 \u2013 2017|last=Singer|first=Randall S|last2=Porter|first2=Leah|date=August 2019|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref> was a 95% decrease in in-feed tetracycline use in broiler chicks from 2013 to 2017, a 67% reduction in in-feed use of tetracycline in turkeys, and a 42% drop in hatchery use of gentamicin in turkey poults. This is an encouraging sign; the 53% overall reduction in antibiotic use seen in the UK between 2013 and 2018<ref name=\":15\" /><ref name=\":13\" /> was initiated from a voluntary stewardship programme developed by the UK poultry meat sector.<ref name=\":16\" />\n\n== Research into alternatives ==\nIncreasing concern due to the emergence of antibiotic-resistant bacteria has led researchers to look for alternatives to using antibiotics in livestock.<ref name=Allen>{{cite journal | author = Allen H. K. | author2=Trachsel J. | author3= Looft T. | author4= Casey T. A. | year = 2014 | title = Finding alternatives to antibiotics | journal = Annals of the New York Academy of Sciences | volume = 1323 | issue = 1| pages = 91\u2013100 | pmid = 24953233 | doi=10.1111/nyas.12468| bibcode=2014NYASA1323...91A}}</ref>\n\n[[Probiotics]], cultures of a single bacteria strain or mixture of different strains, are being studied in livestock as a production enhancer.<ref>{{cite journal | author = Hume M. E. | year = 2011 | title = Historic perspective: Prebiotics, probiotics, and other alternatives to antibiotics | url = http://naldc.nal.usda.gov/download/57525/PDF | journal = Poultry Science | volume = 90 | issue = 11| pages = 2663\u20139 | pmid = 22010256 | doi=10.3382/ps.2010-01030}}</ref>\n\n[[Prebiotics]] are non-digestible carbohydrates. The carbohydrates are mainly made up of oligosaccharides which are short chains of monosaccharides. The two most commonly studied prebiotics are fructooligosaccharides (FOS) and mannanoligosaccharides (MOS). FOS has been studied for use in chicken feed. MOS works as a competitive binding site, as bacteria bind to it rather than the intestine and are carried out.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Griggs |first1=J.P. |last2=Jacob |first2=J.P. |title=Alternatives to Antibiotics for Organic Poultry Production |journal=Journal of Applied Poultry Research |date=December 2005 |volume=14 |issue=4 |pages=750\u2013756 |doi=10.1093/japr/14.4.750}}</ref>\n\n[[Bacteriophages]] are able to infect most bacteria and are easily found in most environments colonized by bacteria, and have been studied as well.<ref name=Allen/>\n\nIn another study it was found that using probiotics, competitive exclusion, enzymes, immunomodulators and organic acids prevents the spread of bacteria and can all be used in place of antibiotics.<ref>Doyle, M.E. 2001: Alternatives to Antibiotic Use for Growth Promotion in Animal Husbandry. Food Research Institute, University of Wisconsin-Madison.</ref> Another research team was able to use bacteriocins, antimicrobial peptides and bacteriophages in the control of bacterial infections.<ref>{{cite journal | author = Joerger R.D. | year = 2003 | title = Alternatives to antibiotics: bacteriocins, antimicrobial peptides and bacteriophages | url = | journal = Poultry Science | volume = 82 | issue = 4| pages = 640\u2013647 | doi=10.1093/ps/82.4.640| pmid = 12710486}}</ref> While further research is needed in this field, alternative methods have been identified in effectively controlling bacterial infections in animals. All of the alternative methods listed pose no known threat to human health and all can lead the elimination of antibiotics in factory farms. With further research it is highly likely that a cost-effective and health-effective alternative could and will be found.\n\nOther alternatives include preventative approaches to keep the animals healthier and so reduce the need for antibiotics. These include improving the living conditions for animals, stimulating natural immunity through better nutrition, increasing biosecurity, implementing better management and hygiene practices, and ensuring better use of vaccination.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Antibiotic]]\n*[[Antibiotic misuse]]\n*[[Antimicrobial resistance]]\n*[[Antibiotic prophylaxis]] \n*[[List of antibiotic-resistant bacteria]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite web | last = Anomaly| first = Jonathan | url = https://dukespace.lib.duke.edu/dspace/bitstream/handle/10161/9733/Anomaly%20-%20Factory%20Farming.pdf%3bsequence=1 | title = What's Wrong with Factory Farming | publisher = Public Health Ethics | date = 2015}}\n* {{cite web | last = O'Neill| first = Jim | url = https://amr-review.org/sites/default/files/Antimicrobials%20in%20agriculture%20and%20the%20environment%20-%20Reducing%20unnecessary%20use%20and%20waste.pdf | title = Antimicrobials in Agriculture and the Environment | publisher = The Review on Antimicrobial Resistance | date = 2015}}\n*O'Neill, Jim (2016). [https://amr-review.org/sites/default/files/160525_Final%20paper_with%20cover.pdf \"Tackling Drug Resistance Globally: Final report and recommendations\"] (PDF)\n* [https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/shows/meat/safe/overview.html PBS report on antibiotics in livestock production]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=C_pr1T33-EM Fix Food, Fix Antibiotics], a 90-second video explaining the problem of antibiotic resistance and campaigning for action\n* [http://www.pewhealth.org/other-resource/record-high-antibiotic-sales-for-meat-and-poultry-production-85899449119 Pew Trust campaign] for restricting antibiotic use\n* [http://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/pkg/CHRG-111hhrg77921/pdf/CHRG-111hhrg77921.pdf Antibiotic Resistance and the Use of Antibiotics in Animal Agriculture: Hearing before the Subcommittee on Health of the Committee on Energy and Commerce, House of Representatives, One Hundred Eleventh Congress, Second Session, July 14, 2010]\n* [http://www.indiaenvironmentportal.org.in/search/?q=antibiotics Resources on antibiotic use and resistance]\n*[http://.farmantibiotics.org Farm Antibiotics] information website\n\n{{Antibiotics social and layman issues}}\n\n[[Category:Antibiotic resistance]]\n[[Category:Evolutionary biology]]\n[[Category:Food politics]]\n[[Category:Health disasters]]\n[[Category:Livestock]]\n[[Category:Meat industry]]\n[[Category:Pharmaceuticals policy]]\n[[Category:Veterinary medicine]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n'''Antibiotic use in livestock''' is the use of [[antibiotics]] for any purpose in the [[animal husbandry|husbandry]] of [[livestock]], which includes treatment when ill ([https://www.medicinenet.com/script/main/art.asp?articlekey=18811 therapeutic]), treatment of a group of animals when at least one is diagnosed with clinical infection (metaphylaxis<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=Bousquet-Melou|first=Alain|last2=Ferran|first2=Aude|last3=Toutain|first3=Pierre-Louis|date=May 2010|title=Prophylaxis & Metaphylaxis in Veterinary Antimicrobial Therapy|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/281440602|journal=Conference: 5TH International Conference on Antimicrobial Agents in Veterinary Medicine (AAVM)At: Tel Aviv, Israel|volume=|pages=|via=ResearchGate}}</ref>), and [[preventive healthcare|preventative treatment (prophylaxis)]]. Antibiotics are an important tool to treat animal as well as human disease, safeguard animal health and welfare, and support food safety.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.bva.co.uk/media/1161/bva-policy-position-on-the-responsible-use-of-antimicrobials-in-food-producing-animals-1.pdf|title= BVA policy position on the responsible use of antimicrobials in food producing animals|last=British Veterinary Association, London |date=May 2019|accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref> However, used irresponsibly, this may also have impacts on human, animal and environmental health in a [[One Health]] context, as up to 90% of the antibiotic parent compounds can be directly excreted and this can lead to antibiotic resistance developing in the environment.<ref name=\"Mass\u00e9 et al 2004\">{{cite journal |last1=Mass\u00e9 |first1=Daniel |last2=Saady |first2=Noori |last3=Gilbert |first3=Yan |title=Potential of Biological Processes to Eliminate Antibiotics in Livestock Manure: An Overview |journal=Animals |date=4 April 2014 |volume=4 |issue=2 |pages=146\u2013163 |doi=10.3390/ani4020146 |pmid=26480034 |pmc=4494381 |url=https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/fb5a763e94860b1eab74b3661cde875127196b76}}</ref><ref name=\"Sarmah et al 2006\">{{cite journal |last1=Sarmah |first1=Ajit K. |last2=Meyer |first2=Michael T. |last3=Boxall |first3=Alistair B. A. |title=A global perspective on the use, sales, exposure pathways, occurrence, fate and effects of veterinary antibiotics (VAs) in the environment |journal=Chemosphere |date=1 October 2006 |volume=65 |issue=5 |pages=725\u2013759 |doi=10.1016/j.chemosphere.2006.03.026 |pmid=16677683 |bibcode=2006Chmsp..65..725S}}</ref><ref name=\"Kumar et al 2005\">{{cite journal |last1=Kumar |first1=Kuldip |last2=C. Gupta |first2=Satish |last3=Chander |first3=Yogesh |last4=Singh |first4=Ashok K. |title=Antibiotic Use in Agriculture and Its Impact on the Terrestrial Environment |journal=Advances in Agronomy |date=1 January 2005 |volume=87 |pages=1\u201354 |doi=10.1016/S0065-2113(05)87001-4 |isbn=9780120007851}}</ref><ref name=\"VanBoeckel2017\">{{cite journal |last1=Boeckel |first1=Thomas P. Van |last2=Glennon |first2=Emma E. |last3=Chen |first3=Dora |last4=Gilbert |first4=Marius |last5=Robinson |first5=Timothy P. |last6=Grenfell |first6=Bryan T. |last7=Levin |first7=Simon A. |last8=Bonhoeffer |first8=Sebastian |last9=Laxminarayan |first9=Ramanan |title=Reducing antimicrobial use in food animals |journal=Science |date=29 September 2017 |volume=357 |issue=6358 |pages=1350\u20131352 |doi=10.1126/science.aao1495 |pmid=28963240 |pmc=6510296 |bibcode=2017Sci...357.1350V |url=https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/5c647b3baf054be90bb5a0fb4cef016b71748723}}</ref> [[File:Ar-infographic-950px.jpg|thumb|A [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]] infographic on the spread of antibiotic-resistant bacteria from farm animals]] While levels of use vary dramatically from country to country, for example some Northern European countries use very low quantities to treat animals compared with humans,<ref name=ESVACreport2019>{{cite web|url= https://www.ema.europa.eu/en/documents/report/sales-veterinary-antimicrobial-agents-31-european-countries-2017_en.pdf|title= Sales of veterinary antimicrobial agents in 31 European countries in 2017: Trends from 2010 to 2017 |last=ESVAC (European Medicines Agency) |date=October 2019|accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref> worldwide an estimated 73% of [[antimicrobial]]s (mainly antibiotics) are consumed by farm animals.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Boeckel|first=Thomas P. Van|last2=Pires|first2=Jo\u00e3o|last3=Silvester|first3=Reshma|last4=Zhao|first4=Cheng|last5=Song|first5=Julia|last6=Criscuolo|first6=Nicola G.|last7=Gilbert|first7=Marius|last8=Bonhoeffer|first8=Sebastian|last9=Laxminarayan|first9=Ramanan|date=20 September 2019|title=Global trends in antimicrobial resistance in animals in low- and middle-income countries|journal=Science|language=en|volume=365|issue=6459|pages=eaaw1944|doi=10.1126/science.aaw1944|issn=0036-8075|pmid=31604207|url=https://dipot.ulb.ac.be/dspace/bitstream/2013/296867/3/vanboeckel.pdf}}</ref> Furthermore, a 2015 study also estimates that global agricultural antibiotic usage will increase by 67% from 2010 to 2030, mainly from increases in use in developing [[BRIC]] countries.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/d04c/774cc6a90f9da0072f7fa81450373bc98bd4.pdf |title=Global trends in antimicrobial use in food animals}}</ref> This is a matter of concern as [[antibiotic resistance]] is considered to be a serious threat to human and animal welfare in the future, and growing levels of antibiotics or antibiotic-resistant bacteria in the environment could increase the numbers of drug-resistant infections in both.<ref name=pmid22048738>{{cite journal |last1=Bush |first1=Karen |last2=Courvalin |first2=Patrice |last3=Dantas |first3=Gautam |last4=Davies |first4=Julian |last5=Eisenstein |first5=Barry |last6=Huovinen |first6=Pentti |last7=Jacoby |first7=George A. |last8=Kishony |first8=Roy |last9=Kreiswirth |first9=Barry N. |last10=Kutter |first10=Elizabeth |last11=Lerner |first11=Stephen A. |last12=Levy |first12=Stuart |last13=Lewis |first13=Kim |last14=Lomovskaya |first14=Olga |last15=Miller |first15=Jeffrey H. |last16=Mobashery |first16=Shahriar |last17=Piddock |first17=Laura J. V. |last18=Projan |first18=Steven |last19=Thomas |first19=Christopher M. |last20=Tomasz |first20=Alexander |last21=Tulkens |first21=Paul M. |last22=Walsh |first22=Timothy R. |last23=Watson |first23=James D. |last24=Witkowski |first24=Jan |last25=Witte |first25=Wolfgang |last26=Wright |first26=Gerry |last27=Yeh |first27=Pamela |last28=Zgurskaya |first28=Helen I. |title=Tackling antibiotic resistance |journal=Nature Reviews Microbiology |date=2 November 2011 |volume=9 |issue=12 |pages=894\u2013896 |doi=10.1038/nrmicro2693 |pmid=22048738 |pmc=4206945 |url=https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/2a244a95db85ac10c1a67791ef1b8d5890574285}}</ref> Infectious diseases are the third leading cause of death in Europe and a future without effective antibiotics would fundamentally change the way modern human as well as veterinary medicine is practised.<ref name=pmid22048738/><ref name=\"Tang et al\">{{cite journal| last1=Tang |first1=Karen L |last2=Caffrey |first2=Niamh P |last3=N\u00f3brega |first3=Diego| last4=Cork |first4=Susan C |last5=Ronksley |first5=Paul C |last6=Barkema |first6=Herman W |last7=Polachek |first7=Alicia J |last8=Ganshorn |first8=Heather |last9=Sharma |first9=Nishan |last10=Kellner |first10=James D |last11=Ghali |first11=William A|title=Restricting the use of antibiotics in food-producing animals and its associations with antibiotic resistance in food-producing animals and human beings: a systematic review and meta-analysis|journal=The Lancet Planetary Health |date= November 2017|volume=1|issue=8|pages=e316\u2013e327|doi=10.1016/S2542-5196(17)30141-9|pmid=29387833 |pmc=5785333}}</ref><ref name=pmid25918440/> However, legislation and other curbs on antibiotic use in farm animals are now being introduced across the globe.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.ema.europa.eu/en/veterinary-regulatory/overview/implementation-new-veterinary-medicines-regulation|title= Implementation of the new Veterinary Medicines Regulation in the EU|last=European Medicines Agency}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.oecd.org/officialdocuments/publicdisplaydocumentpdf/?cote=TAD/CA/APM/WP(2018)19/FINAL&docLanguage=En|title= Working Party on Agricultural Policies and Markets: Antibiotic Use and Antibiotic Resistance in Food Producing Animals in China|last=OECD, Paris|date=May 2019| accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.fda.gov/animal-veterinary/antimicrobial-resistance/timeline-fda-action-antimicrobial-resistance|title= Timeline of FDA Action on Antimicrobial Resistance|last=US Food & Drug Administration |date=July 2019| accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref> In 2017, the [[World Health Organization]] strongly suggested reducing antibiotic use in animals used in the food industry.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web|url=https://apps.who.int/iris/bitstream/handle/10665/258970/9789241550130-eng.pdf?sequence=1 |title=WHO guidelines on use of medically important antimicrobials in food-producing animals}}</ref> The use of antibiotics for growth promotion purposes was banned in the European Union from 2006,<ref name=\":7\">{{cite web |url=https://ec.europa.eu/commission/presscorner/detail/en/IP_05_1687 |title=Ban on antibiotics as growth promoters in animal feed enters into effect|last=European Commission, Brussels |date=December 2005}}</ref> and the use of sub-therapeutic doses of medically important antibiotics in [[animal feed]] and water<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{Cite journal|url=https://www.fda.gov/downloads/AnimalVeterinary/GuidanceComplianceEnforcement/GuidanceforIndustry/UCM216936.pdf|title=The Judicious Use of Medically Important Antimicrobial Drugs in Food-Producing Animals|last=|first=|date=2012|journal=Guidance for Industry|pages=|via=|issue=#209}}</ref> to promote growth and improve [[feed conversion ratio|feed efficiency]] became illegal in the United States on 1 January 2017, through legislative change enacted by the Food and Drug Administration (FDA), which sought voluntary compliance from drug manufacturers to re-label their antibiotics.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.avma.org/KB/Resources/Pages/VFD123.aspx|title=Veterinary Feed Directive (VFD) Basics|website=AVMA|accessdate=14 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170415174849/https://www.avma.org/KB/Resources/Pages/VFD123.aspx|archive-date=15 April 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://beef.unl.edu/veterinary-feed-directive-questions-and-answers|title=Veterinary Feed Directive Questions and Answers|last=University of Nebraska, Lincoln|date=October 2015|website=UNL Beef|accessdate=14 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe 2018 book 'Pharming animals: a global history of antibiotics in food production (1935\u20132017)'<ref name=\"Kirchhelle C\">{{cite journal| last1=Kirchelle |first1=Claas|title= Pharming animals: a global history of antibiotics in food production (1935\u20132017) |journal= Palgrave Communications |date= 7 August 2018|volume=4|issue= |doi= 10.1057/s41599-018-0152-2}}</ref> summarises the central role antibiotics have played in agriculture: \"Since their advent during the 1930s, antibiotics have not only had a dramatic impact on human medicine, but also on food production. On farms, whaling and fishing fleets as well as in processing plants and aquaculture operations, antibiotics were used to treat and prevent disease, increase feed conversion, and preserve food. Their rapid diffusion into nearly all areas of food production and processing was initially viewed as a story of progress on both sides of the Iron Curtain.\"\n\nTo retrace, while natural antibiotics or antibacterials were known to ancient man, [[antibiotic]]<nowiki/>s as we know them came to the fore during World War II to help treat war time casualties. It is recorded that antibiotics were first used in farming towards the end of the war, in the form of intra-mammary penicillin preparations to treat bovine mastitis.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite journal|last=Gustafson|first=R. H.|last2=Bowen|first2=R. E.|date=1997|title=Antibiotic use in animal agriculture|journal=Journal of Applied Microbiology|language=en|volume=83|issue=5|pages=531\u2013541|doi=10.1046/j.1365-2672.1997.00280.x|pmid=9418018|issn=1365-2672}}</ref> At that time, milk was seen as an agricultural product which was highly susceptible to bacterial contamination, and farmers welcomed the opportunity to 'purify' their produce for the safety of consumers; it was only later that concern switched from the bacterial load of the product to the residues that might result from untimely or unregulated treatment.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=SMITH-HOWARD|first=KENDRA|date=2010|title=Antibiotics and Agricultural Change: Purifying Milk and Protecting Health in the Postwar Era|journal=Agricultural History|volume=84|issue=3|pages=327\u2013351|doi=10.3098/ah.2010.84.3.327|jstor=27868996|issn=0002-1482}}</ref>\n\nThe use of antibiotics to treat and prevent disease has followed a similar path to that used in human medicine in terms of [https://www.medicinenet.com/script/main/art.asp?articlekey=18811 therapeutic] and metaphylactic<ref name=\":4\" /> applications to treat and manage disease and improve population health, and the application of case-by-case strategic preventative treatments when animals are deemed at particular risk. However, in the late 1940s, studies examining the supplementation of B12 in chicks' diets found that B12 produced from the fermentation of ''Streptomyces aureofaciens'', an antibiotic for use in human medicine, produced a better weight gain for chicks than B12 supplied from other sources, and a reduced amount of feed to bring the birds to market weight.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stokstad|first=ELR|last2=Jukes|first2=TH|last3=Pierce|first3=J|last4=Page|first4=AC Jnr|last5=Franklin|first5=AL|date=1949|title=The multiple nature of the animal protein factor|url=https://www.cabdirect.org/cabdirect/abstract/19491403454|journal=Journal of Biological Chemistry|volume=180|pages=647\u2013654|pmid=18135798|via=CAB Direct}}</ref> Further studies on other livestock species showed a similar improved growth and feed efficiency effect with the result that as the cost of antibiotics came down, they were increasingly included at low ('[https://www.collinsdictionary.com/dictionary/english/subtherapeutic sub-therapeutic')] levels in livestock feed as a means of increasing production of affordable animal protein to meet the needs of a rapidly-expanding post-war population.<ref name=\":8\" /> This development coincided with an increase in the scale of individual farms and the level of confinement of the animals on them, and so routine preventative antibiotic treatments became the most cost-effective means of treating the anticipated disease that could sometimes arise as a result.<ref name=\":8\" /> As a result, veterinary medicine increasingly embraced the therapeutic, metaphylactic and strategic preventative use of antibiotics to treat disease. The routine use of antibiotics for growth stimulation and disease prevention also grew.\n\n==Growth stimulation==\nIn 1910 in the United States, a meat shortage resulted in protests and boycotts.<ref name=\"Ogle2013\">{{cite web|url=http://blogs.scientificamerican.com/guest-blog/2013/09/03/riots-rage-and-resistance-a-brief-history-of-how-antibiotics-arrived-on-the-farm/|title=Riots, Rage and Resistance: A Brief History of How Antibiotics Arrived on the Farm|last=Ogle|first=Maureen|date=3 September 2013|work=[[Scientific American]]|accessdate=5 November 2013}}\n</ref><ref>Reported locally in these:\n*\"To Become Vegetarians\", Mansfield (O.) ''News'', 17 January 1910, p2\n*\"150,000 at Cleveland Stop the Use of Meat\" Syracuse ''Herald-Journal'', 25 January 1910, p1\n*\"Boycott on Meat is Rapidly Spreading; Men Who Are Blamed For High Price\", Atlanta ''Constitution'', 25 January 1910, p1</ref> After this and other shortages, the public demanded government research into stabilization of food supplies.<ref name=\"Ogle2013\"/> Since the 1900s, livestock production on United States farms has had to rear larger quantities of animals over a short period of time to meet new consumer demands. It was discovered in the 1940s that feeding subtherapeutic levels of antibiotics improved feed efficiency and accelerated animal growth.<ref>{{cite book |doi=10.1109/CONIIN.2018.8489822 |chapter=A review of hot and sweet pepper added in animal nutrition: Alternative against the use of antibiotics |title=2018 XIV International Engineering Congress (CONIIN) |pages=1\u20136 |year=2018 |last1=Flores-Tejeida |first1=L.B |last2=Soto-Zarazua |first2=G.M |last3=Guevara-Gonzalez |first3=R.G |last4=Escamilla-Garcia |first4=A. |last5=Gomez-Soto |first5=J.G |isbn=978-1-5386-7018-7}}</ref> Following this discovery, [[American Cyanamid]] published research establishing the practice of using antibiotic growth promoters.<ref name=\"Ogle2013\"/> By 2001, this practice had grown so much that a report by the [[Union of Concerned Scientists]] found that nearly 90% of the total use of antimicrobials in the United States was for non-therapeutic purposes in agricultural production.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hogging It!: Estimates of Antimicrobial Abuse in Livestock |year=2001|publisher=Union of Concerned Scientists|url=https://www.ucsusa.org/food_and_agriculture/our-failing-food-system/industrial-agriculture/hogging-it-estimates-of.html#.Wycey1MvzEY}}</ref>\nCertain antibiotics, when given in low, subtherapeutic doses, are known to improve [[feed conversion efficiency]] (more output, such as muscle or milk, for a given amount of feed) and may promote greater growth, most likely by affecting [[gut flora]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.merckvetmanual.com/pharmacology/growth-promotants-and-production-enhancers/antimicrobial-feed-additives|title=Antimicrobial Feed Additives|last=Reinhardt|first=Christopher|work=Merck Veterinary Manual}}</ref> The drugs listed below can be used to increase feed conversion ratio and weight gain, but are not legally allowed to be used for such purposes any longer in the United States. Some drugs listed below are [[ionophore]]s, which are [[coccidiostat]]s and not classified as antibiotics in many countries; they have not been shown to increase risk of antibiotic-resistant infections in humans.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"5\" style=\"background-color: #CCEEEE;\" | Antibiotic Growth Promoters historically used in Livestock Production in some countries\n|-\n! Drug\n! Class\n! Livestock\n|-\n|[[Bacitracin]]\n|[[Peptide]]\n| Beef cattle, chickens, swine, and turkeys; promotes egg production in chickens<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"MerckReinhardt\"/>\n|-\n|[[Bambermycin]]\n|\n|Beef cattle, chickens, swine, and turkeys.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|title = Altered egos: antibiotic effects on food animal microbiomes|journal = Annual Review of Microbiology|date = 1 January 2014|issn = 1545-3251|pmid = 25002091|pages = 297\u2013315|volume = 68|doi = 10.1146/annurev-micro-091213-113052|first = Heather K.|last = Allen|first2 = Thad B.|last2 = Stanton|url = https://zenodo.org/record/1235023}}</ref><ref name=\"MerckReinhardt\">{{Citation |last=Reinhardt |first=Christopher D. |year=2012 |title=Merck Veterinary Manual | chapter=Antimicrobial Feed Additives | chapter-url=http://www.merckmanuals.com/vet/pharmacology/growth_promotants_and_production_enhancers/antimicrobial_feed_additives.html |publisher=[[Merck & Co.]] and [[Merial]] |location= | editor1-last=Aiello | editor1-first =Susan E.| editor2-last=Moses | editor2-first =Michael A. |page= |title-link=Merck Veterinary Manual}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Carbadox]]\n|\n|Swine<ref name=\":0\" />\n|-\n|[[Laidlomycin]]\n|\n|Beef cattle<ref name=\":0\" />\n|-\n|[[Lasalocid]]\n|[[Ionophore]]\n|Beef cattle<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"MerckReinhardt\"/>\n|-\n|[[Lincomycin]]\n|\n|Chickens and swine<ref name=\":0\" />\n|-\n|[[Monensin]]\n|Ionophore\n|Beef cattle and sheep; promotes milk production in dairy cows<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"MerckReinhardt\"/>\n|-\n|[[Neomycin]]/ Oxytetracycline\n|\n|Beef cattle, chickens, swine, and turkeys<ref name=\":0\" />\n|-\n|[[Penicillin]]\n|\n|Chickens, swine, and turkeys<ref name=\":0\" />\n|-\n|[[Roxarsone]]\n|\n|Chickens and turkeys<ref name=\":0\" />\n|-\n|[[Salinomycin]]\n|Ionophore\n|\n|-\n|[[Tylosin]]\n|\n|Chickens and swine<ref name=\":0\" />\n|-\n|[[Virginiamycin]]\n|Peptide\n|Beef cattle, chickens, swine, turkeys<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"MerckReinhardt\"/>\n|}\nThe practice of using antibiotics for growth stimulation has been deemed problematic for these following reasons:<ref name=\"Silbergeld\">{{Cite journal|last1=Silbergeld|first1=E. K.|last2=Graham|first2=J.|last3=Price|first3=L. B.|year=2008|title=Industrial Food Animal Production, Antimicrobial Resistance, and Human Health|url=|journal=Annual Review of Public Health|volume=29|pages=151\u2013169|doi=10.1146/annurev.publhealth.29.020907.090904|pmc=|pmid=18348709|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\n*It is the largest use of antimicrobials worldwide\n*Subtherapeutic use of antibiotics results in bacterial resistance\n*Every important class of antibiotics are being used in this way, making every class less effective\n*The bacteria being changed harm humans\n\n==Antibiotic resistance==\n\n=== Mechanisms for the development of resistance ===\nAntibiotic resistance - often referred to as [[antimicrobial resistance]] (AMR) although this term covers anti-virals, anti-fungals and other products - can occur when antibiotics are present in concentrations too low to inhibit bacterial growth, triggering cellular responses in the bacteria that allow them to survive. These bacteria can then reproduce and spread their antibiotic-resistant genes to other generations, increasing their prevalence and leading to infections that cannot be healed by antibiotics.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ben|first=Yujie|last2=Fu|first2=Caixia|last3=Hu|first3=Min|last4=Liu|first4=Lei|last5=Wong|first5=Ming Hung|last6=Zheng|first6=Chunmiao|date=February 2019|title=Human health risk assessment of antibiotic resistance associated with antibiotic residues in the environment: A review|journal=Environmental Research|volume=169|pages=483\u2013493|doi=10.1016/j.envres.2018.11.040|issn=1096-0953|pmid=30530088|bibcode=2019ER....169..483B|url=https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/c46b56253afd303cb0f561aedb3113573cd129e5}}</ref> This is a growing matter of concern as antibiotic resistance is considered to be a serious future threat to human welfare.<ref name=pmid22048738/> Infectious diseases are the third leading cause of death in Europe and a future without effective antibiotics would fundamentally change the way modern medicine is practised.<ref name=pmid22048738/><ref name=pmid25918440>{{cite journal |last1=Shallcross |first1=Laura J. |last2=Howard |first2=Simon J. |last3=Fowler |first3=Tom |last4=Davies |first4=Sally C. |title=Tackling the threat of antimicrobial resistance: from policy to sustainable action |journal=Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society B: Biological Sciences |date=5 June 2015 |volume=370 |issue=1670 |pages=20140082 |doi=10.1098/rstb.2014.0082 |pmid=25918440 |pmc=4424432 |url=https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/89772d0ac83159bdc04737d8b8db9cc099b2b4f9}}</ref> \n[[File:Hartsock Genetic Engineering Bacteria Cell Division.png|thumb|Bacterial conjugation|333x333px]]\nBacteria can alter their genetic inheritance through two main ways, either by mutating their genetic material or acquiring a new one from other bacteria. The latter being the most important for causing antibiotic-resistant bacteria strains in animals and humans. One of the methods bacteria can obtain new genes is through a process called conjugation which deals with transferring genes using plasmids. These conjugative plasmids carry a number of genes that can be assembled and rearranged, which could then enable bacteria to exchange beneficial genes among themselves ensuring their survival against antibiotics and rendering them ineffective to treat dangerous diseases in humans, resulting into multi-drug resistant organisms.<ref>Bennett P. M. (2008). Plasmid encoded antibiotic resistance: acquisition and transfer of antibiotic resistance genes in bacteria. British journal of pharmacology, 153 Suppl 1(Suppl 1), S347-57.</ref>\n\nHowever, it is important to note that antibiotic resistance also occurs naturally, as it is a bacterium's response to any threat. As a result, antibiotic-resistant bacteria have been found in pristine environments unrelated to human activity such as in the frozen and uncovered remains of woolly mammoths,<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Perry |first1=Julie |last2=Waglechner |first2=Nicholas |last3=Wright |first3=Gerard |title=The Prehistory of Antibiotic Resistance |journal=Cold Springs Harbor Perspectives in Medicine |date=June 2016 |volume=6 |issue=6 |page=a025197 |doi=10.1101/cshperspect.a025197 |pmid=27252395 |pmc=4888810}}</ref> in the polar ice caps<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Nesme |first1=Joseph |last2=Cecillon |first2=Sebastien |last3=Delmont |first3=Tom |last4=Monier |first4=Jean-Michel |last5=Vogel |first5=Timothy |last6=Simonet |first6=Pascal |title=Large-Scale Metagenomic-Based Study of Antibiotic Resistance in the Environment |journal=Current Biology |date=May 2014 |volume=24 |issue=10 |pages=1096\u2013100 |doi=10.1016/j.cub.2014.03.036 |pmid=24814145}}</ref> and in isolated caves deep underground.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Bhullar |first1=K |last2=Waglechner |first2=N |last3=Pawlowski |first3=A |last4=Koteva |first4=K |last5=Banks |first5=ED |last6=Johnston |first6=MD |last7=Barton |first7=HA |last8=Wright |first8=GD |title=Antibiotic resistance is prevalent in an isolated cave microbiome |journal=PLOS One |date=2012 |volume=7 |issue=4 |page=e34953 |doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0034953 |pmid=22509370 |pmc=3324550 |bibcode=2012PLoSO...734953B}}</ref>\n\n=== High priority antibiotics ===\nThe [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) published a revised list in 2019 of 'Critically Important Antimicrobials for Human Medicine, 6th revision'<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apps.who.int/iris/bitstream/handle/10665/312266/9789241515528-eng.pdf?ua=1|title=Critically Important Antimicrobials for Human Medicine, 6th Revision|last=World Health Organization|date=2018|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref> with the intent that it be used \"as a reference to help formulate and prioritise risk assessment and risk management strategies for containing antimicrobial resistance due to human and non-human antimicrobial use to help preserve the effectiveness of currently available antimicrobials. It lists its Highest Priority Critically Important Antimicrobials as: 3rd, 4th and 5th generation cephalosporins, glycopeptides, macrolides and ketolides, polymyxins including colistin, and quinolones including fluoroqinolones.\n\nThe [[European Medicines Agency]] (EMA) Antimicrobial Advice Ad-Hoc Expert Group (AMEG) also published an updated categorisation<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ema.europa.eu/en/veterinary-regulatory/overview/antimicrobial-resistance/advice-impacts-using-antimicrobials-animals|title=Advice on impacts of using antimicrobials in animals|last=European Medicines Agency|date=January 2020|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref> of different antibiotics in veterinary medicine by the antibiotic resistance risk to humans of using them alongside the need to treat disease in animals for health and welfare reasons. The categorisation specifically focuses on the situation in Europe. Category A (\u2018Avoid\u2019) antibiotics are designated as \u2018not appropriate for use in food producing animals\u2019. Category B (\u2018Restrict\u2019) products, also known as Highest Priority Critically Important Antibiotics, are only to be used as a last resort. These include quinolones (such as fluoroquinolones), 3rd and 4th generation cephalosporins, and polymyxins, including colistin. A new intermediate Category C (\u2018Caution\u2019) has been created for antibiotics which should be used when there is no available product in Category D (\u2018Prudence\u2019) that would be clinically effective. Category C includes macrolides and aminoglycosides, with the exception of spectinomycin, which remains in Category D.\n\nEvidence for the transfer of [[macrolide]]-resistant microorganisms from animals to humans has been scant,<ref name=\"pmid15151237\">{{cite journal|last1=Hurd|first1=H. Scott|last2=Doores|first2=Stephanie|last3=Hayes|first3=Dermot|last4=Mathew|first4=Alan|last5=Maurer|first5=John|last6=Silley|first6=Peter|last7=Singer|first7=Randall S.|last8=Jones|first8=Ronald N.|date=1 May 2004|title=Public Health Consequences of Macrolide Use in Food Animals: A Deterministic Risk Assessment|journal=Journal of Food Protection|volume=67|issue=5|pages=980\u2013992|doi=10.4315/0362-028X-67.5.980|issn=0362-028X|pmid=15151237}}</ref><ref name=\"pmid18643826\">{{cite journal|last1=Hurd|first1=H. Scott|last2=Malladi|first2=Sasidhar|date=June 2008|title=A stochastic assessment of the public health risks of the use of macrolide antibiotics in food animals|url=https://www.sandersonfarms.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/PDF-5-Hurd_et_al-2008-Risk_Analysis.pdf|journal=Risk Analysis|volume=28|issue=3|pages=695\u2013710|doi=10.1111/j.1539-6924.2008.01054.x|issn=1539-6924|pmid=18643826|ref=harv}}</ref> and most evidence shows that pathogens of concern in human populations originated in humans and are maintained there, with rare cases of transference to humans. Macrolides are also extremely useful in the effective treatment of some ''Mycoplasma'' species in poultry, ''Lawsonia'' in pigs, respiratory tract infections in cattle and in some circumstances, lameness in sheep.<ref name=\":11\" />\n\n=== Sources of antibiotic resistance ===\n\n==== Summary ====\nWhile the human medical use of antibiotics is the main source of antibiotic resistant infections in humans,<ref>{{cite web |last1=UK Government |title=UK 5 Year Antimicrobial Resistance Strategy 2013 |date=10 September 2013 |page=Paragraph 2.1 |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/uk-5-year-antimicrobial-resistance-strategy-2013-to-2018 |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=The European Medicines Agency Committee for Medicinal Products for Veterinary Use |title=CVMP Strategy on Antimicrobials 2016-2020 |date=6 October 2016 |page=Page 4 |url=https://www.ema.europa.eu/en/documents/scientific-guideline/cvmp-strategy-antimicrobials-2016-2020_en.pdf |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Shea K.M. 2003\">{{cite journal|last=Shea|first=Katherine M.|date=1 July 2003|title=Antibiotic Resistance: What Is the Impact of Agricultural Uses of Antibiotics on Children's Health?|url=http://pediatrics.aappublications.org/content/112/Supplement_1/253|journal=Pediatrics|volume=112|issue=Supplement 1|pages=253\u2013258|issn=0031-4005|pmid=12837918|via=|doi-access=}}</ref> it is known that humans can acquire antibiotic resistance genes from a variety of animal sources, including farm animals, pets and wildlife.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Graham |first1=David W |last2=Bergeron |first2=Gilles |last3=Bourassa |first3=Megan W |last4=Dickson |first4=James |last5=Gomes |first5=Filomena |last6=Howe |first6=Adina |last7=Kahn |first7=Laura H |last8=Morley |first8=Paul S |last9=Scott |first9=H Morgan |last10=Simjee |first10=Shabbir |last11=Singer |first11=Randall S |last12=Smith |first12=Tara C |last13=Storrs |first13=Carina |last14=Wittum |first14=Thomas E |title=Complexities in understanding antimicrobial resistance across domesticated animal, human, and environmental systems |journal=Annals of the New York Academy of Sciences |date=April 2019 |volume=1441 |issue=1 |pages=17\u201330 |doi=10.1111/nyas.14036 |pmid=30924539 |pmc=6850694 |bibcode=2019NYASA1441...17G}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Marshall|first1=Bonnie M|last2=Levy|first2=Stuart B|date=October 2011|title=Food Animals and Antimicrobials: Impacts on Human Health|journal=Clinical Microbiology Reviews|volume=24|issue=4|pages=718\u2013733|doi=10.1128/CMR.00002-11|pmc=3194830|pmid=21976606}}</ref><ref name=\":32\">{{Cite journal|last=Economou|first=Vangelis|last2=Gousia|first2=Panagiota|date=1 April 2015|title=Agriculture and food animals as a source of antimicrobial-resistant bacteria|url=https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/791ac5a1f47bf034b4971bd5014b3e17312d0355|journal=Infection and Drug Resistance|volume=8|pages=49\u201361|doi=10.2147/IDR.S55778|issn=1178-6973|pmc=4388096|pmid=25878509}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Swartz|first=Morton N.|date=1 June 2002|title=Human Diseases Caused by Foodborne Pathogens of Animal Origin|journal=Clinical Infectious Diseases|volume=34|issue=Supplement_3|pages=S111\u2013S122|doi=10.1086/340248|issn=1058-4838|pmid=11988881|ref=harv|doi-access=free}}</ref> Three potential mechanisms by which agricultural antibiotic use could lead to human disease have been identified as: 1 - direct infection with resistant bacteria from an animal source; 2 - breaches in the species barrier followed by sustained transmission in humans of resistant strains arising in livestock; 3 - transfer of resistance genes from agriculture into human pathogens.<ref name=\":10\">{{cite journal|last1=Chang|first1=Qiuzhi|last2=Wang|first2=Weike|last3=Regev-Yochay|first3=Gili|last4=Lipsitch|first4=Marc|last5=Hanage|first5=William P.|date=March 2015|title=Antibiotics in agriculture and the risk to human health: how worried should we be?|url=https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/341d7f7cd9948ade51820a9ba30167190555e8df|journal=Evolutionary Applications|volume=8|issue=3|pages=240\u2013247|doi=10.1111/eva.12185|pmc=4380918|pmid=25861382|ref=harv}}</ref> While there is evidence of transmission of resistance from animals to humans in all three cases, either the scale is limited or causality is hard to establish. As Chang ''et al'' (2014)<ref name=\":10\" /> state: \"The topic of agricultural antibiotic use is complex. As we noted ...many believe that agricultural antibiotics have become a critical threat to human health. While the concern is not unwarranted, the extent of the problem may be exaggerated. There is no evidence that agriculture is \u2018largely to blame\u2019 for the increase in resistant strains and we should not be distracted from finding adequate ways to ensure appropriate antibiotic use in all settings, the most important of which being clinical medicine.\"\n\n==== Direct contact with animals ====\nIn terms of direct infection with resistant bacteria from an animals source, studies have shown that direct contact with livestock can lead to the spread of antibiotic-resistant bacteria. The risk appears greatest in those handling or managing livestock, for example in a study where resistant bacteria were monitored in farm labourers and neighbours after chickens receiving an antibiotic in their feed.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Levy |first1=SB |last2=FitxGerald |first2=GB |last3=Macone |first3=AB |title=Changes in intestinal flora of farm personnel after introduction of a tetracycline-supplemented feed on a farm |journal=New England Journal of Medicine |date=September 1976 |volume=295 |issue=11 |pages=583\u20138 |doi=10.1056/NEJM197609092951103 |pmid=950974}}</ref> Manure may also be contain antibiotic-resistant ''Staphylococcus aureus'' bacteria which can infect humans.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Zhang|first=Sarah|year=2013|title=Pig-manure fertilizer linked to human MRSA infections|journal=Nature News|doi=10.1038/nature.2013.13752|ref=harv|doi-access=free}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Casey|first1=Joan A.|last2=Curriero|first2=Frank C.|last3=Cosgrove|first3=Sara E.|last4=Nachman|first4=Keeve E.|last5=Schwartz|first5=Brian S.|date=25 November 2013|title=High-Density Livestock Operations, Crop Field Application of Manure, and Risk of Community-Associated Methicillin-Resistant Staphylococcus aureus Infection in Pennsylvania|journal=JAMA Internal Medicine|volume=173|issue=21|pages=1980\u201390|doi=10.1001/jamainternmed.2013.10408|pmc=4372690|pmid=24043228}}</ref> In 2017, the [[WHO]] included methicillin-resistant ''S. aureus'' (MRSA) in its priority list of 12 antibiotic-resistant bacteria, urging the need to search for new and more effective antibiotics against it. There also has been an increase in the number of bacterial pathogens resistant to multiple antimicrobial agents, including MRSA, which have recently emerged into different lineages. Some of them are associated with livestock and companion animals that are then able to be transmitted to humans, also called livestock-associated methicillin-resistant ''Staphylococcus aureus'' (LA-MRSA). These new lineages can be found on soft tissues of livestock workers, for example in their noses. A study looked at the association between exposure to livestock and the occurrence of LA-MRSA infection and observed that LA-MRSA infection was 9.64 times as likely to be found among livestock workers and veterinarians compared to their unexposed families and community members, showing that exposure to livestock significantly increases the risk of developing methicillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus (MRSA) infection.<ref>Chen, C., & Wu, F. (2018). Livestock-Associated Methicillin-Resistant Staphylococcus Aureus (LA-MRSA) Colonization and Infection Among Livestock Workers and Veterinarians: A Systematic Review and Meta-Analysis. Available at SSRN 3208968.</ref><ref>{{cite journal | author1 = Nadimpalli M. | author2 =Rinsky J. L. | author3 =Wing S. | author4 =Hall D. | author5 =Stewart J. | author6 =Larsen J. | author7 =Strelitz J. | year = 2015 | title = Persistence of livestock-associated antibiotic-resistant Staphylococcus aureus among industrial hog operation workers in North Carolina over 14 days | url = https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/c17bce5f715ae79bf241be768f7ed1c877c1a963| journal = Occup Environ Med | volume = 72 | issue = 2| pages = 90\u201399 | doi=10.1136/oemed-2014-102095| pmid = 25200855 | pmc = 4316926}}</ref> While total numbers colonised by LA-MRSA remain low, and fewer still suffer infection,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Anjum|first=Muna F.|last2=Marco-Jimenez|first2=Francisco|last3=Duncan|first3=Daisy|last4=Mar\u00edn|first4=Clara|last5=Smith|first5=Richard P.|last6=Evans|first6=Sarah J.|date=2019-09-12|title=Livestock-Associated Methicillin-Resistant Staphylococcus aureus From Animals and Animal Products in the UK|journal=Frontiers in Microbiology|volume=10|pages=2136|doi=10.3389/fmicb.2019.02136|issn=1664-302X|pmc=6751287|pmid=31572341}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/4fca/b9277652e3d8cc34a8150b31de865a838e67.pdf|title=Risk Assessment on Methicillin-Resistant Staphylococcus aureus (MRSA), with a focus on Livestock-associated MRSA, in the UK Food Chain|last=Food Standards Agency|date=February 2017|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref> the condition is nonetheless rising in prevalence, difficult to treat, and has become a public health concern.<ref>Livestock-associated Staphylococcus Aureus (LA-MRSA), Research topic. Retrieved from: https://www.frontiersin.org/research-topics/6689/livestock-associated-staphylococcus-aureus-la-mrsa</ref>\n\n==== Foodborne antibiotic resistance ====\nAnother way humans can be exposed to antibiotic-resistant bacteria is by pathogens on food.<ref name=\"cdc.gov\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/drugresistance/pdf/ar-threats-2013-508.pdf|title=Antibiotic Resistance Threats in the United States|publisher=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|accessdate=30 December 2016}}</ref> In particular, If resistant bacteria are ingested by humans via food and then colonise the gut, they can cause infections which are unpleasant enough in themselves, but can be even harder to treat if they are serious enough to require antibiotic treatment but are also resistant to commonly-used antibiotics.<ref name=\":32\" /><ref>{{cite journal|author=Bortolaia V|displayauthors=etal|date=Feb 2016|title=Human health risks associated with antimicrobial-resistant enterococci and Staphylococcus aureus on poultry meat|url=|journal=Clinical Microbiology and Infection|volume=22|issue=2|pages=130\u201340|doi=10.1016/j.cmi.2015.12.003|pmid=26706616|doi-access=free}}</ref>''[[Campylobacter]]'', ''[[Salmonella]],'' ''[[Escherichia coli|E. coli]]'' and ''[[Listeria]]'' species are the most common foodborne bacteria.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.foodauthority.nsw.gov.au/consumer/food-poisoning/foodborne-illness-pathogens|title=Foodborne illness pathogens|last=New South Wales Government|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> ''Salmonella'' and ''Campylobacter'' alone account for over 400,000 Americans becoming sick from antibiotic-resistant infections every year.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/drugresistance/food.html|title=Antibiotic Resistance and Food are Connected|last=CDC|date=10 September 2018|website=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|language=en-us|accessdate=29 March 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"NARMS 2013\">{{Cite report|url=https://www.cdc.gov/narms/pdf/2013-annual-report-narms-508c.pdf|title=Human Isolates Final Report|last=Center for Disease Control and Prevention|first=|date=2013|issue=|doi=|volume=|pmid=|accessdate=|work=National Antibiotic Resistance Monitoring System: Enteric Bacteria}}</ref> Dairy products, ground minced beef and poultry are among the most common foods that can harbour pathogens both resistant and susceptible to antibiotics,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cspinet.org/sites/default/files/attachment/outbreaks_antibiotic_resistance_in_foodborne_pathogens_2013.pdf|title=Antibiotic Resistance in Foodborne Pathogens|last1=DeWaal|first1=J.D.|last2=Grooters|first2=Susan Vaughn|date=May 2013|work=Center for Science in the Public Interest}}</ref> and surveillance of retail meats such as turkey, chicken, pork and beef have found Enterobacteriaceae. While some studies have established connections between antibiotic resistant infections and food-producing animals,<ref name=\"Molbak K 2005\">{{cite journal|last1=Angulo|first1=F. J.|last2=Molbak|first2=K.|date=1 December 2005|title=Human Health Consequences of Antimicrobial Drug--Resistant Salmonella and Other Foodborne Pathogens|journal=Clinical Infectious Diseases|volume=41|issue=11|pages=1613\u20131620|doi=10.1086/497599|pmid=16267734|ref=harv}}</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceB\">{{cite journal|last1=M\u00f8lbak|first1=K\u00e5re|last2=Baggesen|first2=Dorte Lau|last3=Aarestrup|first3=Frank M\u00f8ller|last4=Ebbesen|first4=Jens Munk|last5=Engberg|first5=J\u00f8rgen|last6=Frydendahl|first6=Kai|last7=Gerner-Smidt|first7=Peter|last8=Petersen|first8=Andreas Munk|last9=Wegener|first9=Henrik C.|date=4 November 1999|title=An Outbreak of Multidrug-Resistant, Quinolone-Resistant Salmonella enterica Serotype Typhimurium DT104|journal=New England Journal of Medicine|volume=341|issue=19|pages=1420\u20131425|doi=10.1056/NEJM199911043411902|pmid=10547404|doi-access=free}}</ref> others have struggled to establish causal links, even when examining plasmid-mediated resistance.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=McCrackin|first=M.A.|last2=Helke|first2=Kristi L.|last3=Galloway|first3=Ashley M.|last4=Poole|first4=Ann Z.|last5=Salgado|first5=Cassandra D.|last6=Marriott|first6=Bernadette p.|date=2016-10-02|title=Effect of Antimicrobial Use in Agricultural Animals on Drug-resistant Foodborne Campylobacteriosis in Humans: A Systematic Literature Review|journal=Critical Reviews in Food Science and Nutrition|language=en|volume=56|issue=13|pages=2115\u20132132|doi=10.1080/10408398.2015.1119798|pmid=26580432|issn=1040-8398}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mather|first=A. E.|last2=Reid|first2=S. W. J.|last3=Maskell|first3=D. J.|last4=Parkhill|first4=J.|last5=Fookes|first5=M. C.|last6=Harris|first6=S. R.|last7=Brown|first7=D. J.|last8=Coia|first8=J. E.|last9=Mulvey|first9=M. R.|last10=Gilmour|first10=M. W.|last11=Petrovska|first11=L.|date=2013-09-27|title=Distinguishable Epidemics of Multidrug-Resistant Salmonella Typhimurium DT104 in Different Hosts|journal=Science|language=en|volume=341|issue=6153|pages=1514\u20131517|doi=10.1126/science.1240578|issn=0036-8075|pmc=4012302|pmid=24030491|bibcode=2013Sci...341.1514M}}</ref><ref name=\":12\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Zaheer|first=Rahat|last2=Cook|first2=Shaun R.|last3=Barbieri|first3=Ruth|last4=Goji|first4=Noriko|last5=Cameron|first5=Andrew|last6=Petkau|first6=Aaron|last7=Polo|first7=Rodrigo Ortega|last8=Tymensen|first8=Lisa|last9=Stamm|first9=Courtney|last10=Song|first10=Jiming|last11=Hannon|first11=Sherry|date=2020|title=Surveillance of Enterococcus spp. reveals distinct species and antimicrobial resistance diversity across a One-Health continuum|journal=Scientific Reports|language=en|volume=10|issue=1|pages=3937|doi=10.1038/s41598-020-61002-5|issn=2045-2322|pmc=7054549|pmid=32127598|bibcode=2020NatSR..10.3937Z}}</ref> Standard precautions such as pasteurising, or preparing and cooking meat properly, [[food preservation]] methods, and effective hand washing can help eliminate, decrease, or prevent spread of and infection from these and other potentially harmful bacteria.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fsis.usda.gov/wps/portal/fsis/topics/food-safety-education/get-answers/food-safety-fact-sheets/safe-food-handling/cleanliness-helps-prevent-foodborne-illness/ct_index|title=Cleanliness Helps Prevent Foodborne Illness|last=United States Department of Agriculture|date=December 2016|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rajendran|first=Reshma|date=2018|title=Superbug infection.|journal=World Journal of Pharmaceutical Research|volume=7|pages=275\u2013287|doi=10.20959/wjpr2018-11480|doi-broken-date=2020-03-15|url=https://wjpr.net/dashboard/abstract_id/9482}}</ref>\n\n==== Other sources of resistance ====\nAs well as via food, ''E. coli'' from a variety of sources can also cause urinary and bloodstream infections. While one study suggests a large proportion of resistant ''[[Escherichia coli|E. coli]]'' isolates causing bloodstream infections in people could emanate from livestock produced for food,<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Vieira|first1=Antonio R.|last2=Collignon|first2=Peter|last3=Aarestrup|first3=Frank M.|last4=McEwen|first4=Scott A.|last5=Hendriksen|first5=Rene S.|last6=Hald|first6=Tine|last7=Wegener|first7=Henrik C.|date=December 2011|title=Association Between Antimicrobial Resistance in ''Escherichia coli'' Isolates from Food Animals and Blood Stream Isolates from Humans in Europe: An Ecological Study|journal=Foodborne Pathogens and Disease|volume=8|issue=12|pages=1295\u20131301|doi=10.1089/fpd.2011.0950|pmid=21883007}}</ref> other studies have since contradicted this, finding little commonality between resistance genes from livestock sources and those found in human infections, even when examining plasmid-mediated resistance.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dorado-Garc\u00eda|first=Alejandro|last2=Smid|first2=Joost H|last3=van Pelt|first3=Wilfrid|last4=Bonten|first4=Marc J M|last5=Fluit|first5=Ad C|last6=van den Bunt|first6=Gerrita|last7=Wagenaar|first7=Jaap A|last8=Hordijk|first8=Joost|last9=Dierikx|first9=Cindy M|last10=Veldman|first10=Kees T|last11=de Koeijer|first11=Aline|date=2018-02-01|title=Molecular relatedness of ESBL/AmpC-producing Escherichia coli from humans, animals, food and the environment: a pooled analysis|url=http://academic.oup.com/jac/article/73/2/339/4641706|journal=Journal of Antimicrobial Chemotherapy|language=en|volume=73|issue=2|pages=339\u2013347|doi=10.1093/jac/dkx397|pmid=29165596|issn=0305-7453}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ludden|first=Catherine|last2=Raven|first2=Kathy E.|last3=Jamrozy|first3=Dorota|last4=Gouliouris|first4=Theodore|last5=Blane|first5=Beth|last6=Coll|first6=Francesc|last7=de Goffau|first7=Marcus|last8=Naydenova|first8=Plamena|last9=Horner|first9=Carolyne|last10=Hernandez-Garcia|first10=Juan|last11=Wood|first11=Paul|date=2019-01-22|editor-last=Sansonetti|editor-first=Philippe J.|title=One Health Genomic Surveillance of Escherichia coli Demonstrates Distinct Lineages and Mobile Genetic Elements in Isolates from Humans versus Livestock|journal=mBio|language=en|volume=10|issue=1|pages=e02693\u201318, /mbio/10/1/mBio.02693\u201318.atom|doi=10.1128/mBio.02693-18|issn=2150-7511|pmc=6343043|pmid=30670621}}</ref><ref name=\":12\">{{Cite journal|last=El Garch|first=Farid|last2=de Jong|first2=Anno|last3=Bertrand|first3=Xavier|last4=Hocquet|first4=Didier|last5=Sauget|first5=Marl\u00e8ne|date=2018|title=mcr-1-like detection in commensal Escherichia coli and Salmonella spp. from food-producing animals at slaughter in Europe|journal=Veterinary Microbiology|language=en|volume=213|pages=42\u201346|doi=10.1016/j.vetmic.2017.11.014|pmid=29292002}}</ref>\n\nThe use of antibiotics in livestock also has the potential to introduce antibiotic-resistant bacteria to humans via environmental exposure or inhalation of airborne bacteria. Antibiotics given to livestock in sub-therapeutic concentrations to stimulate growth when there is no diagnosis of disease - a practice still permitted in some countries - may kill some, but not all, of the bacterial organisms in the animal, possibly leaving those that are naturally antibiotic-resistant in the environment. Hence the practice of using antibiotics for growth stimulation could result in selection for resistance.<ref>{{cite book|last=Wegener|first=Henrik C.|title=Antibiotic Resistance \u2014 Linking Human And Animal Health: Improving Food Safety Through a One Health Approach Workshop Summary|publisher=National Academies Press|year=2012|isbn=978-0-309-25937-8|editor=Choffnes, E.R.|location=Washington DC|pages=|chapter=A15 Antibiotic Resistance\u2014Linking Human and Animal Health|doi=10.17226/13423|pmid=23230579|id=NBK114485|editor2=Relman, D.A.|editor3=Olsen, L.|editor4=Hutton, R.|editor5=Mack, A.|chapterurl=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK114485/}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author=Wegener H|year=2003|title=Antibiotics in animal feed and their role in resistance development|journal=Current Opinion in Microbiology|volume=6|issue=5|pages=439\u2013445|doi=10.1016/j.mib.2003.09.009|pmid=14572534}}</ref> Antibiotics are not fully digested and processed in the animal or human gut, therefore, an estimated 40 to 90% of the antibiotics ingested are excreted in urine and/or faeces.<ref name=\"Prevalence\">{{cite journal |last1=Zhang |first1=X |title=Prevalence of veterinary antibiotics and antibiotic-resistant Escherichia coli in the surface water of a livestock production region in northern China |journal=PLOS One |volume=9 |issue=11 |pages=e111026 |pmid=25372873 |pmc=4220964 |year=2014 |doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0111026 |bibcode=2014PLoSO...9k1026Z |url=https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/aec867274d40c5ac7a084ae5ced227a6ff56ee5a}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Storteboom|first=Heather|last2=Arabi|first2=Mazdak|last3=Davis|first3=Jessica G.|last4=Crimi|first4=Barbara|last5=Pruden|first5=Amy|date=October 2010|title=Tracking Antibiotic Resistance Genes in the South Platte River Basin Using Molecular Signatures of Urban, Agricultural, And Pristine Sources|journal=Environmental Science & Technology|language=en|volume=44|issue=19|pages=7397\u20137404|doi=10.1021/es101657s|pmid=20809616|bibcode=2010EnST...44.7397S|issn=0013-936X}}</ref> This means that as well as finding antibiotics in human sewage and animal manure, both can also contain antibiotic-resistant bacteria which have developed ''in vivo'' or in the environment. When animal manures are stored inadequately or applied as fertiliser, this can then spread bacteria to crops and into run-off water.<ref name=\"Sarmah et al 2006\" /><ref name=\"Prevalence\" /> Antibiotics have been found in small amounts in crops grown in fertilised fields,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cimitile |first1=Matthew |title=Worried about Antibiotics in Your Beef? Vegetables May Be No Better |url=https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/vegetables-contain-antibiotics/}}</ref> and detected in runoff from animal waste-fertilised land.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Sun |first1=P |title=Detection and quantification of ionophore antibiotics in runoff, soil and poultry litter. |journal=Journal of Chromatography A |volume=1312 |pages=10\u20137 |pmid=24028934 |year=2013 |doi=10.1016/j.chroma.2013.08.044}}</ref> Composting has been shown to reduce the presence of various antibiotics by 20-99%,<ref name=\"Prevalence\" /> but one study found that chlortetracycline (CTC), an antibiotic used in livestock feed in China, degraded at different rates dependent on the animal it was fed to, and that manure composting was not sufficient to ensure the microbial degradation of CTC.<ref name=\"Depletion\">{{cite journal|last1=Bao|first1=Yanyu|last2=Zhou|first2=Qixing|last3=Guan|first3=Lianzhu|last4=Wang|first4=Yingying|date=April 2009|title=Depletion of chlortetracycline during composting of aged and spiked manures.|journal=Waste Management|volume=29|issue=4|pages=1416\u20131423|doi=10.1016/j.wasman.2008.08.022|pmid=18954968}}</ref>\n\n== Global positions on antibiotic use in farm animals ==\nIn 2017, the World Health Organization (WHO) recommended reducing antibiotic use in animals used in the food industry. Due to the increasing risk of antibiotic resistant bacteria, the WHO strongly suggested restrictions on antibiotics being used for growth promotion and antibiotics used on healthy animals. Animals that require antibiotics should be treated with antibiotics that pose the smallest risk to human health.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> [[HSBC]] also produced a report in October 2018 warning that the use of antibiotics in meat production could have \u201cdevastating\u201d consequences for humans. It noted that many dairy and meat producers in Asia and the Americas had an economic incentive to continue high usage of antibiotics, particularly in crowded or unsanitary living conditions.<ref>{{cite news |title=One of the world's largest banks has issued an alarming warning about antibiotic resistance \u2014 with big consequences for humanity |url=http://uk.businessinsider.com/hsbc-says-meat-production-creates-devastating-antibiotic-resistance-2018-10 |accessdate=13 November 2018 |publisher=Business Insider UK |date=10 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nHowever, the [[World Organisation for Animal Health]] has acknowledged the need to protect antibiotics but argued against a total ban on antibiotic use in animal production.<ref>{{cite news |title=Antibiotics for livestock vital to feed world: OIE |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-antibiotics-livestock/antibiotics-for-livestock-vital-to-feed-world-oie-idUSTRE80A1JF20120111 |work=Reuters |date=11 January 2012}}</ref> A total ban on antibiotics might drastically reduce protein supply in some parts of the world,<ref name=\":1\">Stop using antibiotics in healthy animals to preserve their effectiveness. (2017). Retrieved from https://www.who.int/news-room/detail/07-11-2017-stop-using-antibiotics-in-healthy-animals-to-prevent-the-spread-of-antibiotic-resistance</ref> and when use of antibiotics is reduced or eliminated in livestock through legislation or voluntarily, both animal health and welfare and economic impacts can be negatively affected.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Karavolias |first1=Joanna |last2=Salois |first2=Matthew Jude |last3=Baker |first3=Kristi |last4=Watkins |first4=Kevin |title=Raised without antibiotics: impact on animal welfare and implications for food policy |journal=Translational Animal Science |date=October 2018 |volume=2 |issue=4 |pages=337\u2013348 |doi=10.1093/tas/txy016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Phillips |first1=I. |last2=Casewell |first2=M |last3=Cox |first3=T |last4=De Groot |first4=B |last5=Friis |first5=C |last6=Jones |first6=R |last7=Nightingale |first7=C |last8=Preston |first8=R |last9=Waddell |first9=J |title=Does the use of antibiotics in food animals pose a risk to human health? A critical review of published data |journal=Journal of Antimicrobial Chemotherapy |date=4 December 2003 |volume=53 |issue=1 |pages=28\u201352 |doi=10.1093/jac/dkg483 |pmid=14657094 |doi-access=free}}</ref> For example, experiences from farms where antibiotic use has been cut back or eliminated in the interests of meeting a consumer demand for 'antibiotic-free' or 'reared without antibiotics' produce have been shown to have a detrimental effect on animal health and welfare.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Dee |first1=S |last2=Guzman |first2=JE |last3=Hanson |first3=D |last4=Garbes |first4=N |last5=Morrison |first5=R |last6=Amodie |first6=D |title=A randomized controlled trial to evaluate performance of pigs raised in antibiotic-free or conventional production systems following challenge with porcine reproductive and respiratory syndrome virus |journal=PLOS One |date=2018 |volume=13 |issue=12 |page=e0208430|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0208430 |pmid=30521587 |pmc=6283559 |bibcode=2018PLoSO..1308430D}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Gaucher |first1=ML |last2=Quessy |first2=S |last3=Letellier |first3=A |last4=Boulianne |first4=M |title=mpact of a drug-free 391 program on broiler chicken growth performances, gut health, Clostridium perfringens and 392 Campylobacter jejuni occurrences at the farm level |journal=Poultry Science |date=2015 |volume=94 |issue=8 |pages=1791\u2013801 |doi=10.3382/ps/pev142 |pmid=26047674}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Smith |first1=JA |title=Experiences with drug-free broiler production |journal=Poultry Science |date=2011 |volume=90 |issue=11 |pages=2670\u20138 |doi=10.3382/ps.2010-01032 |pmid=22010257}}</ref> When antibiotics are used sub-therapeutically (for animal performance, increased growth, and improved feed efficiency), then the costs of meat, eggs, and other animal products are lowered.<ref name=\"NRC\">{{cite book |author=National Research Council (US) Committee on Drug Use in Food Animals |chapter=Costs of Eliminating Subtherapeutic Use of Antibiotics |title=The Use of Drugs in Food Animals: Benefits and Risks |chapterurl=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK232579/ |date=1999 |publisher=National Academies Press}}</ref> One big argument against the restriction of antibiotic use is the potential economic hardship that would result for producers of livestock and poultry that could also result in higher cost for consumers.In a study analysing the economic cost of the FDA restricting all antibiotic use in animal livestock, it was estimated that the restriction would cost consumers approximately $1.2 billion to $2.5 billion per year.<ref name=\"NRC\" /> In order to determine the overall economic impact of restricting antibiotic use, the financial cost must be weighed against the health benefits to the population. Since it is difficult to estimate the value of potential health benefits, the study concluded that the complete economic impact of restricting antibiotic use has not yet been determined.<ref name=\"NRC\" />\n\nAlthough quantifying health benefits may be difficult, the economic impact of antibiotic restriction in animals can also be evaluated through the economic impact of antibiotic resistance in humans, which is a significant outcome of antibiotic use in animals. The World Health Organization identifies antibiotic resistance as a contributor to longer hospital stays and higher medical costs.<ref name=\"WHO AR\">{{cite web |title=Antibiotic Resistance|url=https://www.who.int/news-room/fact-sheets/detail/antibiotic-resistance |website=WHO |publisher=World Health Organization |accessdate=28 March 2019}}</ref> When infections can no longer be treated by typical first-line antibiotics, more expensive medications are required for treatment. When illness duration is extended by antibiotics resistance, the increased health care costs create a larger economic burden for families and societies.<ref name=\"WHO AR\"/> The Center for Infectious Disease Research and Policy estimates approximately $2.2 billion in antibiotic resistance- related healthcare costs each year.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Dall |first1=Chris |title=Price to Pay: Antibiotic-Resistant Infections Cost $2 billion a year |journal=The Center for Infectious Disease Research and Policy |date=22 March 2018}}</ref> So while restricting antibiotics in animals causes a significant economic burden, the outcome of antibiotic resistance in humans that is perpetuated by antibiotic use in animals carries comparable economic burdens.\n\n== Use and regulation by country ==\nThe use of medicines to treat disease in food-producing animals is regulated in nearly all countries, although some countries prescription-control their antibiotics, meaning only qualified veterinary surgeons can prescribe and in some cases dispense them.<ref name=\"Tang et al2\">{{cite journal|last1=Tang|first1=Karen L|last2=Caffrey|first2=Niamh P|last3=N\u00f3brega|first3=Diego|last4=Cork|first4=Susan C|last5=Ronksley|first5=Paul C|last6=Barkema|first6=Herman W|last7=Polachek|first7=Alicia J|last8=Ganshorn|first8=Heather|last9=Sharma|first9=Nishan|last10=Kellner|first10=James D|last11=Checkley|first11=Sylvia L|date=August 2019|title=Comparison of different approaches to antibiotic restriction in food-producing animals: stratified results from a systematic review and meta-analysis|url=https://gh.bmj.com/content/bmjgh/4/4/e001710.full.pdf|journal=BMJ Global Health|volume=2019|issue=4|pages=e001710|doi=10.1136/bmjgh-2019-001710|pmc=6730577|pmid=31543995|last12=Ghali|first12=William A}}</ref> Historically, the restrictions have existed to prevent contamination of mainly meat, milk, eggs and honey with chemicals that are in any way harmful to humans. Treating a sick animal with medicines may lead the animal product containing some of those medicines when the animal is slaughtered, milked, lays eggs or produces honey, unless withdrawal periods are adhered to which stipulate a period of time to ensure the medicines have left the animal's system sufficiently to avoid any risk.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vmd.defra.gov.uk/pdf/leaflet_residues.pdf|title=Avoiding Veterinary Residues in Food \u2013 Maintaining Consumer Confidence|last1=Veterinary Medicines Directorate|website=Defra (UK)|accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref> Scientific experiments provide data for each medicine in each application, showing how long it is present in the body of an animal and what the animal's body does to metabolise the medicine. By the use of 'drug withdrawal periods' before slaughter or the use of milk or eggs from treated animals, veterinarians and animal owners ensure that the meat, milk and eggs is safe and free of any contamination.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://healthforanimals.org/downloads/library/veterinary%20medicines%20and%20food%20safety.pdf|title=Veterinary Medicines and Food Safety|last1=IFAH|website=Health for Animals|accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref> However, some countries have also banned or heavily controlled routine use of antibiotics for growth stimulation or the preventative control of disease arising from deficiencies in management or facilities. This is not over concerns about residues, but about the growth of antibiotic resistance (also called [[Antimicrobial resistance|antimicrobial resistance/AMR]]).\n\n===Brazil===\nBrazil is the world's largest exporter of beef. The government regulates antibiotic use in the cattle production industry.<ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Millen|first1=D. D.|last2=Pacheco|first2=R. D. L.|last3=Meyer|first3=P. M.|last4=Rodrigues|first4=P. H. M.|last5=De Beni Arrigoni|first5=M.|year=2011|title=Current outlook and future perspectives of beef production in Brazil|url=|journal=Animal Frontiers|volume=1|issue=2|pages=46\u201352|doi=10.2527/af.2011-0017|pmc=|pmid=|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\n===Canada===\nBecause of concerns about antibiotics residues getting into the milk or meat of cattle, the [[Canadian Food Inspection Agency]] (CFIA) enforces standards which protect consumers by ensuring that foods produced will not contain antibiotics at a level which will cause harm to consumers. In Canada the veterinary drug regulation consists of two federal government agencies, namely [[Health Canada]] and the CFIA, which are responsible for implementing and enforcing the [[Food and Drugs Act]]. Testing samples for drug residues include three methods: monitoring, surveillance, and compliance. There are Swab Test On Premises (STOP) procedures to detect antibiotic residues in kidney tissues.<ref name=\"Seven\">{{cite web|url=http://ordercentre.beefinfo.org/ca/en/consumer/Download.aspx?FileName=150147-EN.PDF&masterNo=150147&itemType=PDF&itemUnits=EACH&catalogCode=RES_HEALTHPROFESSIONAL&subCatalogCode=RES_HEALTH_FORTHEHEALTHPRO&Language=LAN_ENGLISH&ProfileNo=462375|title=Understanding Use of Antibiotic and Hormonal Substances in Beef Cattle|author=Canadian Cattlemen's Association and Beef Information Centre|year=2003|work=Nutrition Perspective|url-status=dead|archiveurl=http://arquivo.pt/wayback/20160517162213/http://ordercentre.beefinfo.org/ca/en/consumer/Download.aspx?FileName=150147-EN.PDF&masterNo=150147&itemType=PDF&itemUnits=EACH&catalogCode=RES_HEALTHPROFESSIONAL&subCatalogCode=RES_HEALTH_FORTHEHEALTHPRO&Language=LAN_ENGLISH&ProfileNo=462375|archivedate=17 May 2016|accessdate=29 October 2009|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===China===\nChina produces and consumes the most antibiotics of all countries.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rendezvous.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/02/18/global-health-threat-seen-in-overuse-of-antibiotics-on-chinese-pig-farms/|title=Global Health Threat Seen in Overuse of Antibiotics on Chinese Pig Farms|last=Tatlow|first=Didi Kirsten|date=18 February 2013|work=IHT Rendezvous|accessdate=28 August 2013}}</ref> Antibiotic use has been measured by checking the water near factory farms in China<ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Wei|first1=R.|last2=Ge|first2=F.|last3=Huang|first3=S.|last4=Chen|first4=M.|last5=Wang|first5=R.|year=2011|title=Occurrence of veterinary antibiotics in animal wastewater and surface water around farms in Jiangsu Province, China|url=http://qnnkxjj.cast.org.cn/uploadfile/jiangxiang/2013Jul24/1374656004765.pdf|url-status=dead|journal=Chemosphere|volume=82|issue=10|pages=1408\u20131414|bibcode=2011Chmsp..82.1408W|doi=10.1016/j.chemosphere.2010.11.067|pmc=|pmid=21159362|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180817225810/http://qnnkxjj.cast.org.cn/uploadfile/jiangxiang/2013Jul24/1374656004765.pdf|archive-date=17 August 2018|accessdate=17 August 2018|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Hu|first1=X.|last2=Zhou|first2=Q.|last3=Luo|first3=Y.|year=2010|title=Occurrence and source analysis of typical veterinary antibiotics in manure, soil, vegetables and groundwater from organic vegetable bases, northern China|journal=Environmental Pollution|volume=158|issue=9|pages=2992\u20132998|doi=10.1016/j.envpol.2010.05.023|pmc=|pmid=20580472}}</ref> as well as through animal faeces.<ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Zhao|first1=L.|last2=Dong|first2=Y. H.|last3=Wang|first3=H.|year=2010|title=Residues of veterinary antibiotics in manures from feedlot livestock in eight provinces of China|journal=Science of the Total Environment|volume=408|issue=5|pages=1069\u20131075|bibcode=2010ScTEn.408.1069Z|doi=10.1016/j.scitotenv.2009.11.014|pmc=|pmid=19954821}}</ref> It was calculated that 38.5 million kg (or 84.9 million lbs) of antibiotics were used in China's swine and poultry production in 2012.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Krishnasamy|first1=Vikram|last2=Otte|first2=Joachim|last3=Silbergeld|first3=Ellen|date=28 April 2015|title=Antimicrobial use in Chinese swine and broiler poultry production|url=https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/024a405347f1bbe40e2bddb1c0faf3324d25dfb3|journal=Antimicrobial Resistance and Infection Control|volume=4|issue=1|pages=17|doi=10.1186/s13756-015-0050-y|issn=2047-2994|pmc=4412119|pmid=25922664|ref=harv|doi-access=free}}</ref> The abuse of antibiotics caused severe pollution of soil and surface water in Northern China.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Mu|first1=Quanhua|last2=Li|first2=Jin|last3=Sun|first3=Yingxue|last4=Mao|first4=Daqing|last5=Wang|first5=Qing|last6=Yi|first6=Luo|date=5 December 2014|title=Occurrence of sulfonamide-, tetracycline-, plasmid-mediated quinolone- and macrolide-resistance genes in livestock feedlots in Northern China|url=https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/806fa4931cb62c4b6c7840b4455de7a87cf11fdd|journal=Springer|volume=22|issue=6932\u20136940|pages=6932\u20136940|doi=10.1007/s11356-014-3905-5|pmid=25475616}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, [[U.S. News & World Report]] described the Chinese government's regulation of antibiotics in livestock production as \"weak\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://health.usnews.com/health-news/news/articles/2013/02/11/chinas-overuse-of-antibiotics-in-livestock-may-threaten-human-health|title=China's Overuse of Antibiotics in Livestock May Threaten Human Health|last=Salamon|first=Maureen|date=11 February 2013|work=health.usnews.com|accessdate=28 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn the UK 5-Year Antimicrobial Resistance(AMR) Strategy 2013\u20132018, the importance of addressing AMR negative effects on animal health has been considered as same as human health. Several scientific partnerships with low-middle income countries would be established.<ref>https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/662189/UK_AMR_3rd_annual_report.pdf</ref> UK-China Newton fund has started to build multi-discipline collaboration cross the border to stop the increasing global burden caused by AMR.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mrc.ukri.org/news/browse/4-5m-from-newton-fund-for-collaborations-that-will-tackle-antimicrobial-resistance/|title=\u00a34.5m from Newton Fund for collaborations that will tackle antimicrobial resistance|last=Medical Research Council|first=M. R. C.|date=29 November 2018|website=mrc.ukri.org|accessdate=6 December 2018}}</ref> To achieve the goal of citizen public health and food safety, \u201cThe National action Plan on Controlling Antibiotic-Resistance Bacteria on animal origins(2016-2020)\u201d has been published by Ministry of Agriculture and Rural Affairs of People's Republic of China since 2017. This plan is fully integrated with the concept of one health. It covers not only the research and development, but also social context.\n\nThe following aims should be achieved by 2020:<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://jiuban.moa.gov.cn/zwllm/tzgg/tz/201706/t20170623_5726086.htm|title=\u519c\u4e1a\u90e8\u5173\u4e8e\u5370\u53d1\u300a\u5168\u56fd\u904f\u5236\u52a8\u7269\u6e90\u7ec6\u83cc\u8010\u836f\u884c\u52a8\u8ba1\u5212\uff082017\u20142020\u5e74\uff09\u300b\u7684\u901a\u77e5|website=jiuban.moa.gov.cn|accessdate=6 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://resistancecontrol.info/2017/a-national-action-plan-to-contain-antimicrobial-resistance-in-china-contents-actions-and-expectations/|title=A National Action Plan to Contain Antimicrobial Resistance in China: Contents, Actions and Expectations {{!}} AMR Control|website=resistancecontrol.info|accessdate=6 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n# Implementation of Exit Plan, to encourage the drop of antibiotics as the growth promoters\n# Regulation of drug market, to strengthen the registration and management of veterinary antibiotics\n# Improvements on AMR surveillance system\n# Strengthening on the testing of antibacterial residue\n# Exemplification on effective models of decreasing the use on antibiotics\n# Education on public and professions\n\n===European Union===\n\nIn 1999, the European Union (EU) implemented an antibiotic resistance monitoring program and a plan to phase out antibiotic use for the purposes of growth promotion by 2006.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://europa.eu/rapid/press-release_IP-05-1687_en.htm|title=European Commission - PRESS RELEASES - Press release - Ban on antibiotics as growth promoters in animal feed enters into effect|last=European Union|date=2005|accessdate=22 December 2005}}</ref> The European Union banned the use of antibiotics as growth agents starting on 1 January 2006 with Regulation (EC) No 1831/2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://data.europa.eu/eli/reg/2003/1831/oj|title=EUR-Lex - 32003R1831 - EN - EUR-Lex|website=data.europa.eu}}</ref> In [[Germany]], 1,734 tons of antimicrobial agents were used for animals in 2011 compared with 800 tons for humans.{{citation needed|date=March 2017}} [[Sweden]] banned their use in 1986 and [[Denmark]] started cutting down drastically in 1994, now using 60% less.<ref>{{cite news|last=Koch|first=Julia|url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/europe/danish-pig-farmers-reduce-antibiotics-to-prevent-drug-resistance-a-933344.html|title=Cutting Antibiotics : Denmark Leads Way in Healthier Pig Farming|date=13 November 2013|work=Spiegel Online|accessdate=22 May 2014}}</ref> In [[the Netherlands]], the use of antibiotics to treat diseases increased after the ban on its use for growth purposes in 2006.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Cogliani|first1=Carol|last2=Goossens|first2=Herman|last3=Greko|first3=Christina|date=1 January 2011|title=Restricting Antimicrobial Use in Food Animals: Lessons from Europe|journal=Microbe Magazine|volume=6|issue=6|pages=274\u2013279|doi=10.1128/microbe.6.274.1|issn=1558-7452|ref=harv}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, the European Parliament voted for a non-binding resolution that called for the end of the preventative use of antibiotics in livestock.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/sides/getDoc.do?pubRef=-//EP//TEXT+IM-PRESS+20111026IPR30419+0+DOC+XML+V0//EN|title=Parliament demands smarter use of antibiotics|website=www.europarl.europa.eu}}</ref>\n\nA revised regulation on veterinary medicinal products, proposed in procedure 2014/0257/COD, proposed limiting the use of antibiotics in prophylaxis and metaphylaxis. An agreement on the regulation between the Council of the European Union and the European Parliament was confirmed on 13 June 2018,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eur-lex.europa.eu/procedure/EN/2014_257|title=EUR-Lex - 2014_257 - EN - EUR-Lex|website=eur-lex.europa.eu}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.consilium.europa.eu/en/press/press-releases/2018/06/13/veterinary-medicines-new-eu-rules-to-enhance-availability-and-fight-against-antimicrobial-resistance/|title=Veterinary medicines: new EU rules to enhance availability and fight against antimicrobial resistance - Consilium|website=www.consilium.europa.eu}}</ref> and the new Veterinary Medicines Regulation (Regulation (EU) 2019/6) is due to come into effect on 28 January 2022.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ema.europa.eu/en/veterinary-regulatory/overview/implementation-new-veterinary-medicines-regulation|title=Implementation of the new Veterinary Medicines Regulation|last=European Medicines Agency|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===India===\n\nIn 2011 the Indian government proposed a \"National policy for containment of antimicrobial resistance\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/govt-wants-to-limit-use-of-antibiotics-in-animals/775330/|title=Govt wants to limit use of antibiotics in animals \u2013 Indian Express|last=Thacker|first=Teena|date=13 April 2011|work=indianexpress.com|accessdate=28 August 2013}}</ref> Other policies set schedules for requiring that food producing animals not be given antibiotics for a certain amount of time before their food goes to market.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-11-25/science/30440181_1_antibiotic-resistance-poultry-products-livestock|title=New norm to curb antibiotic resistance \u2013 Times of India|last=Sinha|first=Kounteya|date=25 November 2011|work=indiatimes.com|accessdate=28 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-04-06/india/31300016_1_antibiotics-seafood-and-poultry-products-staphylococcus|title=In a first, antibiotics bar on food-producing animals \u2013 Times of India|last=Sinha|first=Kounteya|date=6 April 2012|work=indiatimes.com|accessdate=28 August 2013}}</ref> A study released by Centre for Science and Environment (CSE) on 30 July 2014 found antibiotic residues in chicken. This study claims that Indians are developing resistance to antibiotics \u2013 and hence falling prey to a host of otherwise curable ailments. Some of this resistance might be due to large-scale unregulated use of [[Antibiotics in poultry farming|antibiotics in the poultry industry]]. CSE finds that India has not set any limits for antibiotic residues in chicken and says that India will have to implement a comprehensive set of regulations including banning of antibiotic use as growth promoters in the poultry industry. Not doing this will put lives of people at risk.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cseindia.org/node/5487/|title=Centre For Science and Environment (CSE)|date=30 July 2014|accessdate=30 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n===New Zealand===\nIn 1999 the New Zealand government issued a statement that they would not then ban the use of antibiotics in livestock production.<ref>{{cite news|last=staff|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=1071|title=NZ holds off ban on animal antibiotics \u2013 National \u2013 NZ Herald News|date=7 January 1999|work=nzherald.co.nz|accessdate=29 August 2013}}</ref> In 2007 [[ABC Online]] reported on antibiotic use in chicken production in New Zealand.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/radionational/programs/scienceshow/antibiotics-and-intensive-chicken-farming-in-new/3222458#transcript|title=Antibiotics and intensive chicken farming in New Zealand \u2013 The Science Show|last1=Williams|first1=Robyn|last2=Cook|first2=Greg|date=11 August 2007|work=abc.net.au|accessdate=29 August 2013}}</ref>\nIn 2017, New Zealand published a new action plan to address the ongoing concern of antimicrobial resistance (AMR). The action plan outlined five objectives with each objective looking both at AMR in humans and AMR in agriculture.<ref>Ministry of Health and Ministry for Primary Industries. 2017. Antimicrobial Resistance: New Zealand\u2019s current situation and identified areas for action. Wellington: Ministry of Health and Ministry for Primary Industries. Retrieved from https://www.health.govt.nz/publication/antimicrobial-resistance-new-zealands-current-situation-and-identified-areas-action</ref>\nCompared to other countries, New Zealand has a very low prevalence of AMR in animals and plants. This is due to their low use of antibiotics in animal treatment.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Hillerton J.|author2=Irvine C.|author3=Bryan M.|author4=Scott D.|author5=Merchant S.|year=2016|title=Use of antimicrobials for animals in New Zealand, and in comparison with other countries|url=|journal=New Zealand Veterinary Journal|volume=65|issue=2|pages=71\u201377|doi=10.1080/00480169.2016.1171736|pmid=27030313}}</ref>\n\n===South Korea===\nIn 1998 some researchers reported use in livestock production was a factor in the high prevalence of antibiotic-resistant bacteria in Korea.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Kim|first1=Woo Joo|last2=Park|first2=Seung Chull|year=1998|title=bacterial Resistance to Antimicrobial Agents: An Overview from Korea|url=http://www.eymj.org/Synapse/Data/PDFData/0069YMJ/ymj-39-488.pdf|journal=[[Yonsei Medical Journal]]|volume=39|issue=6|pages=488\u2013494|doi=10.3349/ymj.1998.39.6.488|pmid=10097674|accessdate=29 August 2013}}</ref> In 2007 ''[[The Korea Times]]'' noted that Korea has relatively high usage of antibiotics in livestock production.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/special/2010/06/180_5376.html|title=Antibiotics in Livestock Harm Human Beings|last=Won-sup|first=Yoon|date=25 June 2007|work=[[The Korea Times]]|accessdate=29 August 2013}}</ref> In 2011, the Korean government banned the use of antibiotics as growth promoters in livestock.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foodsafetynews.com/2011/06/south-korea-bans-antibiotics-in-animal-feed/#.Uh99Nm2KLm0|title=South Korea Bans Antibiotics in Animal Feed|last=Flynn|first=Dan|date=7 June 2011|work=foodsafetynews.com|accessdate=29 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== United Kingdom ===\nAs with other countries in Europe, use of antibiotics for growth promotion was banned in 2006.<ref name=\":7\" /> Less than one third of all antibiotics sold in the UK are now estimated to be used to treat or prevent disease in farmed animals, following an revision to the 2017 sales data published by the UK Government's Veterinary Medicines Directorate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/775075/One_Health_Report_2019_v45.pdf|title=UK One Health Report: Joint report on antibiotic use and antibiotic resistance|date=31 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/840300/PCDOCS-_1698491-v1-VARSS_errata_2017_.pdf|title=Erratum to UK Veterinary Antibiotic Resistance and Sales Surveillance Report UK-VARSS 2017|last=Veterinary Medicines Directorate|date=29 October 2019|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Furthermore, 2018 sales data<ref name=\":13\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/veterinary-antimicrobial-resistance-and-sales-surveillance-2018|title=Veterinary Antimicrobial Resistance and Sales Surveillance UK-VARSS 2018|last=Veterinary Medicines Directorate|date=29 October 2019|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> estimated use at 29.5&nbsp;mg antibiotics per kg of animal at time of treatment during that year. This represents a 53% reduction in sales of antibiotics to treat food-producing animals over five years.<ref name=\":15\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/sales-of-veterinary-antibiotics-halved-over-the-past-four-years|title=Sales of veterinary antibiotics halved over the past four years|last=Defra|date=29 October 2019|website=|publisher=UK Government|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The reduction has largely been achieved without legislation, and has been credited to voluntary industry action coordinated by the Responsible Use of Medicines in Agriculture (RUMA) Alliance <ref>{{cite web|url=https://ruma.org.uk|title=Responsible Use of Medicines in Agriculture Alliance|accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref> through a 'Targets Task Force' comprising a prominent veterinary surgeon and farmer from each livestock enterprise.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ruma.org.uk/targets-task-force/|title=RUMA Targets Task Force|accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref> A European comparison of 2017 sales data found the UK had the fifth lowest sales in Europe during that year, with 2018 comparisons due to be released towards the end of 2020.<ref name=\"ESVACreport2019\" />\n\nWhile sales data give an overview of levels of use, products are often licensed for use in many species and therefore it is not possible to determine levels of use in different species without more specific usage data from each sector. In 2011, British Poultry Council members, representing 90% of the UK poultry meat industry, formed a stewardship programme that started recording antibiotics used to treat birds in the poultry meat sector in 2012. The first report was published in 2016 and reported a 44% reduction in antibiotic use between 2012 and 2015.<ref name=\":16\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.britishpoultry.org.uk/british-poultry-sector-reduces-antibiotic-use-by-44/|title=British Poultry Sector reduces antibiotic use by 44%|last=British Poultry Council|date=27 July 2016|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> Since then, the organisation has produced three further reports, with the 2019 report confirming that the sector is maintaining reductions of over 80% in total use since it started its stewardship group, as well as reducing use of [https://www.ruma.org.uk/high-risk-antibiotics/ Highest Priority Critically Important Antibiotics] by over 80% by stopping use of 3rd and 4th generation cephalosporins in 2012 and colistin in 2016, and only using macrolides and fluoroquinolones as a last resort. Preventative use of antibiotics has also stopped.\n\nAs many products are licensed for use in poultry and pigs, the increasing transparency around use in the UK poultry meat sector motivated the UK pig sector to set up a stewardship programme in 2016<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.farmantibiotics.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/Pig-stewardship-scheme.pdf|title=NPA Pig IndustryAntibiotic Stewardship Programme|last=National Pig Association|date=2016|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> through the [http://www.npa-uk.org.uk/ National Pig Association]. In 2017, an electronic Medicine Book for pigs (eMB-Pigs) was launched by levy body [[Agriculture and Horticulture Development Board]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pork.ahdb.org.uk/health-welfare/health/antimicrobial-usage/e-medicine-book-emb-pigs/|title=e-Medicine Book (eMB-Pigs)|last=Agriculture and Horticulture Development Board (AHDB)|date=January 2017|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> eMB-Pigs provides a centralised electronic version of the existing paper or electronic medicine book kept on farms, and allows pig producers to record and quantify their individual use of medicines for easy review with the veterinary surgeon, at the same time as capturing use on each farm so that data can be collated to provide national usage figures. After it became a requirement of [https://www.redtractor.org.uk/ Red Tractor] farm assurance for pigs<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://assurance.redtractor.org.uk/contentfiles/Farmers-6755.pdf?_=636223349546888284|title=Important Changes to Red Tractor Pig Membership, Spring/ Summer 2017|last=Red Tractor Assurance|date=2017|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> that annual, aggregated records of antibiotic use must be logged on the eMB system, data released May 2018 showed that according to records covering 87% of the UK slaughter pig population, antibiotic use had halved between 2015 and 2017,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pork.ahdb.org.uk/news/news-releases/2018/may/uk-pig-industry-halves-antibiotic-usage-in-two-years/|title=UK pig industry halves antibiotic usage in two years|last=Agriculture and Horticulture Development Board|date=May 2018|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> Data for 2018 confirms that overall antibiotic use in the UK pig sector fell further, by 60% from the estimated 2015 figure,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/837173/PCDOCS-_1691961-v1-VARSS_2016_Highlights_-_watermarked.pdf|title=UK VARSS 2016 Highlights Report|last=Veterinary Medicines Directorate|date=November 2016|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> to 110&nbsp;mg/kg. Use of [https://www.ruma.org.uk/high-risk-antibiotics/ Highest Priority Critically Important Antibiotics] also fell to 0.06&nbsp;mg/kg,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ahdb.org.uk/news/pig-industry-antibiotic-results-show-further-reduction|title=Pig industry antibiotic results show further reduction|last=Agriculture and Horticulture Development Board|date=May 2019|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> a reduction of 95% from 2015, with use of colistin almost nil.\n\nAs reported in an annual update of progress against UK targets, factors such as levels of infectious disease domestically or internationally, weather and vaccine availability can all affect antibiotic use.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ruma.org.uk/targets-update-shows-further-progress-towards-farm-antibiotic-goals-but-with-more-to-do/|title=Targets update shows further progress towards farm antibiotic goals \u2013 but with more to do|last=Responsible Use of Medicines in Agriculture (RUMA) Alliance|date=October 2019|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> For example, the Scottish salmon farming sector worked with Government and researchers to introduce a vaccine for the disease Furunculosis (''Aeromonas salmonicida'') in 1994, which significantly reduced the need for antibiotic treatments,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www2.gov.scot/Topics/marine/Fish-Shellfish/aquaculture/diseases/notifiableDisease/Furunculosis/Aeromonas|title=Aeromonas Salmonicida|last=Scottish Government|date=February 2018|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> but the trout sector is still without an effective vaccine for this disease. Lack of data can also make it difficult for farmers to know they compare with their peers or what they need to focus on, a particular problem for the sheep and cattle sectors in the UK, which are in the process of trying to set up their own electronic medicines hub to capture data.<ref name=\":9\" /> While unnecessary or inappropriate use is not acceptable, the UK takes a position that zero use is not necessarily desirable either.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ruma.org.uk/ruma-confirms-position-on-antibiotic-free-labelling/|title='Antibiotic-free' labelling|last=Responsible Use of Medicines in Agriculture (RUMA) Alliance|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===United States===\nIn 1970 the [[Food and Drug Administration|FDA]] first recommended that antibiotic use in livestock be limited but set no actual regulations governing this recommendation.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\" /> By 2001, the [[Union of Concerned Scientists]] estimated that more than 70% of the antibiotics consumed in the US were given to food animals (for example, chickens, pigs, and cattle), in the absence of disease.<ref name=\"TheRealNews-2014-05-18\">{{cite web|url=http://therealnews.com/t2/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=31&Itemid=74&jumival=11872|title=Why Are Antibiotics Becoming Useless All Over the World?|author=Martin Khor|authorlink=Martin Khor|date=18 May 2014|publisher=[[The Real News]]|accessdate=18 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ucsusa.org/food_and_agriculture/our-failing-food-system/industrial-agriculture/hogging-it-estimates-of.html#.Wycey1MvzEY|title=Executive summary from the UCS report \"Hogging It: Estimates of Antimicrobial Abuse in Livestock\"|date=January 2001|publisher=Union of Concerned Scientists|ref=harv}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004 the [[Government Accountability Office]] (GAO) heavily critiqued the FDA for not collecting enough information and data on antibiotic use in factory farms. From this, the GAO concluded the FDA did not have enough information to create effective policy changes regarding antibiotic use. In response, the FDA said more research was being conducted and voluntary efforts within the industry would solve the problem of antibiotic resistance.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gao.gov/products/GAO-11-801|title=Antibiotic Resistance: Agencies Have Made Limited Progress Addressing Antibiotic Use in Animals|date=14 September 2011|publisher=U. S. Government Accountability Office}}</ref> However, by 2011, a total of {{Convert|13.6|e6kg|e6lb|abbr=unit}} of antimicrobials were sold for use in food-producing animals in the United States,<ref name=\"FDA2013\">{{Cite report|url=https://www.fda.gov/downloads/ForIndustry/UserFees/AnimalDrugUserFeeActADUFA/UCM440584.pdf|title=Summary Report on Antimicrobials Sold or Distributed for Use in Food-Producing Animals|last=|first=|date=2013|publisher=FDA|issue=|doi=|volume=|pmid=|accessdate=}}</ref> which represented 80% of all antibiotics sold or distributed in the United States.<ref name=\"FDA 2012, Drug Use Review, Table 1\">{{Cite report|url=https://www.fda.gov/downloads/drugs/drugsafety/informationbydrugclass/ucm319435.pdf|title=Drug Use Review|last=|first=|date=2012|publisher=FDA|issue=|doi=|volume=|pmid=|accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2012, the [[United States District Court for the Southern District of New York]], ruling in an action brought by the [[Natural Resources Defense Council]] and others, ordered the FDA to revoke approvals for the use of antibiotics in livestock that violated FDA regulations.<ref name=\"MPFDA\">{{cite news|author=John Gever|url=http://www.medpagetoday.com/PublicHealthPolicy/FDAGeneral/31792|title=FDA Told to Move on Antibiotic Use in Livestock|date=23 March 2012|newspaper=MedPage Today|accessdate=24 March 2012}}</ref> On 11 April 2012 the FDA announced a voluntary program to phase out unsupervised use of drugs as feed additives and convert approved over-the-counter uses for antibiotics to prescription use only, requiring veterinarian supervision of their use and a prescription.<ref name=\"NYTPrescription\">{{cite news|author=Gardiner Harris|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/04/12/us/antibiotics-for-livestock-will-require-prescription-fda-says.html|title=U.S. Tightens Rules on Antibiotics Use for Livestock|date=11 April 2012|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=12 April 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"FDAFAQ\">{{cite web|url=https://www.fda.gov/AnimalVeterinary/GuidanceComplianceEnforcement/GuidanceforIndustry/ucm216939.htm|title=FDA's Strategy on Antimicrobial Resistance&nbsp;\u2014 Questions and Answers|date=11 April 2012|publisher=US Food and Drug Administration|accessdate=12 April 2012|quote=\"Judicious use\" is using an antimicrobial drug appropriately and only when necessary; Based on a thorough review of the available scientific information, FDA recommends that use of medically important antimicrobial drugs in food-producing animals be limited to situations where the use of these drugs is necessary for ensuring animal health, and their use includes veterinary oversight or consultation. FDA believes that using medically important antimicrobial drugs to increase production in food-producing animals is not a judicious use.}}</ref> In December 2013, the FDA announced the commencement of these steps to phase out the use of antibiotics for the purposes of promoting livestock growth.<ref name=\"TheRealNews-2014-05-18\" /><ref>{{cite news|last=Tavernise|first=Sabrina|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/12/12/health/fda-to-phase-out-use-of-some-antibiotics-in-animals-raised-for-meat.html|title=F.D.A. to Phase Out Use of Some Antibiotics in Animals Raised for Meat|date=11 December 2013|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=11 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, the FDA approved a new Veterinary Feed Directive (VFD), an updated guideline giving instructions to pharmaceutical companies, veterinarians and producers about how to administer necessary drugs through the animal's feed and water.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.fda.gov/AnimalVeterinary/GuidanceComplianceEnforcement/GuidanceforIndustry/ucm216939.htm|title=FDA's Strategy on Antimicrobial Resistance - Questions and Answers|last=Center for Veterinary Medicine, FDA|date=December 2013|website=Guidance for Industry|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=14 March 2017|ref=FDAQA}}</ref> Around the same time, the FDA published a report of antibiotics sold or distributed for food-producing animals which found that between 2009 and 2013, just over 60% were 'medically-important' drugs also used in humans;<ref name=\"FDA2013\" /> the rest were from drug classes like [[ionophores]], which are not used in human medicine.<ref name=\"Guidance for Industry: Evaluating the Safety of Antimicrobial New Animal Drugs with Regard to Their Microbiological Effects on Bacteria of Human Health Concern\">{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=2003|title=Evaluating the Safety of Antimicrobial New Animal Drugs with Regard to Their Microbiological Effects on Bacteria of Human Health Concern|url=https://www.fda.gov/downloads/AnimalVeterinary/GuidanceComplianceEnforcement/GuidanceforIndustry/ucm052519.pdf|journal=Guidance for Industry|volume=|issue=#152|pages=|via=}}</ref> Following this, the FDA asked drug companies to voluntarily edit its labels to exclude growth promotion as an indication for antibiotic usage. It subsequently reports that \u201cUnder Guidance for Industry (GFI) #213, which went into effect Jan 1, 2017, antibiotics that are important for human medicine can no longer be used for growth promotion or feed efficiency in cows, pigs, chickens, turkeys, and other food animals.\u201d<ref>Summary Report On Antimicrobials Sold or Distributed for Use in Food-Producing Animals. (2018). US Food and Drug Administration. Retrieved from https://www.fda.gov/downloads/ForIndustry/UserFees/AnimalDrugUserFeeActADUFA/UCM628538.pdf</ref> These new 2017 guidelines for instance prohibited using a drug off-label for non-therapeutic purposes, which would make using the re-labeled drug for growth enhancement illegal. In addition, some drugs were reclassified from 'Over the Counter' (OTC) to 'Veterinary Feed Directive' (VFD); VFD drugs require a veterinarian's authorization before they can be delivered in feed.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":14\">{{Cite web|url=https://ahdc.vet.cornell.edu/programs/NYSCHAP/nysvfrp/vfd.cfm#AffectedVFD|title=VFD \u2013 Veterinary Feed Directive|last=Cornell University College of Veterinary Medicine|accessdate=14 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=\":3\" /> As a result, the FDA reported a 33% decrease from 2016 to 2017 in domestic sales of medically important antibiotics for use in livestock. Despite this progress, the [[Natural Resources Defense Council]] (NRDC) remains concerned that sales of antibiotics to the beef and pork industries remain elevated in 2017 compared with the poultry industries, and their use could still primarily be for preventing diseases in healthy animals, which further increases the threat on antibiotic resistance.<ref>Dall C. (2018). FDA reports major drop in antibiotics for food animals. CIDRAP News. Retrieved from http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/news-perspective/2018/12/fda-reports-major-drop-antibiotics-food-animals</ref> However, the FDA policy remains the same as it stated in 2013:<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n{{Quote|text=The key aspect of FDA\u2019s strategy is the request that animal drug sponsors (those who own the right to market the product) voluntarily work with FDA to revise the approved use conditions for their medically important antimicrobial drug products to remove production uses (such as growth enhancement or feed efficiency), and bring the remaining therapeutic uses under veterinary oversight. Once manufacturers voluntarily make these changes, products can no longer be used for production purposes and therapeutic use of these products would require veterinary oversight.|sign=|source=|title=}}\n\nBecause of concerns about antibiotics residues getting into the milk or meat of cattle, in the United States, the government requires a withdraw period for any animal treated with antibiotics before it can be slaughtered, to allow residue to exit the animal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fsis.usda.gov/factsheets/beef_from_farm_to_table/index.asp|title=Beef...from Farm to Table|author=USDA|work=Fact Sheets|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130224010018/http://www.fsis.usda.gov/Factsheets/Beef_from_Farm_to_Table/index.asp|archivedate=24 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nSome [[grocery stores]] have policies about antibiotic use in the animal whose produce they sell. In response to consumer concerns about the [[use of antibiotics in poultry]], [[Perdue Farms|Perdue]] removed all human antibiotics from its feed in 2007 and launched the Harvestland brand, under which it sold products that met the requirements for an \"antibiotic-free\" label. In 2012 in the United States advocacy organization [[Consumers Union]] organized a petition asking the store [[Trader Joe's]] to discontinue the sale of meat produced with antibiotics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.meatwithoutdrugs.org|title=Meat Without Drugs|publisher=[[Consumers Union]]|accessdate=27 August 2013}}, which is described in the following works\n\n*{{cite book|last=Gore|first=Al|title=The Future : Six Drivers of Global Change|title-link=The Future : Six Drivers of Global Change|publisher=[[Random House]]|year=2013|isbn=9780812992946|edition=First|location=New York|pages=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780812992946/page/227 227 and citation on 475]|chapter=The Reinvention of Life and Death: Antibiotics before Swine|authorlink=Al Gore}}\n*{{cite journal|last=Hurd|first=Scott|date=26 June 2012|title=Commentary: 'Meat without Drugs' could be inhumane|url=http://www.bovinevetonline.com/news/industry/Commentary-Meat-without-Drugs-could-be-inhumane-160409875.html|journal=Bovine Veterinarian|accessdate=27 August 2013|quote=All peer-reviewed scientific risk assessments have demonstrated a negligible risk of human health harm due to livestock antibiotic use.}}\n*{{cite journal|last=Greenaway|first=Twilight|date=20 June 2012|title=Your meat on drugs: Will grocery stores cut out antibiotics?|url=http://grist.org/factory-farms/your-meat-on-drugs-can-grocery-stores-be-convinced-to-cut-out-antibiotics/|journal=[[Grist (magazine)|Grist]]|accessdate=27 August 2013}}</ref> By 2014, Perdue had also phased out ionophores from its hatchery and began using the \"antibiotic free\" labels on its Harvestland, Simply Smart, and Perfect Portions products,<ref name=\"Stephanie Strom\">{{cite news|author=Stephanie Strom|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/01/business/perdue-and-the-race-to-end-antibiotic-use-in-chickens.html|title=Perdue Sharply Cuts Antibiotic Use in Chickens and Jabs at Its Rivals|date=31 July 2015|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=12 August 2015}}</ref> and by 2015, 52% of the company's chickens were raised without the use of any type of antibiotics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://perduefarms.com/News_Room/Statements_and_Comments/details.asp?id=545&title=Antibiotics%20Position%20Statement|title=Antibiotics Position Statement|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150728182903/http://www.perduefarms.com/News_Room/Statements_and_Comments/details.asp?id=545&title=Antibiotics%20Position%20Statement|archive-date=28 July 2015|accessdate=12 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe CDC and FDA do not now support the use of antibiotics for growth promotion because of evidence suggesting that antibiotics used for growth promotion purposes could lead to the development of resistant bacteria.<ref name=\":6\" /> In addition to this, [[The Pew Charitable Trusts]] has stated that \"hundreds of scientific studies conducted over four decades demonstrate that feeding low doses of antibiotics to livestock breeds antibiotic-resistant superbugs that can infect people\".<ref name=\"pew-2012\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pewhealth.org/uploadedFiles/PHG/Content_Level_Pages/Issue_Briefs/HHIFBibliographyFinal%20with%20TOC%20_071712.pdf|title=Antibiotic Resistance and Food Animal Production: a Bibliography of Scientific Studies (1969-2012)|website=The Pew Charitable Trusts|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120811001709/http://www.pewhealth.org/uploadedFiles/PHG/Content_Level_Pages/Issue_Briefs/HHIFBibliographyFinal%20with%20TOC%20_071712.pdf|archivedate=11 August 2012}}</ref> The FDA, the U.S. Department of Agriculture and the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention have all testified before Congress that there is a definitive link between the routine, non-therapeutic use of antibiotics in food animal production and the challenge of antibiotic resistance in humans.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pewtrusts.org/news_room_detail.aspx?id=85899424573|title=Pew Comments on Proposed Antibiotics Legislation|author=The Pew Charitable Trusts|authorlink=The Pew Charitable Trusts|date=15 October 2012|accessdate=26 August 2013}}</ref> However, the [[National Pork Board]], a [[government-owned corporation]] of the United States, has said: \"The vast majority of producers use (antibiotics) appropriately.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2010/02/09/eveningnews/main6191530.shtml|title=Animal Antibiotic Overuse Hurting Humans?|last=Couric|first=Katie|date=10 February 2010|work=[[CBS News]]|publisher=[[CBS Broadcasting|CBS]]|location=New York City|accessdate=29 August 2013}}</ref> In 2011 the [[National Pork Producers Council]], an American [[trade association]], also said, \"Not only is there no scientific study linking antibiotic use in food animals to antibiotic resistance in humans, as the US pork industry has continually pointed out, but there isn't even adequate data to conduct a study.\"<ref>*{{cite web|url=http://growinggeorgia.com/news/2011/09/natl-pork-producers-council-issues-statement-about-gaos-report-antibiotic-resistance/|title=Nat'l Pork Producers Council Issues Statement About GAO's Report on Antibiotic Resistance|author=National Pork Producers Council|authorlink=National Pork Producers Council|date=15 September 2011|work=growinggeorgia.com|accessdate=29 August 2013}}\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.motherjones.com/tom-philpott/2011/09/meat-industry-antibiotic-resistance|title=Meat Industry Still Denying Antibiotic Resistance|last=Philpott|first=Tom|date=21 September 2011|work=motherjones.com|accessdate=29 August 2013}}</ref> The statement was issued in response to a [[United States Government Accountability Office]] report that asserts: \"Antibiotic use in food animals contributes to the emergence of resistant bacteria that may affect humans\".<ref name=\"gao-2011\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gao.gov/products/GAO-11-801|title=Antibiotic Resistance: Agencies Have Made Limited Progress Addressing Antibiotic Use in Animals|last1=Office|first1=U. S. Government Accountability|date=7 September 2011|publisher=[[Government Accountability Office|U.S. Government Accountability Office]]|quote=Antibiotics have saved millions of lives, but antibiotic use in food animals contributes to the emergence of resistant bacteria that may affect humans.|issue=GAO-11-801}}</ref>\n\nIt is difficult to set up a comprehensive surveillance system for measuring rates of change in antibiotic resistance.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Bax|first1=R.|last2=Bywater|first2=R.|last3=Cornaglia|first3=G.|last4=Goossens|first4=H.|last5=Hunter|first5=P.|last6=Isham|first6=V.|last7=Jarlier|first7=V.|last8=Jones|first8=R.|last9=Phillips|first9=I.|last10=Sahm|first10=D.|last11=Senn|first11=S.|date=June 2001|title=Surveillance of antimicrobial resistance \u2014 what, how and whither?|journal=Clinical Microbiology and Infection|volume=7|issue=6|pages=316\u2013325|doi=10.1046/j.1198-743x.2001.00239.x|pmid=11442565|doi-access=free|last13=Taylor|first13=D.|last14=White|first14=A.|first12=M.|last12=Struelens}}</ref> The US [[Government Accountability Office]] published a report in 2011 stating that government and commercial agencies had not been collecting sufficient data to make a decision about best practices.<ref>{{Cite report|url=https://www.gao.gov/products/GAO-11-801|title=Agencies Have Made Limited Progress Addressing Antibiotic Use in Animals|last=U.S. Government Accountability Office|first=|date=7 September 2011|issue=GAO-11-801|doi=|volume=|pmid=|author-link=U.S. Government Accountability Office|accessdate=27 August 2013}}</ref> There is also no regulatory agency in the United States that systematically collects detailed data on antibiotic use in humans and animals, which means it is not clear which antibiotics are prescribed for which purpose and at what time. While this may be lacking at a regulatory level, the US poultry meat sector has been working on the issue of data collection itself, and has now reported comparative data showing significant reductions in antibiotic use.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/news-perspective/2019/08/us-poultry-data-show-big-reductions-key-antibiotics|title=US poultry data show big reductions in key antibiotics|last=CIDRAP|date=August 2019|website=Center for Infectious Disease Research and Policy, University of Minnesota|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref> Among the highlights in the report<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mindwalkconsultinggroup.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/Poultry_On-Farm_Antimicrobial_Use_Report_2013-2017.pdf|title=Estimates of On-Farm Antimicrobial Usage in Broiler Chicken and Turkey Production in the United States, 2013 \u2013 2017|last=Singer|first=Randall S|last2=Porter|first2=Leah|date=August 2019|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref> was a 95% decrease in in-feed tetracycline use in broiler chicks from 2013 to 2017, a 67% reduction in in-feed use of tetracycline in turkeys, and a 42% drop in hatchery use of gentamicin in turkey poults. This is an encouraging sign; the 53% overall reduction in antibiotic use seen in the UK between 2013 and 2018<ref name=\":15\" /><ref name=\":13\" /> was initiated from a voluntary stewardship programme developed by the UK poultry meat sector.<ref name=\":16\" />\n\n== Research into alternatives ==\nIncreasing concern due to the emergence of antibiotic-resistant bacteria has led researchers to look for alternatives to using antibiotics in livestock.<ref name=Allen>{{cite journal | author = Allen H. K. | author2=Trachsel J. | author3= Looft T. | author4= Casey T. A. | year = 2014 | title = Finding alternatives to antibiotics | journal = Annals of the New York Academy of Sciences | volume = 1323 | issue = 1| pages = 91\u2013100 | pmid = 24953233 | doi=10.1111/nyas.12468| bibcode=2014NYASA1323...91A}}</ref>\n\n[[Probiotics]], cultures of a single bacteria strain or mixture of different strains, are being studied in livestock as a production enhancer.<ref>{{cite journal | author = Hume M. E. | year = 2011 | title = Historic perspective: Prebiotics, probiotics, and other alternatives to antibiotics | url = http://naldc.nal.usda.gov/download/57525/PDF | journal = Poultry Science | volume = 90 | issue = 11| pages = 2663\u20139 | pmid = 22010256 | doi=10.3382/ps.2010-01030}}</ref>\n\n[[Prebiotics]] are non-digestible carbohydrates. The carbohydrates are mainly made up of oligosaccharides which are short chains of monosaccharides. The two most commonly studied prebiotics are fructooligosaccharides (FOS) and mannanoligosaccharides (MOS). FOS has been studied for use in chicken feed. MOS works as a competitive binding site, as bacteria bind to it rather than the intestine and are carried out.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Griggs |first1=J.P. |last2=Jacob |first2=J.P. |title=Alternatives to Antibiotics for Organic Poultry Production |journal=Journal of Applied Poultry Research |date=December 2005 |volume=14 |issue=4 |pages=750\u2013756 |doi=10.1093/japr/14.4.750}}</ref>\n\n[[Bacteriophages]] are able to infect most bacteria and are easily found in most environments colonized by bacteria, and have been studied as well.<ref name=Allen/>\n\nIn another study it was found that using probiotics, competitive exclusion, enzymes, immunomodulators and organic acids prevents the spread of bacteria and can all be used in place of antibiotics.<ref>Doyle, M.E. 2001: Alternatives to Antibiotic Use for Growth Promotion in Animal Husbandry. Food Research Institute, University of Wisconsin-Madison.</ref> Another research team was able to use bacteriocins, antimicrobial peptides and bacteriophages in the control of bacterial infections.<ref>{{cite journal | author = Joerger R.D. | year = 2003 | title = Alternatives to antibiotics: bacteriocins, antimicrobial peptides and bacteriophages | url = | journal = Poultry Science | volume = 82 | issue = 4| pages = 640\u2013647 | doi=10.1093/ps/82.4.640| pmid = 12710486}}</ref> While further research is needed in this field, alternative methods have been identified in effectively controlling bacterial infections in animals. All of the alternative methods listed pose no known threat to human health and all can lead the elimination of antibiotics in factory farms. With further research it is highly likely that a cost-effective and health-effective alternative could and will be found.\n\nOther alternatives include preventative approaches to keep the animals healthier and so reduce the need for antibiotics. These include improving the living conditions for animals, stimulating natural immunity through better nutrition, increasing biosecurity, implementing better management and hygiene practices, and ensuring better use of vaccination.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Antibiotic]]\n*[[Antibiotic misuse]]\n*[[Antimicrobial resistance]]\n*[[Antibiotic prophylaxis]] \n*[[List of antibiotic-resistant bacteria]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite web | last = Anomaly| first = Jonathan | url = https://dukespace.lib.duke.edu/dspace/bitstream/handle/10161/9733/Anomaly%20-%20Factory%20Farming.pdf%3bsequence=1 | title = What's Wrong with Factory Farming | publisher = Public Health Ethics | date = 2015}}\n* {{cite web | last = O'Neill| first = Jim | url = https://amr-review.org/sites/default/files/Antimicrobials%20in%20agriculture%20and%20the%20environment%20-%20Reducing%20unnecessary%20use%20and%20waste.pdf | title = Antimicrobials in Agriculture and the Environment | publisher = The Review on Antimicrobial Resistance | date = 2015}}\n*O'Neill, Jim (2016). [https://amr-review.org/sites/default/files/160525_Final%20paper_with%20cover.pdf \"Tackling Drug Resistance Globally: Final report and recommendations\"] (PDF)\n* [https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/shows/meat/safe/overview.html PBS report on antibiotics in livestock production]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=C_pr1T33-EM Fix Food, Fix Antibiotics], a 90-second video explaining the problem of antibiotic resistance and campaigning for action\n* [http://www.pewhealth.org/other-resource/record-high-antibiotic-sales-for-meat-and-poultry-production-85899449119 Pew Trust campaign] for restricting antibiotic use\n* [http://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/pkg/CHRG-111hhrg77921/pdf/CHRG-111hhrg77921.pdf Antibiotic Resistance and the Use of Antibiotics in Animal Agriculture: Hearing before the Subcommittee on Health of the Committee on Energy and Commerce, House of Representatives, One Hundred Eleventh Congress, Second Session, July 14, 2010]\n* [http://www.indiaenvironmentportal.org.in/search/?q=antibiotics Resources on antibiotic use and resistance]\n*[http://.farmantibiotics.org Farm Antibiotics] information website\n\n{{Antibiotics social and layman issues}}\n\n[[Category:Antibiotic resistance]]\n[[Category:Evolutionary biology]]\n[[Category:Food politics]]\n[[Category:Health disasters]]\n[[Category:Livestock]]\n[[Category:Meat industry]]\n[[Category:Pharmaceuticals policy]]\n[[Category:Veterinary medicine]]\n", "name_user": "Fant123", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antibiotic_use_in_livestock"}
{"title_page": "Nagin (1954 film)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2015}}\n{{other uses|Nagin (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Nagin\n| image          = Nagin 1954.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = Nandlal Jaswantlal\n| screenplay     = Hameed Butt\n| producer       = Mahendra Shah\n| story          = [[Bijon Bhattacharya]]\n| starring       = [[Vyjayanthimala]]<br>[[Pradeep Kumar]]<br>[[Jeevan]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1954}}\n| runtime        = 139 minutes\n| language       = Hindi\n| country        = [[India]]\n| music          = [[Hemanta Mukherjee| Hemant Kumar]]\n| cinematography = [[Fali Mistry]]\n| editing        = Babu Lavande\n}}\n\n'''''Nagin''''' is a [[Bollywood films of 1954|1954]] Indian [[Hindi-language]] [[romantic drama film]], directed by Nandlal Jaswantlal, and written by Hameed Butt and [[Bijon Bhattacharya]]. It stars [[Vyjayanthimala]] and [[Pradeep Kumar]], and has a hit musical score by [[Hemant Kumar]]. This film was partly produced in [[Technicolor]].\n\n== Synopsis ==\nTwo [[Adivasi]] tribes are in conflict for the local economic rights. The daughter of the Nagi tribe's chief, Mala ([[Vyjayanthimala]]), vows to kill the son of the Ragi tribe's chief, Sanatan ([[Pradeep Kumar]]), as revenge. Trespassing in the enemy territory, she is mesmerized by the music of a flute (played by the musician [[Kalyanji Virji Shah]]). Coming closer, she finds out that the player is Sanatan. They fall in love, but find it difficult to appease the enmity between the two tribes and to resist the attempts of the villain Prabir ([[Jeevan]]) to marry Mala.\n\n==Cast==\n\n* [[Vyjayanthimala]]... Mala\n* [[Pradeep Kumar]]... Sanatan\n* [[Jeevan]]... Prabir\n* [[Mubarak (actor)]]... Dhopal - The Nagi Chieftain\t\t\t\n* [[Ruby Mayer]]... Mala's Mother (as Sulochana)\n* [[I. S. Johar]]\n* Krishna Kumari (Hindi Actress)\n\n\n== Soundtrack ==\nThe film's soundtrack was composed by [[Hemanta Mukherjee|Hemant Kumar]]. It included thirteen tracks, including the hit \"Man Dole Mera Tan Dole\", whose \"Been music\" was performed by [[Kalyanji Virji Shah|Kalyanji]] on the [[clavioline]] and  by [[Ravi (music director)|Ravi]] on the [[harmonium]] (both once worked under Hemant Kumar's direction and later became independent music directors).<ref>[http://arpjournal.com/858/the-cultural-economy-of-sound-reinventing-technology-in-indian-popular-cinema/ Carlo Nardi (July 2011). \"The Cultural Economy of Sound: Reinventing Technology in Indian Popular Cinema\". ''Journal on the Art of Record Production'', Issue 5] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130615074412/http://arpjournal.com/858/the-cultural-economy-of-sound-reinventing-technology-in-indian-popular-cinema/ |date=15 June 2013 }} {{ISSN|1754-9892}}.</ref> It was released under E.P. and L.P. [[gramophone record]]s by The Gramophone Company of India, now known as [[Saregama]]. The lyrics were written by [[Rajinder Krishan]].\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! No. !! Title !! Artist(s)\n|-\n| 1 || \"Been Music\" || Kalyanji, Ravi\n|-\n| 2 || \"Man Dole Mera Tan Dole\" || [[Lata Mangeshkar]]\n|-\n| 3 || \"Tere Dwar Khada Ek Jogi\" || [[Hemanta Mukherjee| Hemant Kumar]]\n|-\n| 4 || \"Sun Rasiya Man Bhasiya\" || [[Lata Mangeshkar]]\n|-\n| 5 || \"Yaad Rakhna Pyar Ki Nishani\" || [[Hemant Kumar]], [[Asha Bhosle]], Chorus\n|-\n| 6 || \"Sun Ri Sakhi\" || [[Lata Mangeshkar]], Chorus\n|-\n| 7 || \"Mera Dil Ye Pukare Aaja\" || [[Lata Mangeshkar]]\n|-\n| 8 || \"Jadugar Saiyan\" || [[Lata Mangeshkar]]\n|-\n| 9 || \"Ari Chhod De Patang\" || [[Lata Mangeshkar]], [[Hemanta Mukherjee| Hemant Kumar]]\n|-\n| 10 || \"Mera Badli Mein Chhup Gaya Chand\" || [[Lata Mangeshkar]]\n|-\n| 11 || \"O Zindagi Ke Denewale\" || [[Hemanta Mukherjee| Hemant Kumar]], Chorus\n|-\n| 12 || \"Teri Yaad Mein Jalkar Dekh Liya\" || [[Lata Mangeshkar]]\n|-\n| 13 || \"Oonchi Oonchi Duniya Ki Deewarein\" || [[Lata Mangeshkar]]\n|}\n\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb title|0048410|Nagin}}\n\n[[Category:1954 films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:1950s Hindi-language films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Hemant Mukherjee]]\n\n\n{{1950s-Hindi-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2015}}\n{{other uses|Nagin (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Nagin\n| image          = Nagin 1954.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = Nandlal Jaswantlal\n| screenplay     = Hameed Butt\n| producer       = Mahendra Shah\n| story          = [[Bijon Bhattacharya]]\n| starring       = [[Vyjayanthimala]]<br>[[Pradeep Kumar]]<br>[[Jeevan]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1954}}\n| runtime        = 139 minutes\n| language       = Hindi\n| country        = [[India]]\n| music          = [[Hemanta Mukherjee| Hemant Kumar]]\n| cinematography = [[Fali Mistry]]\n| editing        = Babu Lavande\n}}\n\n'''''Nagin''''' is a [[Bollywood films of 1954|1954]] Indian [[Hindi-language]] [[romantic drama film]], directed by Nandlal Jaswantlal, and written by Hameed Butt and [[Bijon Bhattacharya]]. It stars [[Vyjayanthimala]] and [[Pradeep Kumar]], and has a hit musical score by [[Hemant Kumar]]. This film was partly produced in [[Technicolor]].\n\n== Synopsis ==\nTwo [[Adivasi]] tribes are in conflict for the local economic rights. The daughter of the Nagi tribe's chief, Mala ([[Vyjayanthimala]]), vows to kill the son of the Ragi tribe's chief, Sanatan ([[Pradeep Kumar]]), as revenge. Trespassing in the enemy territory, she is mesmerized by the music of a flute (played by the musician [[Kalyanji Virji Shah]]). Coming closer, she finds out that the player is Sanatan. They fall in love, but find it difficult to appease the enmity between the two tribes and to resist the attempts of the villain Prabir ([[Jeevan]]) to marry Mala.\n\n== Soundtrack ==\nThe film's soundtrack was composed by [[Hemanta Mukherjee|Hemant Kumar]]. It included thirteen tracks, including the hit \"Man Dole Mera Tan Dole\", whose \"Been music\" was performed by [[Kalyanji Virji Shah|Kalyanji]] on the [[clavioline]] and  by [[Ravi (music director)|Ravi]] on the [[harmonium]] (both once worked under Hemant Kumar's direction and later became independent music directors).<ref>[http://arpjournal.com/858/the-cultural-economy-of-sound-reinventing-technology-in-indian-popular-cinema/ Carlo Nardi (July 2011). \"The Cultural Economy of Sound: Reinventing Technology in Indian Popular Cinema\". ''Journal on the Art of Record Production'', Issue 5] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130615074412/http://arpjournal.com/858/the-cultural-economy-of-sound-reinventing-technology-in-indian-popular-cinema/ |date=15 June 2013 }} {{ISSN|1754-9892}}.</ref> It was released under E.P. and L.P. [[gramophone record]]s by The Gramophone Company of India, now known as [[Saregama]]. The lyrics were written by [[Rajinder Krishan]].\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! No. !! Title !! Artist(s)\n|-\n| 1 || \"Been Music\" || Kalyanji, Ravi\n|-\n| 2 || \"Man Dole Mera Tan Dole\" || [[Lata Mangeshkar]]\n|-\n| 3 || \"Tere Dwar Khada Ek Jogi\" || [[Hemanta Mukherjee| Hemant Kumar]]\n|-\n| 4 || \"Sun Rasiya Man Bhasiya\" || [[Lata Mangeshkar]]\n|-\n| 5 || \"Yaad Rakhna Pyar Ki Nishani\" || [[Hemant Kumar]], [[Asha Bhosle]], Chorus\n|-\n| 6 || \"Sun Ri Sakhi\" || [[Lata Mangeshkar]], Chorus\n|-\n| 7 || \"Mera Dil Ye Pukare Aaja\" || [[Lata Mangeshkar]]\n|-\n| 8 || \"Jadugar Saiyan\" || [[Lata Mangeshkar]]\n|-\n| 9 || \"Ari Chhod De Patang\" || [[Lata Mangeshkar]], [[Hemanta Mukherjee| Hemant Kumar]]\n|-\n| 10 || \"Mera Badli Mein Chhup Gaya Chand\" || [[Lata Mangeshkar]]\n|-\n| 11 || \"O Zindagi Ke Denewale\" || [[Hemanta Mukherjee| Hemant Kumar]], Chorus\n|-\n| 12 || \"Teri Yaad Mein Jalkar Dekh Liya\" || [[Lata Mangeshkar]]\n|-\n| 13 || \"Oonchi Oonchi Duniya Ki Deewarein\" || [[Lata Mangeshkar]]\n|}\n\n==Cast==\n\n* [[Vyjayanthimala]]... Mala\n* [[Pradeep Kumar]]... Sanatan\n* [[Jeevan]]... Prabir\n* [[Mubarak (actor)]]... Dhopal - The Nagi Chieftain\t\t\t\n* [[Ruby Mayer]]... Mala's Mother (as Sulochana)\n* [[I. S. Johar]]\n* Krishna Kumari (Hindi Actress)\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb title|0048410|Nagin}}\n\n[[Category:1954 films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:1950s Hindi-language films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Hemant Mukherjee]]\n\n\n{{1950s-Hindi-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ratnil1", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nagin_(1954_film)"}
{"title_page": "GPS disciplined oscillator", "text_new": "A '''GPS clock''', or '''GPS disciplined oscillator''' ('''GPSDO'''), is a combination of a [[GPS]] receiver and a high-quality, stable oscillator such as a [[Crystal oven|quartz]] or [[Rubidium standard|rubidium oscillator]] whose output is controlled to agree with the signals broadcast by GPS or other [[GNSS]] satellites.<ref>http://www.4timing.com/SyncGPS.pdf</ref><ref>[http://tf.nist.gov/general/enc-d.htm Time and Frequency from A to Z<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\nGPSDOs work well as a source of timing because the satellite time signals must be accurate in order to provide positional accuracy for GPS in navigation. These signals are accurate to nanoseconds and provide a good reference for timing applications.<ref name=autogenerated1>http://tf.nist.gov/general/pdf/2297.pdf</ref><ref>http://www.rt66.com/~shera/QST_GPS.pdf</ref>\n\n[[File:GPS disciplined oscillator unit.jpg|thumb|A GPS disciplined oscillator unit with a GPS antenna input, 10 MHz and 1 [[Pulse-per-second signal|pulse-per-second (PPS)]] outputs, and an [[RS232]] interface.]]\n\n==Applications==\nGPSDOs serve as an indispensable source of timing in a range of applications, and some technology applications would not be practical without them.<ref>http://www.dtic.mil/cgi-bin/GetTRDoc?Location=U2&doc=GetTRDoc.pdf&AD=ADA484160</ref>\nGPSDOs are used as the basis for [[Coordinated Universal Time]] (UTC) around the world. UTC is the official accepted standard for time and frequency. UTC is controlled by the Bureau International des Poids et Mesures ([[BIPM]]). Timing centers around the world [[Global Positioning System#Timekeeping|use GPS]] to align their own time scales to UTC.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.agilent.com/metrology/gps-do_report.shtml |title=Agilent {{!}} GPS-DO Performance<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=2011-10-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120117071732/http://www.agilent.com/metrology/gps-do_report.shtml |archive-date=2012-01-17 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=autogenerated2>{{Cite web |url=http://tycho.usno.navy.mil/ptti/1998/Vol%2030_15.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=2011-10-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120112231810/http://tycho.usno.navy.mil/ptti/1998/Vol%2030_15.pdf |archive-date=2012-01-12 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\nGPS based standards are used to [[Holdover in synchronization applications#The Importance of GPS Derived Timing|provide synchronization to wireless base stations]]<ref>[http://www.prc68.com/I/timefreq.shtml#CDMA Time & Frequency<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> and serve well in standards laboratories as an alternative to [[caesium standard|cesium-based references]].<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\nGPSDOs can be used to provide synchronization of multiple RF receivers, allowing for RF phase coherent operation among the receivers<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2018-03-08|title=What is a GPS/Multi-GNSS Disciplined Oscillator (GPSDO/GNSSDO)?|url=http://www.furuno.com/en/gnss/technical/gnssdo|website=www.furuno.com}}</ref> and applications, such as [[passive radar]] and [[ionosonde]]s.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2018-03-08|title=GNU Chirp Sounder|url=http://www.sgo.fi/~j/gnu_chirp_sounder/|website=www.sgo.fi}}</ref>\n\n==Operation==\n[[File:GPSDO.png|thumb|left|A modern GPSDO]]\nA GPSDO works by disciplining, or steering a high quality [[crystal oscillator|quartz]] or rubidium oscillator by locking the output to a GPS signal via a tracking loop. The disciplining mechanism works in a similar way to a [[phase-locked loop]] (PLL), but in most GPSDOs the loop filter is replaced with a [[microcontroller]] that uses software to compensate for not only the phase and frequency changes of the local oscillator, but also for the \"learned\" effects of aging, temperature, and other environmental parameters.<ref name=autogenerated1 /><ref>[http://www.symmetricom.com/products/gps-solutions/gps-time-frequency-receivers/4411A/ 4411A<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nOne of the keys to the usefulness of a GPSDO as a timing reference is the way it is able to combine the stability characteristics of the GPS signal and the oscillator controlled by the tracking loop. GPS receivers have excellent long-term stability (as characterized by their [[Allan variance|Allan deviation]])<ref name=autogenerated2 /> at averaging times greater than several hours. However, their short-term stability is degraded by limitations of the internal resolution of the [[Pulse-per-second signal|one pulse per second (1PPS)]] reference timing circuits, [[Radio propagation|signal propagation]] effects such as [[multipath interference]], atmospheric conditions, and other impairments. On the other hand, a quality oven-controlled oscillator has better short-term stability but is susceptible to thermal, aging, and other long-term effects. A GPSDO aims to utilize the best of both sources, combining the short-term stability performance of the oscillator with the long-term stability of the GPS signals to give a reference source with excellent overall stability characteristics.<ref>http://www.ko4bb.com/Timing/FAQ-2.php#[Def1]</ref>\n\nGPSDOs typically phase-align the internal flywheel oscillator to the GPS signal by using dividers to generate a 1PPS signal from the reference oscillator, then phase comparing this 1PPS signal to the GPS-generated 1PPS signal and using the phase differences to control the local oscillator frequency in small adjustments via the tracking loop.<ref>{{cite book|first1=Dan|last1=Doberstein|title=Fundamentals of GPS Receivers: A Hardware Approach|url=https://books.google.com/?id=EQV0hBF25bkC&pg=PA155&dq=gps+disciplined+oscillator+design#v=onepage&q=gps%2520disciplined%2520oscillator%2520design&f=false|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|date=22 October 2011|isbn=9781461404095|via=Google Books}}</ref> This differentiates GPSDOs from their cousins NCOs ([[numerically controlled oscillator]]). Rather than disciplining an oscillator via frequency adjustments, NCOs typically use a free-running, low-cost crystal oscillator and adjust the output phase by digitally lengthening or shortening the output phase many times per second in large phase steps assuring that on average the number of phase transitions per second is aligned to the GPS receiver reference source. This guarantees frequency accuracy at the expense of high phase noise and jitter, a degradation that true GPSDOs do not suffer.\n\nWhen the GPS signal becomes unavailable, the GPSDO goes into a state of [[Holdover in synchronization applications|holdover]], where it tries to maintain accurate timing using only the internal oscillator.\n\nSophisticated algorithms are used to compensate for the aging and temperature stability of the oscillator while the GPSDO is in holdover.<ref>{{Cite book |doi = 10.1109/FREQ.1996.560284|isbn = 0-7803-3309-8|chapter = Adaptive temperature compensation of GPS disciplined quartz and rubidium oscillators|title = Proceedings of 1996 IEEE International Frequency Control Symposium|year = 1996|last1 = Penrod|first1 = B.M.|pages = 980\u2013987}}</ref>\n\nThe use of [[Error analysis for the Global Positioning System#GPS SA|Selective Availability]] (SA) prior to May 2000 restricted the accuracy of GPS signals available for civilian use and in turn presented challenges to the accuracy of GPSDO derived timing. The turning off of SA resulted in a significant increase in the accuracy that GPSDOs can offer.<ref>[http://www.leapsecond.com/pages/saoff/ Effect of no SA on HP 58503A GPS Time & Frequency Receiver<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\nGPSDOs are capable of generating frequency accuracies and stabilities on the order of parts per billion for even entry-level, low-cost units, to parts per trillion for more advanced units within minutes after power-on, and are thus one of the highest-accuracy physically-derived reference standards available.\n\n==References==\n<!--- See http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Footnotes on how to create references using <ref></ref> tags which will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.jrmiller.demon.co.uk/projects/freqstd/frqstd.htm GPS Disciplined 10MHz Oscillator]\n*[http://www.jackson-labs.com GPS Disciplined Oscillator Modules]\n*[http://www.vectron.com/products/modules/md-010.htm Disciplined Oscillator Module]\n*[https://www.nist.gov/pml/div688/grp40/receiverlist.cfm Manufacturers of Time and Frequency Receivers]\n*[http://ve2zaz.net/GPS_Std/GPS_Std.htm A Simplified GPS-Derived Frequency Standard]\n*[http://www.ik0otg.net/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=53%3Aoscillatore-10mhz-sinc-gps GPS synchronized 10MHz oscillator]\n\n[[Category:Synchronization]]\n", "text_old": "A '''GPS clock''', or '''GPS disciplined oscillator''' ('''GPSDO'''), is a combination of a [[GPS]] receiver and a high-quality, stable oscillator such as a [[Crystal oven|quartz]] or [[Rubidium standard|rubidium oscillator]] whose output is controlled to agree with the signals broadcast by GPS or other [[GNSS]] satellites.<ref>http://www.4timing.com/SyncGPS.pdf</ref><ref>[http://tf.nist.gov/general/enc-d.htm Time and Frequency from A to Z<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\nGPSDOs work well as a source of timing because the satellite time signals must be accurate in order to provide positional accuracy for GPS in navigation. These signals are accurate to nanoseconds and provide a good reference for timing applications.<ref name=autogenerated1>http://tf.nist.gov/general/pdf/2297.pdf</ref><ref>http://www.rt66.com/~shera/QST_GPS.pdf</ref>\n\n[[File:GPS disciplined oscillator unit.jpg|thumb|A GPS disciplined oscillator unit with a GPS antenna input, 10 MHz and 1 pulse-per-second (PPS) outputs, and an [[RS232]] interface.]]\n\n==Applications==\nGPSDOs serve as an indispensable source of timing in a range of applications, and some technology applications would not be practical without them.<ref>http://www.dtic.mil/cgi-bin/GetTRDoc?Location=U2&doc=GetTRDoc.pdf&AD=ADA484160</ref>\nGPSDOs are used as the basis for [[Coordinated Universal Time]] (UTC) around the world. UTC is the official accepted standard for time and frequency. UTC is controlled by the Bureau International des Poids et Mesures ([[BIPM]]). Timing centers around the world [[Global Positioning System#Timekeeping|use GPS]] to align their own time scales to UTC.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.agilent.com/metrology/gps-do_report.shtml |title=Agilent {{!}} GPS-DO Performance<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=2011-10-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120117071732/http://www.agilent.com/metrology/gps-do_report.shtml |archive-date=2012-01-17 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=autogenerated2>{{Cite web |url=http://tycho.usno.navy.mil/ptti/1998/Vol%2030_15.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=2011-10-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120112231810/http://tycho.usno.navy.mil/ptti/1998/Vol%2030_15.pdf |archive-date=2012-01-12 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\nGPS based standards are used to [[Holdover in synchronization applications#The Importance of GPS Derived Timing|provide synchronization to wireless base stations]]<ref>[http://www.prc68.com/I/timefreq.shtml#CDMA Time & Frequency<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> and serve well in standards laboratories as an alternative to [[caesium standard|cesium-based references]].<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\nGPSDOs can be used to provide synchronization of multiple RF receivers, allowing for RF phase coherent operation among the receivers<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2018-03-08|title=What is a GPS/Multi-GNSS Disciplined Oscillator (GPSDO/GNSSDO)?|url=http://www.furuno.com/en/gnss/technical/gnssdo|website=www.furuno.com}}</ref> and applications, such as [[passive radar]] and [[ionosonde]]s.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2018-03-08|title=GNU Chirp Sounder|url=http://www.sgo.fi/~j/gnu_chirp_sounder/|website=www.sgo.fi}}</ref>\n\n==Operation==\n[[File:GPSDO.png|thumb|left|A modern GPSDO]]\nA GPSDO works by disciplining, or steering a high quality [[crystal oscillator|quartz]] or rubidium oscillator by locking the output to a GPS signal via a tracking loop. The disciplining mechanism works in a similar way to a [[phase-locked loop]] (PLL), but in most GPSDOs the loop filter is replaced with a [[microcontroller]] that uses software to compensate for not only the phase and frequency changes of the local oscillator, but also for the \"learned\" effects of aging, temperature, and other environmental parameters.<ref name=autogenerated1 /><ref>[http://www.symmetricom.com/products/gps-solutions/gps-time-frequency-receivers/4411A/ 4411A<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nOne of the keys to the usefulness of a GPSDO as a timing reference is the way it is able to combine the stability characteristics of the GPS signal and the oscillator controlled by the tracking loop. GPS receivers have excellent long-term stability (as characterized by their [[Allan variance|Allan deviation]])<ref name=autogenerated2 /> at averaging times greater than several hours. However, their short-term stability is degraded by limitations of the internal resolution of the one pulse per second (1PPS) reference timing circuits, [[Radio propagation|signal propagation]] effects such as [[multipath interference]], atmospheric conditions, and other impairments. On the other hand, a quality oven-controlled oscillator has better short-term stability but is susceptible to thermal, aging, and other long-term effects. A GPSDO aims to utilize the best of both sources, combining the short-term stability performance of the oscillator with the long-term stability of the GPS signals to give a reference source with excellent overall stability characteristics.<ref>http://www.ko4bb.com/Timing/FAQ-2.php#[Def1]</ref>\n\nGPSDOs typically phase-align the internal flywheel oscillator to the GPS signal by using dividers to generate a 1PPS signal from the reference oscillator, then phase comparing this 1PPS signal to the GPS-generated 1PPS signal and using the phase differences to control the local oscillator frequency in small adjustments via the tracking loop.<ref>{{cite book|first1=Dan|last1=Doberstein|title=Fundamentals of GPS Receivers: A Hardware Approach|url=https://books.google.com/?id=EQV0hBF25bkC&pg=PA155&dq=gps+disciplined+oscillator+design#v=onepage&q=gps%2520disciplined%2520oscillator%2520design&f=false|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|date=22 October 2011|isbn=9781461404095|via=Google Books}}</ref> This differentiates GPSDOs from their cousins NCOs ([[numerically controlled oscillator]]). Rather than disciplining an oscillator via frequency adjustments, NCOs typically use a free-running, low-cost crystal oscillator and adjust the output phase by digitally lengthening or shortening the output phase many times per second in large phase steps assuring that on average the number of phase transitions per second is aligned to the GPS receiver reference source. This guarantees frequency accuracy at the expense of high phase noise and jitter, a degradation that true GPSDOs do not suffer.\n\nWhen the GPS signal becomes unavailable, the GPSDO goes into a state of [[Holdover in synchronization applications|holdover]], where it tries to maintain accurate timing using only the internal oscillator.\n\nSophisticated algorithms are used to compensate for the aging and temperature stability of the oscillator while the GPSDO is in holdover.<ref>{{Cite book |doi = 10.1109/FREQ.1996.560284|isbn = 0-7803-3309-8|chapter = Adaptive temperature compensation of GPS disciplined quartz and rubidium oscillators|title = Proceedings of 1996 IEEE International Frequency Control Symposium|year = 1996|last1 = Penrod|first1 = B.M.|pages = 980\u2013987}}</ref>\n\nThe use of [[Error analysis for the Global Positioning System#GPS SA|Selective Availability]] (SA) prior to May 2000 restricted the accuracy of GPS signals available for civilian use and in turn presented challenges to the accuracy of GPSDO derived timing. The turning off of SA resulted in a significant increase in the accuracy that GPSDOs can offer.<ref>[http://www.leapsecond.com/pages/saoff/ Effect of no SA on HP 58503A GPS Time & Frequency Receiver<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\nGPSDOs are capable of generating frequency accuracies and stabilities on the order of parts per billion for even entry-level, low-cost units, to parts per trillion for more advanced units within minutes after power-on, and are thus one of the highest-accuracy physically-derived reference standards available.\n\n==References==\n<!--- See http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Footnotes on how to create references using <ref></ref> tags which will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.jrmiller.demon.co.uk/projects/freqstd/frqstd.htm GPS Disciplined 10MHz Oscillator]\n*[http://www.jackson-labs.com GPS Disciplined Oscillator Modules]\n*[http://www.vectron.com/products/modules/md-010.htm Disciplined Oscillator Module]\n*[https://www.nist.gov/pml/div688/grp40/receiverlist.cfm Manufacturers of Time and Frequency Receivers]\n*[http://ve2zaz.net/GPS_Std/GPS_Std.htm A Simplified GPS-Derived Frequency Standard]\n*[http://www.ik0otg.net/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=53%3Aoscillatore-10mhz-sinc-gps GPS synchronized 10MHz oscillator]\n\n[[Category:Synchronization]]\n", "name_user": "Nvtj", "label": "safe", "comment": "adding links toPulse-per-second signal", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/GPS_disciplined_oscillator"}
{"title_page": "Water supply and sanitation in the Wellington region", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n'''Water supply and sanitation in the Wellington region''' involves the provision of the \"three waters\" \u2013 [[drinking water]], [[stormwater]], and [[wastewater]] services in the Greater Wellington region.\n\nThe provision of these services in the [[Wellington]] urban area is the responsibility of five councils: [[Wellington City Council|Wellington City]], [[Lower Hutt|Hutt]], [[Upper Hutt]] and [[Porirua]] city councils, and the [[Wellington Region|Greater Wellington]] Regional Council.  However, the water assets of these councils are managed by an [[infrastructure asset management]] company, [[Wellington Water]]. From 1 October 2019, Wellington Water also became the asset manager of the water assets of the [[South Wairarapa District]] Council.  \n<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= South Wairarapa District Council joins Wellington Water|url= https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/AK1909/S00704/south-wairarapa-district-council-joins-wellington-water.htm|work= Scoop|location= |date= 26 September 2019|access-date= 12 April 2020|archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200411215909/https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/AK1909/S00704/south-wairarapa-district-council-joins-wellington-water.htm|archive-date=12 April 2020}}</ref>\nWellington Water is jointly owned by all six councils.\n<ref>{{cite web| url=https://app.companiesoffice.govt.nz/companies/app/ui/pages/companies/1337122/shareholdings| title= Wellington Water Limited (1337122)| publisher= New Zealand Companies Office| accessdate=2 April 2020|archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200409030103/https://app.companiesoffice.govt.nz/companies/app/ui/pages/companies/1337122/shareholdings|archive-date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\nThe assets in the region covered by these six councils includes 6,300&nbsp;km of pipes, 138 reservoirs, 249 pump stations and four drinking water treatment plants.\n<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.wellingtonwater.co.nz/your-water/overview/| title= Overview -Your water| publisher= Wellington Water| accessdate=8 April 2020|archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200409025904/https://www.wellingtonwater.co.nz/your-water/overview/|archive-date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThree waters services for the remaining parts of the Greater Wellington region are provided by the [[Kapiti Coast District]] Council, the [[Carterton, New Zealand|Carterton]] District Council and [[Masterton]] District Council.\n\nThe challenges for managing the three waters in the Wellington region include the deteriorated condition of pipelines in the Wellington urban area.  The pipelines are in significantly worse condition than those in other large networks nationwide, and there has been a recent history of serious failures.  The water supply to the region is also at significant risk during a severe earthquake, although some projects are underway to improve resilience.\n\nWater supplies to the Wellington urban area meet the requirements of the Health Act and conform with drinking water standards.  However, for some of the towns in the Kapiti Coast and Wairarapa regions, there have been occasional non-conformances with the required standards for drinking water quality and safety.\n\nBenchmarking data published by Water New Zealand as part of their 2018/19 National Performance Review showed that capital expenditure on three waters assets in the Wellington urban area is well below the average of the expenditure on networks in most other major centres, and for the wastewater network, expenditure was the lowest out of the seven large networks in the review.\n<ref name=\"Capex\">{{cite web| url=https://www.waternz.org.nz/Category?Action=View&Category_id=1018| title= Annual capital expenditure per property connected to the network| publisher= Water New Zealand| accessdate=13 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n==Drinking water==\n===Regional water supply networks===\nThe supply of reticulated drinking water is regulated under the Health Act, and suppliers are registered and subject to a testing regime.  The registered water suppliers for the Greater Wellington region are listed in annual drinking water quality reports published by the Ministry of Health. \n<ref name=\"MoH_quality_report\">{{cite web| url=https://www.health.govt.nz/system/files/documents/publications/drinking-water-annual-report-appendix-1-revised-aug2019.pdf| title= Annual Report on Drinking-water Quality 2017\u201318 \u2013 Appendix 1: Water supply compliance| publisher= Ministry of Health| date= June 2019| accessdate=10 April 2020 |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200409204622/https://www.health.govt.nz/system/files/documents/publications/drinking-water-annual-report-appendix-1-revised-aug2019.pdf |archive-date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Supplier !! Region/ Town !! Population\n|-\n| Greater Wellington Water || Wellington urban area \u2013 bulk supply || 350,000\n|-\n| Hutt City Council || Lower Hutt || 95,469\n|-\n| Kapiti Coast District Council || Otaki || 5,700\n|-\n| Kapiti Coast District Council || Paekakariki || 1,665\n|-\n| Kapiti Coast District Council || Waikanae, Paraparaumu, Raumati || 35,800\n|-\n| Porirua City Council || Porirua || 46,444\n|-\n| Upper Hutt City Council || Upper Hutt || 34,650\n|-\n| Wellington City Council || Wellington City || 165,126\n|-\n| Carterton District Council || Carterton || 4,200\n|-\n| Masterton District Council || Masterton || 19,000\n|-\n| Opaki Water Supply Association || Opaki || 1,500\n|-\n| South Wairarapa District Council || Featherston || 2,580\n|-\n| South Wairarapa District Council || Greytown || 1,952\n|-\n| South Wairarapa District Council || Martinborough || 1,505\n|}\nThis table omits several small supplies serving populations less than 1,000.\n\n===Water sources for Wellington urban area===\nWater supply for the Wellington urban area comes from three sources:\n<ref name=\"Sources\">{{cite web| url=https://www.wellingtonwater.co.nz/your-water/drinking-water/where-does-it-come-from/| title= Where does it come from?| publisher= Wellington Water| accessdate=7 April 2020 |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200409031320/https://www.wellingtonwater.co.nz/your-water/drinking-water/where-does-it-come-from/ |archive-date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n* Hutt River\n* Wainuiomata and Orongorongo rivers\n* Waiwhetu aquifer\n\nThere are times each year, particularly during summer months, where the total demand is greater than can be supplied from these sources.  There are two large storage lakes that can be used to supplement the supply during these periods.\n\n====Hutt River catchment====\nThe [[Hutt River (New Zealand)|Hutt river]] water supply catchment covers almost 9,000 hectares of bush-clad mountains and valleys at the southern edge of the [[Tararua Forest Park]] and adjoining the [[Kaitoke Regional Park]]. Rainwater from tributary streams flows into the Hutt River and is intercepted at a [[weir]] at [[Kaitoke]], north of [[Upper Hutt]].  The water is then strained to remove sticks, leaves and silt, and piped through tunnels to the [[Te Marua]] Water Treatment Plant. Up to 150 million litres of water per day may be diverted from the Hutt River, provided an adequate flow is maintained downstream of the weir. The Hutt water supply catchment provides about 40 percent of the water used in the Wellington urban area each year.<ref name=\"Sources\" />\n\n====Macaskill storage lakes====\nThere are two large storage lakes at Te Marua \u2013 the Macaskill Lakes. These lakes are filled from the Hutt River intake when the water is clean and there is sufficient flow available. Stored water is pumped from the lakes into the treatment plant when there is not enough water in the river to meet public demand.  The storage lakes are also used to meet demand when the river is too dirty \u2013 after heavy rainfall \u2013 or when it is in flood and the intake is closed to prevent rocks and gravel from entering the intake pipes.\n\nThe Macaskill Lakes are 17.3 metres deep and have a combined usable capacity of approximately 3,350 million litres, or enough to meet average water use for around 23 days.<ref name=\"Sources\" />\n\nBuilding the lakes was first proposed in 1975. The construction of the two lakes proved difficult because of weather and on-site conditions, resulting in cost increases and litigation.  There were also problems with leaks after completion, leading to further litigation.\n<ref>{{cite news |last= O'Neill |first= Andrea |title= Upper Hutt lakes leak water and money |url= https://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/news/69822534/upper-hutt-lakes-leak-water-and-money---150-years-of-news |work= Stuff |location= |date= 30 June 2015|access-date= 7 April 2020 | archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200412011422/https://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/news/69822534/upper-hutt-lakes-leak-water-and-money---150-years-of-news |archive-date=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Wainuiomata/Orongorongo rivers====\nThe Wainuiomata/Orongorongo water supply catchment area lies within the [[Remutaka Range]]s to the east of [[Wainuiomata]]. The collection area covers 7,600 hectares. Five low dams (weirs) with intake pipes provide water from the rivers to the Wainuiomata Water Treatment Plant. These catchment areas provide approximately 20% of the water used in the Wellington urban area each year.<ref name=\"Sources\"/>\n\n====Waiwhetu aquifer====\nThe Waiwhetu [[artesian aquifer]] is a zone of water-retaining sand, gravel and boulders beneath the Hutt Valley. Water from the Hutt River starts to flow underground around Taita Gorge. From Melling southwards, the water becomes naturally pressurised beneath a layer of hard clay. This pressurised zone, the Waiwhetu artesian aquifer, stretches as far south as the harbour. It is estimated to be up to 70 metres thick at its western edge against the Wellington fault line, and 20 metres thick at the eastern edge of the harbour. The pressure in the aquifer has resulted in several fresh water springs in the harbour floor.\n\nWater takes more than 12 months to pass through the aquifer to wells where it is extracted for distribution via the water network. Extraction is monitored and controlled to minimise the risk of [[saline intrusion]]. The Waiwhetu aquifer provides around 40 percent of the annual water supply.<ref name=\"Sources\" />\n\nThe Te Puna Wai Ora (Spring of Life) in Buick Street, [[Petone]] provides untreated water from the aquifer free to the public. \n<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.jacksonstreet.co.nz/listing/te-puna-wai-ora-spring-of-life/\n| title= Te Puna Wai Ora (Spring of Life)| publisher= Jackson Street Program| archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200409022604/https://www.jacksonstreet.co.nz/listing/te-puna-wai-ora-spring-of-life/|archive-date=9 April 2020| accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.huttvalleynz.com/upload/documents/petone_water.pdf| title= Hutt City \u2013 Petone's Artesian Water |publisher= Hutt City Council |date=13 May 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100513230407/http://www.huttvalleynz.com/upload/documents/Petone_water.pdf|archive-date= 5 April 2012 }}</ref>\n\n===Water sources for remaining areas===\n\nThe water sources for the South Wairarapa District Council area are the [[Waiohine River|Waiohine]] catchment for Featherston, the Kuratawhiti Street bore for Greytown residents, and the Herricks bore field for users in Martinborough. \n<ref name=\"SWDC\">{{cite web| url=https://www.swdc.govt.nz/water-and-sewerage#water| title= Water and sewerage| publisher= South Wairarapa District Council | accessdate=7 April 2020 |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200409085630/https://www.swdc.govt.nz/water-and-sewerage |archive-date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nWater supplies for the Kapiti Coast region are sourced from combination of bores and surface water from the [[Waikanae]] River.\n<ref name=\"Kapiti_water\">{{cite web| url=https://www.kapiticoast.govt.nz/services/a-z-council-services-and-facilities/water/| title= Water supply| publisher= Kapiti Coast District Council | accessdate=10 April 2020 |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200410091317/https://www.kapiticoast.govt.nz/services/a-z-council-services-and-facilities/water/ |archive-date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nWater supply for the Carterton district comes from the Kaipatangata Stream and two underground bores.\n<ref name=\"Carterton_water\">{{cite web| url=https://cdc.govt.nz/services/water | title= Water supply| publisher= Carterton District Council | accessdate=10 April 2020 |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200410091614/https://cdc.govt.nz/services/water/ |archive-date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nMasterton's drinking water is sourced Waingawa River, about 10&nbsp;km west of Masterton.\n<ref name=\"Masterton_water\">{{cite web| url=https://mstn.govt.nz/services/water-services/| title= Services \u2013 Water| publisher= Masterton District Council | accessdate=10 April 2020 |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200410091846/https://mstn.govt.nz/services/water-services/%7C |archive-date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Water treatment===\n====Wellington urban area====\nThere are four [[Water purification|water treatment]] plants located in the Hutt Valley (Te Marua, Waterloo, Gear Island and Wainuiomata). These plants supply water for use in Upper Hutt, Lower Hutt, Porirua and Wellington cities.\n<ref>{{cite web| url=https://wellington.govt.nz/services/environment-and-waste/water/wellingtons-water-supply/water-treatment | title= Water treatment| publisher= Wellington City Council| accessdate=9 April 2020|archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200409075257/https://wellington.govt.nz/services/environment-and-waste/water/wellingtons-water-supply/water-treatment |archive-date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\nThe treatment processes at the four treatment plants differ based on the characteristics of the incoming water.\n\nAt the Te Marua water treatment plant, the main treatment processes are:\n<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.wellingtonwater.co.nz/dmsdocument/385 | title= Te Marua Water Treatment Plant Technical Information| date= January 2008| publisher= Greater Wellington Regional Council| via= Wellington Water| accessdate=9 April 2020|archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200409081435/https://www.wellingtonwater.co.nz/dmsdocument/385 |archive-date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n* Straining\n* [[Coagulation (water treatment)|Coagulation]] and [[flocculation]]\n* [[Sedimentation (water treatment)|Sedimentation]]\n* [[Filtration]]\n* [[Water chlorination|Chlorination]]\n* [[Water purification#pH adjustment|pH adjustment]]\n* [[Water fluoridation|Fluoridation]]\n\nThe Gear Island and Waterloo plants both treat water that is drawn from the Waiwhetu aquifer.\n\n===Pipeline age and condition===\nThe 2018/19 National Performance Review published by Water New Zealand compares the average pipeline age and condition across water supply networks. The data for the Wellington water supply network shows that 20% of the pipelines are in poor or very poor condition.  The Wellington network ranks the worst  on this measure out of the six large supply networks nationwide.\n<ref name=\"Pipeline_condition\">{{cite web| url=https://www.waternz.org.nz/Category?Action=View&Category_id=1008| title= National performance review \u2013 Pipeline condition| publisher= Water New Zealand| accessdate=9 April 2020 }}</ref>\nThe review also includes average pipeline age. The Wellington network has an average age of 43 years, and ranks as the second oldest of the six large supply networks.\n<ref name=\"Pipeline_age\">{{cite web| url=https://www.waternz.org.nz/Category?Action=View&Category_id=1007| title= National performance review \u2013 Pipeline age| publisher= Water New Zealand| accessdate=9 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n===Consumption, losses and metering===\nDuring a prolonged dry spell in November 2017, Wellington Water reported that weekend consumption in the Wellington urban area reached 171 million litres for the day \u2013 around 30 million litres more than a typical day, and the highest November daily consumption in five years. Wellington Water called on consumers to cut back on their water use, and make sure they observe garden watering restrictions.\n<ref>{{cite news |last= Shelton |first= Lindsay |title= Water use soars; cut back on using water, says Wellington Water |url= http://wellington.scoop.co.nz/?p=105145 |work= Scoop |location= |date= 22 November 2017|access-date= 9 April 2020|archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200409030309/http://wellington.scoop.co.nz/?p=105145|archive-date= 9 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\nA National Performance Review published by Water New Zealand for the 2019 financial year showed that daily residential consumption in the Wellington metropolitan region was about 226 litres per person. By way of comparison, daily residential water use in Auckland and Tauranga was significantly lower at about 156 and 189 litres per person respectively. Both Auckland and Tauranga have water metering in place for all residences, but in Wellington only around 1% of residential supplies are currently metered.\n<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.waternz.org.nz/Category?Action=View&Category_id=1010| title= National performance review \u2013 Residential water efficiency| publisher= Water New Zealand| accessdate=9 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\nThe same National Performance Review also compares water losses between supply networks.  The data for Wellington shows that despite having a higher than average system pressure, the water losses (reported as an infrastructure leakage index), were lower than average, and approaching a threshold where action to reduce losses even further could be uneconomic unless there are shortages.\n<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.waternz.org.nz/Category?Action=View&Category_id=1023| title= National performance review \u2013 Water losses| publisher= Water New Zealand| accessdate=9 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\nIn their submission to a Wellington City Council Water Committee, Wellington Water warned  that \"current water consumption and a growing population will lead to water shortages by 2040\".\n<ref>{{cite news |last= Fonseka |first= Dileepa  |title= Water meters suggested as Wellington faces water shortage |url= https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/110782642/water-meters-suggested-as-wellington-faces-water-shortage |work= Stuff |location= |date= 13 December 2019|access-date= 22 February 2019 |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200409030927/https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/110782642/water-meters-suggested-as-wellington-faces-water-shortage |archive-date=9 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, it was reported that Wellington City Council was considering installing water meters for all domestic consumers.\n<ref>{{cite news |last= McManus |first= Joel |title= Councillors considering water metering to solve Wellington pipe woes |url= https://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/news/wellington/119959891/councillors-considering-water-metering-to-solve-wellington-pipe-woes |work= Stuff |location= |date= 4 March 2020| access-date= 7 April 2020 |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200409031054/https://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/news/wellington/119959891/councillors-considering-water-metering-to-solve-wellington-pipe-woes |archive-date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\nAt the time of that report, only 1,200 residential properties in Wellington were using water meters.\n<ref>{{cite web| url=https://wellington.govt.nz/services/environment-and-waste/water/water-meters| title= Water meters| publisher= Wellington City Council| accessdate=7 April 2020 |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200409031212/https://wellington.govt.nz/services/environment-and-waste/water/water-meters |archive-date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2017, the Kapiti Coast District Council reported that there had been a drop in consumption of more than 26% since water meters were installed in July 2014.\n<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.kcnews.co.nz/story.php?storyID=11044| title= Kapiti Council says no water restrictions here| publisher= KC News| date=7 December 2017| accessdate=11 April 2020 |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200411030730/https://www.kcnews.co.nz/story.php?storyID=11044 |archive-date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Quality and safety===\nDrinking water is subject to a regime of testing under the Health Act to verify that the water meets standards.\n\nThe summary results of compliance testing for the 2017/18 year were:\n<ref name=\"MoH_quality_report\">{{cite web| url=https://www.health.govt.nz/system/files/documents/publications/drinking-water-annual-report-appendix-1-revised-aug2019.pdf| title= Annual Report on Drinking-water Quality 2017\u201318 \u2013 Appendix 1: Water supply compliance| publisher= Ministry of Health| date= June 2019| accessdate=10 April 2020 |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200409204622/https://www.health.govt.nz/system/files/documents/publications/drinking-water-annual-report-appendix-1-revised-aug2019.pdf |archive-date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Supplier !! Region/ Town !! Health Act !! Standards\n|-\n| Greater Wellington Water || Wellington urban area \u2013 bulk supply || Complied || Met\n|-\n| Hutt City Council || Lower Hutt || Complied || Met\n|-\n| Kapiti Coast District Council || Otaki ||  Complied || Failed\n|-\n| Kapiti Coast District Council || Paekakariki || Complied || Failed\n|-\n| Kapiti Coast District Council || Waikanae, Paraparaumu, Raumati || Complied || Met\n|-\n| Porirua City Council || Porirua || Complied || Met\n|-\n| Upper Hutt City Council || Upper Hutt || Complied || Met\n|-\n| Wellington City Council || Wellington City || Complied || Met\n|-\n| Carterton District Council || Carterton || Failed || Failed\n|-\n| Masterton District Council || Masterton || Complied || Met\n|-\n| Opaki Water Supply Association || Opaki || Complied || Failed\n|-\n| South Wairarapa District Council || Featherston || Failed || Failed\n|-\n| South Wairarapa District Council || Greytown || Failed || Failed\n|-\n| South Wairarapa District Council || Martinborough || Failed || Failed\n|}\n\n====Waiwhetu aquifer====\nUp until late 2016, bores in the Waterloo well field were considered to be secure. However, a rising trend in bacterial count and E.coli detections triggered a review.  At that stage, about half the customers supplied from the Waterloo treatment station received unchlorinated water.\n\nDuring 2016 and 2017, water supply businesses throughout New Zealand became aware of the severe public health consequences of the [[Water supply and sanitation in New Zealand#Havelock North drinking water contamination|Havelock North drinking water contamination]] incident and the subsequent Government inquiry that recommended all drinking water supplies should be chlorinated.\n\nIn 2017, a decision was made by Greater Wellington Regional Council to chlorinate all the water drawn from the Waiwhetu aquifer.\n<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/91824154/hutt-authorities-to-continue-chlorinating-drinking-water-as-investigations-into-e-coli-continue | title= Hutt authorities to continue chlorinating drinking water as investigations into E coli continue | publisher= Stuff | date=22 April 2017 |accessdate=9 April 2020|archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200411025442/https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/91824154/hutt-authorities-to-continue-chlorinating-drinking-water-as-investigations-into-e-coli-continue |archive-date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Martinborough====\nThere were two periods during early 2019 when a \"boil water\" notice was issued to the residents of Martinborough. \n<ref>{{cite news |last= Fuller |first= Piers |title= Martinborough residents celebrate having drinkable water again after boil water notice lifted |url= https://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/news/wairarapa/112795055/martinborough-residents-celebrate-having-drinkable-water-again-after-boil-water-notice-lifted |work= Stuff |location= |date= 17 May 2019|access-date= 11 April 2020 |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200411032026/https://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/news/wairarapa/112795055/martinborough-residents-celebrate-having-drinkable-water-again-after-boil-water-notice-lifted|archive-date=11 April 2020 }}</ref>\nIn November 2019, Wellington Water said that Martinborough residents needed to restrict demand to avoid restrictions and also to prevent the water from becoming discoloured if it became necessary to draw water from bores that have a higher naturally occurring manganese content.\n<ref>{{cite news |last= Te |first= Mandy |title= Martinborough residents told to save water following a spike in demand |url= https://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/news/wairarapa/117764878/martinborough-residents-told-to-save-water-following-a-spike-in-demand |work= Stuff |location= |date= 27 November 2019|access-date= 11 April 2020 |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200411033051/https://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/news/wairarapa/117764878/martinborough-residents-told-to-save-water-following-a-spike-in-demand|archive-date=11 April 2020 }}</ref>\nIn December 2019, the South Wairarapa District Council announced that a manganese extraction plant would be installed that would help keep water clear, and boost supply by enabling use of all four bores adjacent to the Ruamahanga River.\n<ref>{{cite news |last= Anselm |first= Marcus|date= 12 December 2019|title= More water troubles in Martinborough|url= https://times-age.co.nz/more-water-troubles-in-martinborough/ |work= Wairarapa Times-Age|location= |access-date= 12 April 2020|archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200412010456/https://times-age.co.nz/more-water-troubles-in-martinborough/|archive-date=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Resilience===\n====Wellington urban area====\nThe supply of water to the Wellington region is potentially vulnerable to significant disruption in the event of failures caused by a major earthquake.\nIn 2013, [[GNS Science]] published a study examining a wide range of issues about the impacts of a large earthquake on Wellington's water supply.  Some of the key findings and implications for Civil Defence and Emergency Management from this report include:\n<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.gns.cri.nz/static/pubs/2013/SR%202013-015.pdf\n|title= Water needs and the availability of water in post-earthquake Wellington City, and the significance of social factors in determining community resilience |author= Beban, J.G.; Doody, B,J.; Wright, K.C.; Cousins, W.J,;Becker,J.S. |date= December 2013\n|website= |publisher= GNS Science|access-date= |quote= |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200412001634/https://www.gns.cri.nz/static/pubs/2013/SR%202013-015.pdf|archive-date=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n* The amount of water people have stored in their homes\n* The importance of reservoirs in the provision of water post-earthquake\n* People's willingness to collect and carry water from reservoirs to their homes\n* The importance of developing alternative sources of water to cater for post-earthquake demand\n* The prioritization of water supplies\n\nIn 2016, the Wellington Lifelines Group began work on a Regional Resilience Project, with the aim of ensuring that core infrastructure is as resilient as possible and can enable rapid economic recovery following a major earthquake.\n\nIn October 2019, the Wellington Lifelines Group published their report \"Protecting Wellington's Economy Through Accelerated Infrastructure Investment Programme Business Case\".\nThe appendices to this report include studies of possible impacts of a major earthquake.  The base case studies show that in a major earthquake, the Wellington region would be likely to lose its water supplies for a period of between 3 and 6 months, with treated water potentially not available for up to 12 months.  A wide range of risk mitigation projects were identified and included in modelling to show the potential improvements in resilience.  The risk mitigation projects included works to reduce the risk posed to the bulk water supply that runs parallel to the line of the main Wellington fault.  The modelling of outages indicates that the outage time would reduce to between one and three months, if all the identified risk mitigations were implemented.\n<ref>{{cite web| url=https://wremo.nz/assets/Uploads/Wellington-Lifelines-PBC-MAIN-Combined-20191009.pdf| title= Wellington Lifelines Project \u2013 Regional Resilience Report | publisher= Wellington Region Emergency Management Office| date= Oct 2019| accessdate=11 April 2020 |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200411040711/https://wremo.nz/assets/Uploads/Wellington-Lifelines-PBC-MAIN-Combined-20191009.pdf |archive-date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe report called on its 16 member organisations to help deliver 25 key infrastructure projects across the region over the next two decades, at a cost of $5.3b. It was forecast that implementing these projects would save the country more than $6.1b in lost economic activity in the five years following a major earthquake\nThe list of 25 proposed projects covers a range of lifeline utilities.  The proposed water supply resilience projects are shown below.\n<ref>{{cite news |last=George|first=Damian |url= https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/nz-earthquake/117783826/wellington-lifelines-group-calls-for-20year-investment-programme-to-guard-against-major-earthquake |title= Wellington Lifelines Group calls for 20-year investment programme to guard against major earthquake|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= 3 December 2019|website= |publisher= Stuff |access-date= 12 April 2020|quote=}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Project !! Description !! Est cost !! Timeframe\n|-\n| Cross-harbour pipeline || Build 12.7&nbsp;km underwater pipeline from Seaview to Evans Bay, with connection to Carmichael Reservoir || $139m || 2020\u20132023\n|-\n| Prince of Wales and Bell Rd reservoir upgrade || Build 35 megalitre reservoir at Prince of Wales Park and 10 megalitre reservoir at Bell Rd || $78m || 2019\u20132025\n|-\n| Silverstream Bridge pipeline replacement || Replace Te Marua-to-Ngauranga pipeline where it crosses Silverstream Bridge and Wellington Fault || $23m || 2019\u20132021\n|-\n| General toughening of pipes || Upgrade 152&nbsp;km network of critical ductile pipes || $654m || 2019\u20132025\n|-\n| Carmichael to Johnsonville and Karori pipeline || New water main between Carmichael Reservoir and pump station near Omaroro Reservoir; pump station between cross-harbour pipeline and Johnsonville; water main between Omaroro Reservoir and Churchill Drive; upgrade to batter slopes along Grant Rd, Lennel Rd, and Wadestown Rd || $247m || 2026\u20132031\n|-\n| Porirua low-level zone reservoirs || Build additional nine-megalitre reservoir, and three-megalitre storage area at Takapuwahia || $25m || 2026\u20132028\n|-\n| Waterloo Water Treatment Plant upgrade || Reduce liquefaction risk and improve ground at southern end, or provide extra structural support || $2m || 2029\u20132032\n|-\n| General toughening of pipes ||As above ||n/a || 2026\u20132032\n|}\n\n==== Om\u0101roro/Prince of Wales reservoir====\nIn 2017, Wellington Water applied for the designation of an easement required for the construction of a 35 million litre reservoir on land within the Wellington Town Belt, at Prince of Wales Park in the Wellington suburb of [[Mount Cook, Wellington|Mt Cook]].\n\nThe application for the easement referenced a 2009 study conducted by GNS of possible earthquake damage to the water network.  This study estimated that for a magnitude 7.5 Richter scale earthquake, there would be about 30 breaks on the main trunk pipelines and 60 breaks on the smaller branch lines. There could be as many as 8,000 breaks in the Wellington City local supply network. Bulk water supply and treatment facilities are also expected to suffer damage requiring repair. Wellington Water and Greater Wellington Regional Council estimated that it would take around 60\u201070 days to restore bulk water supply to parts of the Wellington metropolitan area.It could take several years to fully repair damage to the local water distribution network resulting from a severe earthquake, as much of the network may have to be rebuilt.\n<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.wellingtonwater.co.nz/dmsdocument/215\n|title= Prince of Wales \u2013 Omaroro Reservoir \u2013 Town Belt Easement Request \u2013 Includes Appendix A|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= 1 June 2017|website= |publisher= Wellington Water |access-date= 12 April 2020|quote= |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200412204753/https://www.wellingtonwater.co.nz/dmsdocument/215|archive-date=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2018, an independent panel recommended that Wellington City Council confirm the designation of the easement for the reservoir.\n<ref>{{cite web |url= https://wellington.govt.nz/your-council/news/2018/05/prince-of-wales-park-reservoir\n|title= Green light for Om\u0101roro/Prince of Wales Park reservoir|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= 14 May 2018|website= |publisher= Wellington City Council |access-date= 12 April 2020|quote= |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200412212844/https://wellington.govt.nz/your-council/news/2018/05/prince-of-wales-park-reservoir|archive-date=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe reservoir provides a significant increase in water storage for the city, and forms part of the city's resilience strategy to help ensure that fresh water is available to residents after a natural disaster or major network failure.\n\nPreparatory earthworks for the project commenced in February 2019.\n<ref>{{cite news |last= Hunt|first=Tom |date= 5 February 2019|title=  Reservoir earthworks marks beginning of Wellington's Mt Cook becoming a 'building-site suburb'|url= https://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/news/110374164/reservoir-earthworks-marks-beginning-of-wellingtons-mt-cook-becoming-a-buildingsite-suburb|work= Stuff|location= |access-date=12 April 2020 |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200412010647/https://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/news/110374164/reservoir-earthworks-marks-beginning-of-wellingtons-mt-cook-becoming-a-buildingsite-suburb|archive-date=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Stormwater==\n\n===Pipeline age and condition===\nThe 2018/19 National Performance Review published by Water New Zealand compares the average stormwater pipeline age and condition across networks. The data for the Wellington Water network shows that 16% of the pipelines are in poor or very poor condition.  The Wellington stormwater network ranks the worst on this measure out of the six large networks nationwide.\n<ref name=\"Pipeline_condition\" />\nThe review also includes average pipeline age. The Wellington stormwater network has an average age of 49 years, and ranks as the second oldest of the six large networks.\n<ref name=\"Pipeline_age\" />\n\n==Wastewater==\nProperties in urban areas in the Wellington Region are generally all connected to a wastewater system via a [[gravity sewer]].  In some cases, pumps are used to pump wastewater to a treatment plant, or to lift wastewater from lower level drains into a higher elevation gravity sewer so that it can flow to a treatment plant. \n===Wellington urban area===\nWellington's population grew rapidly in the late 19th century after it became the capital city in 1865.\nThere were increasing cases of typhoid and cholera which were attributed to poor sanitation. In 1879 there were 75 deaths in Wellington from typhoid, diphtheria, scarlet fever, measles and cholera \u2013 mostly in the central Te Aro area. \n<ref>{{cite web| last= Roberts| first=Sofia|url=https://www.museumswellington.org.nz/wellingtons-unsightly-and-smelly-past/| title= Wellington\u2019s unsightly and smelly past | publisher= Museums Wellington| accessdate=14 April 2020 |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200414015917/https://www.museumswellington.org.nz/wellingtons-unsightly-and-smelly-past/| archive-date=14 April 2020 }}</ref>\nAfter some political deliberation, construction of a city wastewater network began in 1893. It cost \u00a3175,000 and was completed by 1899.\n\n====The interceptor====\nAs part of the early development of the wastewater network, a large pipe was constructed to take wastewater from Manners St through Mt Victoria and out to an ocean outfall at Moa Point on the south coast.  This main trunk wastewater line was known as \"the interceptor\". In the 1930s the interceptor was extended from Manners St through to Pipitea St, as the city's population topped 100,000.\nAs suburbs spread further north to [[Johnsonville, New Zealand|Johnsonville]], another extension of the interceptor was made from [[Ngauranga Gorge]] and through [[Ngaio, New Zealand|Ngaio]] Gorge to connect at [[Thorndon, New Zealand|Thorndon]].\n<ref name=\u201dinterceptor\u201d>{{cite news| last= Campbell| first=Georgina |url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=12313567| title= Severe corrosion discovered in critical Wellington wastewater pipe| publisher= NZ Herald| date=4 March 2020|accessdate=14 April 2020 | archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200414012313/https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=12313567| archive-date=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Wastewater treatment====\nThere are four [[Sewage treatment|wastewater treatment]] plants serving the Wellington urban area.\nTogether, they treat about 150 million litres of wastewater on a typical day, using biological and ultraviolet treatment processes. The treated water is discharged to the sea. The sludge resulting from filtration and treatment is de-watered (with this water further treated) and the solid content is sent to landfills.\n<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.learnz.org.nz/water172/bg-standard-f/wastewater/| title= Wastewater | publisher= LEARNZ| accessdate=14 April 2020 | archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200414020034/http://www.learnz.org.nz/water172/bg-standard-f/wastewater/|archive-date=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.wellingtonwater.co.nz/your-water/wastewater/where-does-wastewater-go/| title= Where does wastewater go| publisher= Wellington Water| accessdate=14 April 2020 |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200414020137/https://www.wellingtonwater.co.nz/your-water/wastewater/where-does-wastewater-go/|archive-date=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Moa Point====\nThe Moa Point treatment plant handles all the wastewater from most of Wellington city, other than Karori and some northern suburbs.  Treated wastewater is discharged via a 1.8&nbsp;km ocean outfall into Cook Strait.  Sludge is separated from the wastewater at the plant, and pumped to a landfill site at Carey's Gully, where it is dewatered and placed into a landfill.\n\n====Seaview====\nThe Seaview plant handles wastewater from Upper Hutt and Lower Hutt.  There is an ocean outfall at [[Pencarrow Head]].\n\n====Porirua====\nA treatment plant located at Rukutane Point handles wastewater from the northern suburbs of Wellington and Porirua city.  There is an ocean outfall from the plant.\n<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.wellingtonwater.co.nz/pwp/the-wastewater-system/| title= Your wastewater system | publisher= Wellington Water| accessdate=14 April 2020 |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200414020513/https://www.wellingtonwater.co.nz/pwp/the-wastewater-system/| archive-date=14 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n====Karori====\nA separate wastewater and treatment system serves the Karori area.  Treated wastewater is piped out to the South Coast.\n\n===Network condition and performance===\n====Pipeline age and condition====\nThe 2018/19 National Performance Review published by Water New Zealand compares the average wastewater pipeline age and condition across networks. The data for the Wellington Water network shows that 33% of the pipelines are in poor or very poor condition. The Wellington wastewater network ranks the worst on this measure out of the six large networks nationwide. (The next worst is Christchurch, with only 12% in poor or very poor condition).\n<ref name=\"Pipeline_condition\" />\nThe review also includes average pipeline age. The Wellington wastewater network has an average age of 53 years, and ranks as the second oldest of the six large networks.\n<ref name=\"Pipeline_age\" />\n\nIn March 2020, Wellington Water reported the discovery of severe corrosion in the large main trunk sewer (the interceptor) over a length of 250&nbsp;m in a section close to the treatment plant near Moa Point.<ref name=\u201dinterceptor\u201d></ref>\n\n====Porirua network issues====\nAs part of a submission to a Porirua City Council committee in 2018 in relation to renewing resource consents, Wellington Water provided a background document about the issues in the Porirua wastewater system.  The issues reported included:<ref>{{cite web |url= https://poriruacity.govt.nz/documents/1296/1619_-_19_-_WWTP_-_OR_Porirua_Wastewater_Consenting.pdf|title= Porirua Wastewater Consenting |last= |first= |date=14 February 2018 |website= |publisher= Porirua City Council |access-date= 14 April 2020|archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200416020516/https://poriruacity.govt.nz/documents/1296/1619_-_19_-_WWTP_-_OR_Porirua_Wastewater_Consenting.pdf| archive-date=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n* poor existing freshwater quality in the Porirua catchment\n* frequent overflows from wastewater networks into freshwater and coastal water during periods of wet weather, and overflows from the wastewater treatment plant into coastal water\n* inflow and infiltration from stormwater into the wastewater network\n* ageing network prone to failures and with insufficient capacity to accommodate future growth\n* insufficient capacity of the treatment plant to accommodate future growth\nIn February 2020, the Mayor of Porirua announced the establishment of a roving team to search for issues such as cross connections in stormwater and sewage pipes.  As part of that announcement, it was revealed that more than half of Porirua's wastewater pipes are in a poor condition, and that it will cost close to $2 billion over the next two to three decades to bring them up to scratch.\n<ref>{{ cite news| last= | first= |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/news/national/410679/porirua-s-wastewater-woes-get-250-000-boost| title= Porirua's wastewater woes get $250,000 boost | work= RNZ | date=29 February 2020|accessdate=14 April 2020 | archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200416020341/https://www.rnz.co.nz/news/national/410679/porirua-s-wastewater-woes-get-250-000-boost | archive-date=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Significant incidents===\n====\u014cwhiro Bay sewage pollution====\n\u014cwhiro Bay is located on the Wellington south coast.  The shoreline is within the [[Taputeranga Marine Reserve]]. There have been persistent problems with sewage pollution of the \u014cwhiro Stream and beach for at least ten years, and the beach has been closed for swimming for long periods.\n<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/national/3342307/Owhiro-Bay-beach-closed| title= Owhiro Bay beach closed| work= Stuff| date=17 February 2010|accessdate=16 Apr 2020 | archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200416022541/http://www.stuff.co.nz/national/3342307/Owhiro-Bay-beach-closed | archive-date=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite news| last=Stewart|first=Matt|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/news/eastern-suburbs/6574251/Pollution-warning-for-Owhiro-Bay| title= Pollution warning for Owhiro Bay| work= Stuff| date=14 March 2012|accessdate=16 Apr 2020 | archive-url= http://web.archive.org/web/20200416024211/http://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/news/eastern-suburbs/6574251/Pollution-warning-for-Owhiro-Bay | archive-date=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite news| last= Hunt|first=Tom|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/news/118890119/sewage-in-wellington-marine-reserve-43times-worse-than-acceptable-levels| title= Sewage in Wellington marine reserve 43-times worse than acceptable levels| work= Stuff| date=19 January 2020|accessdate=16 Apr 2020 | archive-url= http://web.archive.org/web/20200416023740/https://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/news/118890119/sewage-in-wellington-marine-reserve-43times-worse-than-acceptable-levels|archive-date= 16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, Wellington Water announced that it had found and resolved incorrect connections of wastewater into stormwater systems at five locations in a suburb in the stormwater catchment area of the \u014cwhiro Stream.  Wellington Water said that the mistake occurred when the subdivision was built about eight years ago, and there were likely to be more cross-connections that it had yet to identify.\n<ref>{{cite news| last= George|first=Damian| url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/120187481/wastewater-spilling-into-wellington-stream-since-pipes-incorrectly-laid-in-subdivision-eight-years-ago| title= Wastewater spilling into Wellington stream since pipes incorrectly laid in subdivision eight years ago| work= Stuff| date=11 March 2020|accessdate=16 Apr 2020 | archive-url= http://web.archive.org/web/20200416022804/https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/120187481/wastewater-spilling-into-wellington-stream-since-pipes-incorrectly-laid-in-subdivision-eight-years-ago| archive-date=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n====Illegal discharge from Porirua treatment plant====\nIn October 2018, a series of errors and omissions in the management of the Porirua wastewater treatment plant led to a spill of approximately 5000 cubic metres of wastewater and solids from the outfall into a small bay adjacent to Titahi Bay beach.  In a subsequent hearing in the Environment Court in September 2019, Wellington Water was fined $65,000 for the illegal discharge.\n<ref>{{cite news| last= Boyack | first= Nicholas |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/environment/115781832/wellington-water-fined--67500-for-illegal-discharge-into-sea-near-titahi-bay| title= Wellington Water fined $67,500 for illegal discharge into sea near Titahi Bay| work= Stuff| date=13 September 2019 |accessdate=15 April 2020 | archive-url= http://web.archive.org/web/20200415013049/https://www.stuff.co.nz/environment/115781832/wellington-water-fined--67500-for-illegal-discharge-into-sea-near-titahi-bay | archive-date=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n====Pipeline collapse in Dixon St====\nOn 20 December 2019, a wastewater pipe built in the 1930\u2019s collapsed beneath the intersection of Willis and Dixon Streets in the central business district, leading to the diversion of untreated wastewater into [[Wellington harbour]] at an initial rate of up to 100 litres a second.\nThe broken pipe serves much of the central city, taking wastewater to the interceptor (or main trunk sewer), that leads to the Moa Point wastewater treatment plant.  The public were warned not to swim in the inner harbour, but local iwi placed a [[r\u0101hui]] on the entire Wellington harbour.\n<ref name=\u201ddixon\u201d>{{cite news| author=RNZ |url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=12295880| title= Sewage going into Wellington harbour after pipe collapse|work= NZ Herald| date=20 December 2019|accessdate=14 April 2020 |archive-url= http://web.archive.org/web/20200416023233/https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=12295880| archive-date=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAn emergency above-ground pipe was placed along Upper Willis street \u2013 closing it to all traffic  \u2013 to bypass the failed underground pipe while permanent repairs were made. The swimming restriction on the whole of Wellington Harbour was lifted on 26 December. However, the area of the inner harbour from the [[Whairepo Lagoon]] entrance past the dive platform to the Clyde Quay wharf remained off-limits because of a \u201cseparate network issue\u201d.  \n<ref> {{cite news| |url= http://wellington.scoop.co.nz/?p=124862/| title= Harbour swimming ban lifted \u2013 but not everywhere|work= Scoop| date=27 December 2019|accessdate=14 April 2020 | archive-url= http://web.archive.org/web/20200416023400/http://wellington.scoop.co.nz/?p=124862%2F| archive-date=16 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\nWillis Street was eventually re-opened at the end of March 2020, after the permanent replacement had been installed beneath the road, and the temporary above-ground pipe removed.\n<ref> {{cite news| |url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=12295880| title= Willis Street in Wellington to reopen after pipe replaced |work= Stuff| date=27 March 2020|accessdate=14 April 2020 | archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200416023251/https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=12295880 | archive-date= 16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Failure of sludge pipeline beneath Mt Albert====\nIn January 2020, there was a failure of pipelines carrying sludge pumped at high pressure from the Moa Point treatment plant to the landfill at Carey\u2019s Gully.  The pipelines are 9&nbsp;km long and are about 25 years old.  There are two in parallel allowing one to operate while maintenance can occur on the other pipe.  In this incident both pipes failed at the same time.  \n\nTo avoid discharging the sludge into the ocean, a fleet of sewage trucks was mobilized to carry about one million litres of sludge a day to the dewatering plant at Carey\u2019s Gully. Up to 150 round trips each day were required, with trucks sometimes operating around the clock to keep up with the volume. \n\nThe break in the pipelines was located 200&nbsp;m inside a sewage tunnel beneath Mt Albert, making repairs a significant challenge. The repair solution required the manufacture in Germany of a custom-made polyester woven liner.  This liner was winched from one end of each pipe to the other, and then expanded to essentially act as a new pipeline within the old one.  Specialists from the manufacturer flew to New Zealand to assist in the installation, but were required to spend 14 days in isolation because of the border restrictions imposed in response to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in New Zealand|COVID-19 pandemic]].\n<ref>{{cite news| last= Thomas | first= Rachel |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/news/national/408078/broken-mt-albert-sewer-tunnel-pipe-costly-effort-to-divert-millions-of-litres-of-sludge| title= Broken Mt Albert sewer tunnel pipe: Costly effort to divert millions of litres of sludge| work= RNZ| date=24 January 2020 |accessdate=15 April 2020 | archive-url= http://web.archive.org/web/20200415014537/https://www.rnz.co.nz/news/national/408078/broken-mt-albert-sewer-tunnel-pipe-costly-effort-to-divert-millions-of-litres-of-sludge | archive-date=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite news |last=Campbell|first=Georgina|url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=12318739| title= Coronavirus: Major Wellington wastewater pipe repairs delayed| work= NZ Herald| date=21 March 2020 |accessdate=15 April 2020 | archive-url= http://web.archive.org/web/20200415035134/https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=12318739 | archive-date=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite news|url=http://wellington.scoop.co.nz/?p=127088 | title= Six German experts will fix broken sludge pipeline next month | work= Scoop| date=5 April 2020|accessdate=15 April 2020 | archive-url= http://web.archive.org/web/20200415021810/http://wellington.scoop.co.nz/?p=127088| archive-date=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n====South Wairarapa====\nAlmost half a million litres of partially and fully treated wastewater was discharged into the [[Ruamahanga River]] near Martinborough in two incidents in January 2020, as a result of issues at a treatment plant. Under suitable conditions, discharging fully treated wastewater to the river is a consented activity.  However, when the river level is low, as in this case, this type of discharge is a breach of the resource consent.\n<ref>{{cite news |last= Anselm|first= Marcus|date= 18 January 2020|title= Water problems continue in south|url= https://times-age.co.nz/water-problems-continue-in-south/|work= Wairarapa Times-Age|location= |access-date= 12 April 2020|archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200411214833/https://times-age.co.nz/water-problems-continue-in-south/|archive-date=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite news |last= Campbell|first= Georgina|date= 31 January 2020|title= Second wastewater discharge into Wairarapa river this year raises concerns|url= https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=12305059 |work= NZ Herald|location= |access-date= 12 April 2020|archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200411214943/https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=12305059|archive-date=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Water in New Zealand]]\n* [[Water supply and sanitation in New Zealand]]\n* [[Water purification]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.wellingtonwater.co.nz// Wellington Water]\n* [https://www.dia.govt.nz/Three-waters-review Three Waters Review] at the Department of Internal Affairs\n* [https://www.waternz.org.nz/  Water New Zealand (New Zealand Water and Wastes Association)]\n* [https://www.gw.govt.nz/history-of-our-water-supply History of our water supply] at the Greater Wellington Regional Council\n* [http://www.gw.govt.nz/assets/council-publications/Regional%20Parks_20011127_163445.pdf Wonderful Water Walks \u2013 A History of Water Supply Dams in the Wellington Region] at the Greater Wellington Regional Council\n\n[[Category:Water supply and sanitation in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Wellington Region]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n'''Water supply and sanitation in the Wellington region''' involves the provision of the \"three waters\" \u2013 [[drinking water]], [[stormwater]], and [[wastewater]] services in the Greater Wellington region.\n\nThe provision of these services in the [[Wellington]] urban area is the responsibility of five councils: [[Wellington City Council|Wellington City]], [[Lower Hutt|Hutt]], [[Upper Hutt]] and [[Porirua]] city councils, and the [[Wellington Region|Greater Wellington]] Regional Council.  However, the water assets of these councils are managed by an [[infrastructure asset management]] company, [[Wellington Water]]. From 1 October 2019, Wellington Water also became the asset manager of the water assets of the [[South Wairarapa District]] Council.  \n<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= South Wairarapa District Council joins Wellington Water|url= https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/AK1909/S00704/south-wairarapa-district-council-joins-wellington-water.htm|work= Scoop|location= |date= 26 September 2019|access-date= 12 April 2020|archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200411215909/https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/AK1909/S00704/south-wairarapa-district-council-joins-wellington-water.htm|archive-date=12 April 2020}}</ref>\nWellington Water is jointly owned by all six councils.\n<ref>{{cite web| url=https://app.companiesoffice.govt.nz/companies/app/ui/pages/companies/1337122/shareholdings| title= Wellington Water Limited (1337122)| publisher= New Zealand Companies Office| accessdate=2 April 2020|archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200409030103/https://app.companiesoffice.govt.nz/companies/app/ui/pages/companies/1337122/shareholdings|archive-date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\nThe assets in the region covered by these six councils includes 6,300&nbsp;km of pipes, 138 reservoirs, 249 pump stations and four drinking water treatment plants.\n<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.wellingtonwater.co.nz/your-water/overview/| title= Overview -Your water| publisher= Wellington Water| accessdate=8 April 2020|archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200409025904/https://www.wellingtonwater.co.nz/your-water/overview/|archive-date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThree waters services for the remaining parts of the Greater Wellington region are provided by the [[Kapiti Coast District]] Council, the [[Carterton, New Zealand|Carterton]] District Council and [[Masterton]] District Council.\n\nThe challenges for managing the three waters in the Wellington region include the deteriorated condition of pipelines in the Wellington urban area.  The pipelines are in significantly worse condition than those in other large networks nationwide, and there has been a recent history of serious failures.  The water supply to the region is also at significant risk during a severe earthquake, although some projects are underway to improve resilience.\n\nWater supplies to the Wellington urban area meet the requirements of the Health Act and conform with drinking water standards.  However, for some of the towns in the Kapiti Coast and Wairarapa regions, there have been occasional non-conformances with the required standards for drinking water quality and safety.\n\nBenchmarking data published by Water New Zealand as part of their 2018/19 National Performance Review showed that capital expenditure on three waters assets in the Wellington urban area is well below the average of the expenditure on networks in most other major centres, and for the wastewater network, expenditure was the lowest out of the seven large networks in the review.\n<ref name=\"Capex\">{{cite web| url=https://www.waternz.org.nz/Category?Action=View&Category_id=1018| title= Annual capital expenditure per property connected to the network| publisher= Water New Zealand| accessdate=13 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n==Drinking water==\n===Regional water supply networks===\nThe supply of reticulated drinking water is regulated under the Health Act, and suppliers are registered and subject to a testing regime.  The registered water suppliers for the Greater Wellington region are listed in annual drinking water quality reports published by the Ministry of Health. \n<ref name=\"MoH_quality_report\">{{cite web| url=https://www.health.govt.nz/system/files/documents/publications/drinking-water-annual-report-appendix-1-revised-aug2019.pdf| title= Annual Report on Drinking-water Quality 2017\u201318 \u2013 Appendix 1: Water supply compliance| publisher= Ministry of Health| date= June 2019| accessdate=10 April 2020 |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200409204622/https://www.health.govt.nz/system/files/documents/publications/drinking-water-annual-report-appendix-1-revised-aug2019.pdf |archive-date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Supplier !! Region/ Town !! Population\n|-\n| Greater Wellington Water || Wellington urban area \u2013 bulk supply || 350,000\n|-\n| Hutt City Council || Lower Hutt || 95,469\n|-\n| Kapiti Coast District Council || Otaki || 5,700\n|-\n| Kapiti Coast District Council || Paekakariki || 1,665\n|-\n| Kapiti Coast District Council || Waikanae, Paraparaumu, Raumati || 35,800\n|-\n| Porirua City Council || Porirua || 46,444\n|-\n| Upper Hutt City Council || Upper Hutt || 34,650\n|-\n| Wellington City Council || Wellington City || 165,126\n|-\n| Carterton District Council || Carterton || 4,200\n|-\n| Masterton District Council || Masterton || 19,000\n|-\n| Opaki Water Supply Association || Opaki || 1,500\n|-\n| South Wairarapa District Council || Featherston || 2,580\n|-\n| South Wairarapa District Council || Greytown || 1,952\n|-\n| South Wairarapa District Council || Martinborough || 1,505\n|}\nThis table omits several small supplies serving populations less than 1,000.\n\n===Water sources for Wellington urban area===\nWater supply for the Wellington urban area comes from three sources:\n<ref name=\"Sources\">{{cite web| url=https://www.wellingtonwater.co.nz/your-water/drinking-water/where-does-it-come-from/| title= Where does it come from?| publisher= Wellington Water| accessdate=7 April 2020 |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200409031320/https://www.wellingtonwater.co.nz/your-water/drinking-water/where-does-it-come-from/ |archive-date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n* Hutt River\n* Wainuiomata and Orongorongo rivers\n* Waiwhetu aquifer\n\nThere are times each year, particularly during summer months, where the total demand is greater than can be supplied from these sources.  There are two large storage lakes that can be used to supplement the supply during these periods.\n\n====Hutt River catchment====\nThe [[Hutt River (New Zealand)|Hutt river]] water supply catchment covers almost 9,000 hectares of bush-clad mountains and valleys at the southern edge of the [[Tararua Forest Park]] and adjoining the [[Kaitoke Regional Park]]. Rainwater from tributary streams flows into the Hutt River and is intercepted at a [[weir]] at [[Kaitoke]], north of [[Upper Hutt]].  The water is then strained to remove sticks, leaves and silt, and piped through tunnels to the [[Te Marua]] Water Treatment Plant. Up to 150 million litres of water per day may be diverted from the Hutt River, provided an adequate flow is maintained downstream of the weir. The Hutt water supply catchment provides about 40 percent of the water used in the Wellington urban area each year.<ref name=\"Sources\" />\n\n====Macaskill storage lakes====\nThere are two large storage lakes at Te Marua \u2013 the Macaskill Lakes. These lakes are filled from the Hutt River intake when the water is clean and there is sufficient flow available. Stored water is pumped from the lakes into the treatment plant when there is not enough water in the river to meet public demand.  The storage lakes are also used to meet demand when the river is too dirty \u2013 after heavy rainfall \u2013 or when it is in flood and the intake is closed to prevent rocks and gravel from entering the intake pipes.\n\nThe Macaskill Lakes are 17.3 metres deep and have a combined usable capacity of approximately 3,350 million litres, or enough to meet average water use for around 23 days.<ref name=\"Sources\" />\n\nBuilding the lakes was first proposed in 1975. The construction of the two lakes proved difficult because of weather and on-site conditions, resulting in cost increases and litigation.  There were also problems with leaks after completion, leading to further litigation.\n<ref>{{cite news |last= O'Neill |first= Andrea |title= Upper Hutt lakes leak water and money |url= https://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/news/69822534/upper-hutt-lakes-leak-water-and-money---150-years-of-news |work= Stuff |location= |date= 30 June 2015|access-date= 7 April 2020 | archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200412011422/https://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/news/69822534/upper-hutt-lakes-leak-water-and-money---150-years-of-news |archive-date=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Wainuiomata/Orongorongo rivers====\nThe Wainuiomata/Orongorongo water supply catchment area lies within the [[Remutaka Range]]s to the east of [[Wainuiomata]]. The collection area covers 7,600 hectares. Five low dams (weirs) with intake pipes provide water from the rivers to the Wainuiomata Water Treatment Plant. These catchment areas provide approximately 20% of the water used in the Wellington urban area each year.<ref name=\"Sources\"/>\n\n====Waiwhetu aquifer====\nThe Waiwhetu [[artesian aquifer]] is a zone of water-retaining sand, gravel and boulders beneath the Hutt Valley. Water from the Hutt River starts to flow underground around Taita Gorge. From Melling southwards, the water becomes naturally pressurised beneath a layer of hard clay. This pressurised zone, the Waiwhetu artesian aquifer, stretches as far south as the harbour. It is estimated to be up to 70 metres thick at its western edge against the Wellington fault line, and 20 metres thick at the eastern edge of the harbour. The pressure in the aquifer has resulted in several fresh water springs in the harbour floor.\n\nWater takes more than 12 months to pass through the aquifer to wells where it is extracted for distribution via the water network. Extraction is monitored and controlled to minimise the risk of [[saline intrusion]]. The Waiwhetu aquifer provides around 40 percent of the annual water supply.<ref name=\"Sources\" />\n\nThe Te Puna Wai Ora (Spring of Life) in Buick Street, [[Petone]] provides untreated water from the aquifer free to the public. \n<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.jacksonstreet.co.nz/listing/te-puna-wai-ora-spring-of-life/\n| title= Te Puna Wai Ora (Spring of Life)| publisher= Jackson Street Program| archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200409022604/https://www.jacksonstreet.co.nz/listing/te-puna-wai-ora-spring-of-life/|archive-date=9 April 2020| accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.huttvalleynz.com/upload/documents/petone_water.pdf| title= Hutt City \u2013 Petone's Artesian Water |publisher= Hutt City Council |date=13 May 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100513230407/http://www.huttvalleynz.com/upload/documents/Petone_water.pdf|archive-date= 5 April 2012 }}</ref>\n\n===Water sources for remaining areas===\n\nThe water sources for the South Wairarapa District Council area are the [[Waiohine River|Waiohine]] catchment for Featherston, the Kuratawhiti Street bore for Greytown residents, and the Herricks bore field for users in Martinborough. \n<ref name=\"SWDC\">{{cite web| url=https://www.swdc.govt.nz/water-and-sewerage#water| title= Water and sewerage| publisher= South Wairarapa District Council | accessdate=7 April 2020 |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200409085630/https://www.swdc.govt.nz/water-and-sewerage |archive-date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nWater supplies for the Kapiti Coast region are sourced from combination of bores and surface water from the [[Waikanae]] River.\n<ref name=\"Kapiti_water\">{{cite web| url=https://www.kapiticoast.govt.nz/services/a-z-council-services-and-facilities/water/| title= Water supply| publisher= Kapiti Coast District Council | accessdate=10 April 2020 |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200410091317/https://www.kapiticoast.govt.nz/services/a-z-council-services-and-facilities/water/ |archive-date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nWater supply for the Carterton district comes from the Kaipatangata Stream and two underground bores.\n<ref name=\"Carterton_water\">{{cite web| url=https://cdc.govt.nz/services/water | title= Water supply| publisher= Carterton District Council | accessdate=10 April 2020 |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200410091614/https://cdc.govt.nz/services/water/ |archive-date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nMasterton's drinking water is sourced Waingawa River, about 10&nbsp;km west of Masterton.\n<ref name=\"Masterton_water\">{{cite web| url=https://mstn.govt.nz/services/water-services/| title= Services \u2013 Water| publisher= Masterton District Council | accessdate=10 April 2020 |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200410091846/https://mstn.govt.nz/services/water-services/%7C |archive-date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Water treatment===\n====Wellington urban area====\nThere are four [[Water purification|water treatment]] plants located in the Hutt Valley (Te Marua, Waterloo, Gear Island and Wainuiomata). These plants supply water for use in Upper Hutt, Lower Hutt, Porirua and Wellington cities.\n<ref>{{cite web| url=https://wellington.govt.nz/services/environment-and-waste/water/wellingtons-water-supply/water-treatment | title= Water treatment| publisher= Wellington City Council| accessdate=9 April 2020|archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200409075257/https://wellington.govt.nz/services/environment-and-waste/water/wellingtons-water-supply/water-treatment |archive-date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\nThe treatment processes at the four treatment plants differ based on the characteristics of the incoming water.\n\nAt the Te Marua water treatment plant, the main treatment processes are:\n<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.wellingtonwater.co.nz/dmsdocument/385 | title= Te Marua Water Treatment Plant Technical Information| date= January 2008| publisher= Greater Wellington Regional Council| via= Wellington Water| accessdate=9 April 2020|archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200409081435/https://www.wellingtonwater.co.nz/dmsdocument/385 |archive-date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n* Straining\n* [[Coagulation (water treatment)|Coagulation]] and [[flocculation]]\n* [[Sedimentation (water treatment)|Sedimentation]]\n* [[Filtration]]\n* [[Water chlorination|Chlorination]]\n* [[Water purification#pH adjustment|pH adjustment]]\n* [[Water fluoridation|Fluoridation]]\n\nThe Gear Island and Waterloo plants both treat water that is drawn from the Waiwhetu aquifer.\n\n===Pipeline age and condition===\nThe 2018/19 National Performance Review published by Water New Zealand compares the average pipeline age and condition across water supply networks. The data for the Wellington water supply network shows that 20% of the pipelines are in poor or very poor condition.  The Wellington network ranks the worst  on this measure out of the six large supply networks nationwide.\n<ref name=\"Pipeline_condition\">{{cite web| url=https://www.waternz.org.nz/Category?Action=View&Category_id=1008| title= National performance review \u2013 Pipeline condition| publisher= Water New Zealand| accessdate=9 April 2020 }}</ref>\nThe review also includes average pipeline age. The Wellington network has an average age of 43 years, and ranks as the second oldest of the six large supply networks.\n<ref name=\"Pipeline_age\">{{cite web| url=https://www.waternz.org.nz/Category?Action=View&Category_id=1007| title= National performance review \u2013 Pipeline age| publisher= Water New Zealand| accessdate=9 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n===Consumption, losses and metering===\nDuring a prolonged dry spell in November 2017, Wellington Water reported that weekend consumption in the Wellington urban area reached 171 million litres for the day \u2013 around 30 million litres more than a typical day, and the highest November daily consumption in five years. Wellington Water called on consumers to cut back on their water use, and make sure they observe garden watering restrictions.\n<ref>{{cite news |last= Shelton |first= Lindsay |title= Water use soars; cut back on using water, says Wellington Water |url= http://wellington.scoop.co.nz/?p=105145 |work= Scoop |location= |date= 22 November 2017|access-date= 9 April 2020|archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200409030309/http://wellington.scoop.co.nz/?p=105145|archive-date= 9 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\nA National Performance Review published by Water New Zealand for the 2019 financial year showed that daily residential consumption in the Wellington metropolitan region was about 226 litres per person. By way of comparison, daily residential water use in Auckland and Tauranga was significantly lower at about 156 and 189 litres per person respectively. Both Auckland and Tauranga have water metering in place for all residences, but in Wellington only around 1% of residential supplies are currently metered.\n<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.waternz.org.nz/Category?Action=View&Category_id=1010| title= National performance review \u2013 Residential water efficiency| publisher= Water New Zealand| accessdate=9 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\nThe same National Performance Review also compares water losses between supply networks.  The data for Wellington shows that despite having a higher than average system pressure, the water losses (reported as an infrastructure leakage index), were lower than average, and approaching a threshold where action to reduce losses even further could be uneconomic unless there are shortages.\n<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.waternz.org.nz/Category?Action=View&Category_id=1023| title= National performance review \u2013 Water losses| publisher= Water New Zealand| accessdate=9 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\nIn their submission to a Wellington City Council Water Committee, Wellington Water warned  that \"current water consumption and a growing population will lead to water shortages by 2040\".\n<ref>{{cite news |last= Fonseka |first= Dileepa  |title= Water meters suggested as Wellington faces water shortage |url= https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/110782642/water-meters-suggested-as-wellington-faces-water-shortage |work= Stuff |location= |date= 13 December 2019|access-date= 22 February 2019 |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200409030927/https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/110782642/water-meters-suggested-as-wellington-faces-water-shortage |archive-date=9 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, it was reported that Wellington City Council was considering installing water meters for all domestic consumers.\n<ref>{{cite news |last= McManus |first= Joel |title= Councillors considering water metering to solve Wellington pipe woes |url= https://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/news/wellington/119959891/councillors-considering-water-metering-to-solve-wellington-pipe-woes |work= Stuff |location= |date= 4 March 2020| access-date= 7 April 2020 |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200409031054/https://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/news/wellington/119959891/councillors-considering-water-metering-to-solve-wellington-pipe-woes |archive-date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\nAt the time of that report, only 1,200 residential properties in Wellington were using water meters.\n<ref>{{cite web| url=https://wellington.govt.nz/services/environment-and-waste/water/water-meters| title= Water meters| publisher= Wellington City Council| accessdate=7 April 2020 |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200409031212/https://wellington.govt.nz/services/environment-and-waste/water/water-meters |archive-date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2017, the Kapiti Coast District Council reported that there had been a drop in consumption of more than 26% since water meters were installed in July 2014.\n<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.kcnews.co.nz/story.php?storyID=11044| title= Kapiti Council says no water restrictions here| publisher= KC News| date=7 December 2017| accessdate=11 April 2020 |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200411030730/https://www.kcnews.co.nz/story.php?storyID=11044 |archive-date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Quality and safety===\nDrinking water is subject to a regime of testing under the Health Act to verify that the water meets standards.\n\nThe summary results of compliance testing for the 2017/18 year were:\n<ref name=\"MoH_quality_report\">{{cite web| url=https://www.health.govt.nz/system/files/documents/publications/drinking-water-annual-report-appendix-1-revised-aug2019.pdf| title= Annual Report on Drinking-water Quality 2017\u201318 \u2013 Appendix 1: Water supply compliance| publisher= Ministry of Health| date= June 2019| accessdate=10 April 2020 |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200409204622/https://www.health.govt.nz/system/files/documents/publications/drinking-water-annual-report-appendix-1-revised-aug2019.pdf |archive-date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Supplier !! Region/ Town !! Health Act !! Standards\n|-\n| Greater Wellington Water || Wellington urban area \u2013 bulk supply || Complied || Met\n|-\n| Hutt City Council || Lower Hutt || Complied || Met\n|-\n| Kapiti Coast District Council || Otaki ||  Complied || Failed\n|-\n| Kapiti Coast District Council || Paekakariki || Complied || Failed\n|-\n| Kapiti Coast District Council || Waikanae, Paraparaumu, Raumati || Complied || Met\n|-\n| Porirua City Council || Porirua || Complied || Met\n|-\n| Upper Hutt City Council || Upper Hutt || Complied || Met\n|-\n| Wellington City Council || Wellington City || Complied || Met\n|-\n| Carterton District Council || Carterton || Failed || Failed\n|-\n| Masterton District Council || Masterton || Complied || Met\n|-\n| Opaki Water Supply Association || Opaki || Complied || Failed\n|-\n| South Wairarapa District Council || Featherston || Failed || Failed\n|-\n| South Wairarapa District Council || Greytown || Failed || Failed\n|-\n| South Wairarapa District Council || Martinborough || Failed || Failed\n|}\n\n====Waiwhetu aquifer====\nUp until late 2016, bores in the Waterloo well field were considered to be secure. However, a rising trend in bacterial count and E.coli detections triggered a review.  At that stage, about half the customers supplied from the Waterloo treatment station received unchlorinated water.\n\nDuring 2016 and 2017, water supply businesses throughout New Zealand became aware of the severe public health consequences of the [[Water supply and sanitation in New Zealand#Havelock North drinking water contamination|Havelock North drinking water contamination]] incident and the subsequent Government inquiry that recommended all drinking water supplies should be chlorinated.\n\nIn 2017, a decision was made by Greater Wellington Regional Council to chlorinate all the water drawn from the Waiwhetu aquifer.\n<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/91824154/hutt-authorities-to-continue-chlorinating-drinking-water-as-investigations-into-e-coli-continue | title= Hutt authorities to continue chlorinating drinking water as investigations into E coli continue | publisher= Stuff | date=22 April 2017 |accessdate=9 April 2020|archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200411025442/https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/91824154/hutt-authorities-to-continue-chlorinating-drinking-water-as-investigations-into-e-coli-continue |archive-date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Martinborough====\nThere were two periods during early 2019 when a \"boil water\" notice was issued to the residents of Martinborough. \n<ref>{{cite news |last= Fuller |first= Piers |title= Martinborough residents celebrate having drinkable water again after boil water notice lifted |url= https://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/news/wairarapa/112795055/martinborough-residents-celebrate-having-drinkable-water-again-after-boil-water-notice-lifted |work= Stuff |location= |date= 17 May 2019|access-date= 11 April 2020 |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200411032026/https://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/news/wairarapa/112795055/martinborough-residents-celebrate-having-drinkable-water-again-after-boil-water-notice-lifted|archive-date=11 April 2020 }}</ref>\nIn November 2019, Wellington Water said that Martinborough residents needed to restrict demand to avoid restrictions and also to prevent the water from becoming discoloured if it became necessary to draw water from bores that have a higher naturally occurring manganese content.\n<ref>{{cite news |last= Te |first= Mandy |title= Martinborough residents told to save water following a spike in demand |url= https://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/news/wairarapa/117764878/martinborough-residents-told-to-save-water-following-a-spike-in-demand |work= Stuff |location= |date= 27 November 2019|access-date= 11 April 2020 |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200411033051/https://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/news/wairarapa/117764878/martinborough-residents-told-to-save-water-following-a-spike-in-demand|archive-date=11 April 2020 }}</ref>\nIn December 2019, the South Wairarapa District Council announced that a manganese extraction plant would be installed that would help keep water clear, and boost supply by enabling use of all four bores adjacent to the Ruamahanga River.\n<ref>{{cite news |last= Anselm |first= Marcus|date= 12 December 2019|title= More water troubles in Martinborough|url= https://times-age.co.nz/more-water-troubles-in-martinborough/ |work= Wairarapa Times-Age|location= |access-date= 12 April 2020|archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200412010456/https://times-age.co.nz/more-water-troubles-in-martinborough/|archive-date=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Resilience===\n====Wellington urban area====\nThe supply of water to the Wellington region is potentially vulnerable to significant disruption in the event of failures caused by a major earthquake.\nIn 2013, [[GNS Science]] published a study examining a wide range of issues about the impacts of a large earthquake on Wellington's water supply.  Some of the key findings and implications for Civil Defence and Emergency Management from this report include:\n<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.gns.cri.nz/static/pubs/2013/SR%202013-015.pdf\n|title= Water needs and the availability of water in post-earthquake Wellington City, and the significance of social factors in determining community resilience |author= Beban, J.G.; Doody, B,J.; Wright, K.C.; Cousins, W.J,;Becker,J.S. |date= December 2013\n|website= |publisher= GNS Science|access-date= |quote= |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200412001634/https://www.gns.cri.nz/static/pubs/2013/SR%202013-015.pdf|archive-date=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n* The amount of water people have stored in their homes\n* The importance of reservoirs in the provision of water post-earthquake\n* People's willingness to collect and carry water from reservoirs to their homes\n* The importance of developing alternative sources of water to cater for post-earthquake demand\n* The prioritization of water supplies\n\nIn 2016, the Wellington Lifelines Group began work on a Regional Resilience Project, with the aim of ensuring that core infrastructure is as resilient as possible and can enable rapid economic recovery following a major earthquake.\n\nIn October 2019, the Wellington Lifelines Group published their report \"Protecting Wellington's Economy Through Accelerated Infrastructure Investment Programme Business Case\".\nThe appendices to this report include studies of possible impacts of a major earthquake.  The base case studies show that in a major earthquake, the Wellington region would be likely to lose its water supplies for a period of between 3 and 6 months, with treated water potentially not available for up to 12 months.  A wide range of risk mitigation projects were identified and included in modelling to show the potential improvements in resilience.  The risk mitigation projects included works to reduce the risk posed to the bulk water supply that runs parallel to the line of the main Wellington fault.  The modelling of outages indicates that the outage time would reduce to between one and three months, if all the identified risk mitigations were implemented.\n<ref>{{cite web| url=https://wremo.nz/assets/Uploads/Wellington-Lifelines-PBC-MAIN-Combined-20191009.pdf| title= Wellington Lifelines Project \u2013 Regional Resilience Report | publisher= Wellington Region Emergency Management Office| date= Oct 2019| accessdate=11 April 2020 |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200411040711/https://wremo.nz/assets/Uploads/Wellington-Lifelines-PBC-MAIN-Combined-20191009.pdf |archive-date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe report called on its 16 member organisations to help deliver 25 key infrastructure projects across the region over the next two decades, at a cost of $5.3b. It was forecast that implementing these projects would save the country more than $6.1b in lost economic activity in the five years following a major earthquake\nThe list of 25 proposed projects covers a range of lifeline utilities.  The proposed water supply resilience projects are shown below.\n<ref>{{cite news |last=George|first=Damian |url= https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/nz-earthquake/117783826/wellington-lifelines-group-calls-for-20year-investment-programme-to-guard-against-major-earthquake |title= Wellington Lifelines Group calls for 20-year investment programme to guard against major earthquake|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= 3 December 2019|website= |publisher= Stuff |access-date= 12 April 2020|quote=}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Project !! Description !! Est cost !! Timeframe\n|-\n| Cross-harbour pipeline || Build 12.7&nbsp;km underwater pipeline from Seaview to Evans Bay, with connection to Carmichael Reservoir || $139m || 2020\u20132023\n|-\n| Prince of Wales and Bell Rd reservoir upgrade || Build 35 megalitre reservoir at Prince of Wales Park and 10 megalitre reservoir at Bell Rd || $78m || 2019\u20132025\n|-\n| Silverstream Bridge pipeline replacement || Replace Te Marua-to-Ngauranga pipeline where it crosses Silverstream Bridge and Wellington Fault || $23m || 2019\u20132021\n|-\n| General toughening of pipes || Upgrade 152&nbsp;km network of critical ductile pipes || $654m || 2019\u20132025\n|-\n| Carmichael to Johnsonville and Karori pipeline || New water main between Carmichael Reservoir and pump station near Omaroro Reservoir; pump station between cross-harbour pipeline and Johnsonville; water main between Omaroro Reservoir and Churchill Drive; upgrade to batter slopes along Grant Rd, Lennel Rd, and Wadestown Rd || $247m || 2026\u20132031\n|-\n| Porirua low-level zone reservoirs || Build additional nine-megalitre reservoir, and three-megalitre storage area at Takapuwahia || $25m || 2026\u20132028\n|-\n| Waterloo Water Treatment Plant upgrade || Reduce liquefaction risk and improve ground at southern end, or provide extra structural support || $2m || 2029\u20132032\n|-\n| General toughening of pipes ||As above ||n/a || 2026\u20132032\n|}\n\n==== Om\u0101roro/Prince of Wales reservoir====\nIn 2017, Wellington Water applied for the designation of an easement required for the construction of a 35 million litre reservoir on land within the Wellington Town Belt, at Prince of Wales Park in the Wellington suburb of [[Mount Cook, Wellington|Mt Cook]].\n\nThe application for the easement referenced a 2009 study conducted by GNS of possible earthquake damage to the water network.  This study estimated that for a magnitude 7.5 Richter scale earthquake, there would be about 30 breaks on the main trunk pipelines and 60 breaks on the smaller branch lines. There could be as many as 8,000 breaks in the Wellington City local supply network. Bulk water supply and treatment facilities are also expected to suffer damage requiring repair. Wellington Water and Greater Wellington Regional Council estimated that it would take around 60\u201070 days to restore bulk water supply to parts of the Wellington metropolitan area.It could take several years to fully repair damage to the local water distribution network resulting from a severe earthquake, as much of the network may have to be rebuilt.\n<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.wellingtonwater.co.nz/dmsdocument/215\n|title= Prince of Wales \u2013 Omaroro Reservoir \u2013 Town Belt Easement Request \u2013 Includes Appendix A|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= 1 June 2017|website= |publisher= Wellington Water |access-date= 12 April 2020|quote= |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200412204753/https://www.wellingtonwater.co.nz/dmsdocument/215|archive-date=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2018, an independent panel recommended that Wellington City Council confirm the designation of the easement for the reservoir.\n<ref>{{cite web |url= https://wellington.govt.nz/your-council/news/2018/05/prince-of-wales-park-reservoir\n|title= Green light for Om\u0101roro/Prince of Wales Park reservoir|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= 14 May 2018|website= |publisher= Wellington City Council |access-date= 12 April 2020|quote= |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200412212844/https://wellington.govt.nz/your-council/news/2018/05/prince-of-wales-park-reservoir|archive-date=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe reservoir provides a significant increase in water storage for the city, and forms part of the city's resilience strategy to help ensure that fresh water is available to residents after a natural disaster or major network failure.\n\nPreparatory earthworks for the project commenced in February 2019.\n<ref>{{cite news |last= Hunt|first=Tom |date= 5 February 2019|title=  Reservoir earthworks marks beginning of Wellington's Mt Cook becoming a 'building-site suburb'|url= https://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/news/110374164/reservoir-earthworks-marks-beginning-of-wellingtons-mt-cook-becoming-a-buildingsite-suburb|work= Stuff|location= |access-date=12 April 2020 |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200412010647/https://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/news/110374164/reservoir-earthworks-marks-beginning-of-wellingtons-mt-cook-becoming-a-buildingsite-suburb|archive-date=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Stormwater==\n\n===Pipeline age and condition===\nThe 2018/19 National Performance Review published by Water New Zealand compares the average stormwater pipeline age and condition across networks. The data for the Wellington Water network shows that 16% of the pipelines are in poor or very poor condition.  The Wellington stormwater network ranks the worst on this measure out of the six large networks nationwide.\n<ref name=\"Pipeline_condition\" />\nThe review also includes average pipeline age. The Wellington stormwater network has an average age of 49 years, and ranks as the second oldest of the six large networks.\n<ref name=\"Pipeline_age\" />\n\n==Wastewater==\nProperties in urban areas in the Wellington Region are generally all connected to a wastewater system via a [[gravity sewer]].  In some cases, pumps are used to pump wastewater to a treatment plant, or to lift wastewater from lower level drains into a higher elevation gravity sewer so that it can flow to a treatment plant. \n===Wellington urban area===\nWellington's population grew rapidly in the late 19th century after it became the capital city in 1865.\nThere were increasing cases of typhoid and cholera which were attributed to poor sanitation. In 1879 there were 75 deaths in Wellington from typhoid, diphtheria, scarlet fever, measles and cholera \u2013 mostly in the central Te Aro area. \n<ref>{{cite web| last= Roberts| first=Sofia|url=https://www.museumswellington.org.nz/wellingtons-unsightly-and-smelly-past/| title= Wellington\u2019s unsightly and smelly past | publisher= Museums Wellington| accessdate=14 April 2020 |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200414015917/https://www.museumswellington.org.nz/wellingtons-unsightly-and-smelly-past/| archive-date=14 April 2020 }}</ref>\nAfter some political deliberation, construction of a city wastewater network began in 1893. It cost \u00a3175,000 and was completed by 1899.\n\n====The interceptor====\nAs part of the early development of the wastewater network, a large pipe was constructed to take wastewater from Manners St through Mt Victoria and out to an ocean outfall at Moa Point on the south coast.  This main trunk wastewater line was known as \"the interceptor\". In the 1930s the interceptor was extended from Manners St through to Pipitea St, as the city's population topped 100,000.\nAs suburbs spread further north to [[Johnsonville, New Zealand|Johnsonville]], another extension of the interceptor was made from [[Ngauranga Gorge]] and through [[Ngaio, New Zealand|Ngaio]] Gorge to connect at [[Thorndon, New Zealand|Thorndon]].\n<ref name=\u201dinterceptor\u201d>{{cite news| last= Campbell| first=Georgina |url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=12313567| title= Severe corrosion discovered in critical Wellington wastewater pipe| publisher= NZ Herald| date=4 March 2020|accessdate=14 April 2020 | archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200414012313/https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=12313567| archive-date=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Wastewater treatment====\nThere are four wastewater treatment plants serving the Wellington urban area.\nTogether, they treat about 150 million litres of wastewater on a typical day, using biological and ultraviolet treatment processes. The treated water is discharged to the sea. The sludge resulting from filtration and treatment is de-watered (with this water further treated) and the solid content is sent to landfills.\n<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.learnz.org.nz/water172/bg-standard-f/wastewater/| title= Wastewater | publisher= LEARNZ| accessdate=14 April 2020 | archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200414020034/http://www.learnz.org.nz/water172/bg-standard-f/wastewater/|archive-date=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.wellingtonwater.co.nz/your-water/wastewater/where-does-wastewater-go/| title= Where does wastewater go| publisher= Wellington Water| accessdate=14 April 2020 |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200414020137/https://www.wellingtonwater.co.nz/your-water/wastewater/where-does-wastewater-go/|archive-date=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Moa Point====\nThe Moa Point treatment plant handles all the wastewater from most of Wellington city, other than Karori and some northern suburbs.  Treated wastewater is discharged via a 1.8&nbsp;km ocean outfall into Cook Strait.  Sludge is separated from the wastewater at the plant, and pumped to a landfill site at Carey's Gully, where it is dewatered and placed into a landfill.\n\n====Seaview====\nThe Seaview plant handles wastewater from Upper Hutt and Lower Hutt.  There is an ocean outfall at [[Pencarrow Head]].\n\n====Porirua====\nA treatment plant located at Rukutane Point handles wastewater from the northern suburbs of Wellington and Porirua city.  There is an ocean outfall from the plant.\n<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.wellingtonwater.co.nz/pwp/the-wastewater-system/| title= Your wastewater system | publisher= Wellington Water| accessdate=14 April 2020 |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200414020513/https://www.wellingtonwater.co.nz/pwp/the-wastewater-system/| archive-date=14 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n====Karori====\nA separate wastewater and treatment system serves the Karori area.  Treated wastewater is piped out to the South Coast.\n\n===Network condition and performance===\n====Pipeline age and condition====\nThe 2018/19 National Performance Review published by Water New Zealand compares the average wastewater pipeline age and condition across networks. The data for the Wellington Water network shows that 33% of the pipelines are in poor or very poor condition. The Wellington wastewater network ranks the worst on this measure out of the six large networks nationwide. (The next worst is Christchurch, with only 12% in poor or very poor condition).\n<ref name=\"Pipeline_condition\" />\nThe review also includes average pipeline age. The Wellington wastewater network has an average age of 53 years, and ranks as the second oldest of the six large networks.\n<ref name=\"Pipeline_age\" />\n\nIn March 2020, Wellington Water reported the discovery of severe corrosion in the large main trunk sewer (the interceptor) over a length of 250&nbsp;m in a section close to the treatment plant near Moa Point.<ref name=\u201dinterceptor\u201d></ref>\n\n====Porirua network issues====\nAs part of a submission to a Porirua City Council committee in 2018 in relation to renewing resource consents, Wellington Water provided a background document about the issues in the Porirua wastewater system.  The issues reported included:<ref>{{cite web |url= https://poriruacity.govt.nz/documents/1296/1619_-_19_-_WWTP_-_OR_Porirua_Wastewater_Consenting.pdf|title= Porirua Wastewater Consenting |last= |first= |date=14 February 2018 |website= |publisher= Porirua City Council |access-date= 14 April 2020|archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200416020516/https://poriruacity.govt.nz/documents/1296/1619_-_19_-_WWTP_-_OR_Porirua_Wastewater_Consenting.pdf| archive-date=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n* poor existing freshwater quality in the Porirua catchment\n* frequent overflows from wastewater networks into freshwater and coastal water during periods of wet weather, and overflows from the wastewater treatment plant into coastal water\n* inflow and infiltration from stormwater into the wastewater network\n* ageing network prone to failures and with insufficient capacity to accommodate future growth\n* insufficient capacity of the treatment plant to accommodate future growth\nIn February 2020, the Mayor of Porirua announced the establishment of a roving team to search for issues such as cross connections in stormwater and sewage pipes.  As part of that announcement, it was revealed that more than half of Porirua's wastewater pipes are in a poor condition, and that it will cost close to $2 billion over the next two to three decades to bring them up to scratch.\n<ref>{{ cite news| last= | first= |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/news/national/410679/porirua-s-wastewater-woes-get-250-000-boost| title= Porirua's wastewater woes get $250,000 boost | work= RNZ | date=29 February 2020|accessdate=14 April 2020 | archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200416020341/https://www.rnz.co.nz/news/national/410679/porirua-s-wastewater-woes-get-250-000-boost | archive-date=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Significant incidents===\n====\u014cwhiro Bay sewage pollution====\n\u014cwhiro Bay is located on the Wellington south coast.  The shoreline is within the [[Taputeranga Marine Reserve]]. There have been persistent problems with sewage pollution of the \u014cwhiro Stream and beach for at least ten years, and the beach has been closed for swimming for long periods.\n<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/national/3342307/Owhiro-Bay-beach-closed| title= Owhiro Bay beach closed| work= Stuff| date=17 February 2010|accessdate=16 Apr 2020 | archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200416022541/http://www.stuff.co.nz/national/3342307/Owhiro-Bay-beach-closed | archive-date=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite news| last=Stewart|first=Matt|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/news/eastern-suburbs/6574251/Pollution-warning-for-Owhiro-Bay| title= Pollution warning for Owhiro Bay| work= Stuff| date=14 March 2012|accessdate=16 Apr 2020 | archive-url= http://web.archive.org/web/20200416024211/http://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/news/eastern-suburbs/6574251/Pollution-warning-for-Owhiro-Bay | archive-date=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite news| last= Hunt|first=Tom|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/news/118890119/sewage-in-wellington-marine-reserve-43times-worse-than-acceptable-levels| title= Sewage in Wellington marine reserve 43-times worse than acceptable levels| work= Stuff| date=19 January 2020|accessdate=16 Apr 2020 | archive-url= http://web.archive.org/web/20200416023740/https://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/news/118890119/sewage-in-wellington-marine-reserve-43times-worse-than-acceptable-levels|archive-date= 16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, Wellington Water announced that it had found and resolved incorrect connections of wastewater into stormwater systems at five locations in a suburb in the stormwater catchment area of the \u014cwhiro Stream.  Wellington Water said that the mistake occurred when the subdivision was built about eight years ago, and there were likely to be more cross-connections that it had yet to identify.\n<ref>{{cite news| last= George|first=Damian| url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/120187481/wastewater-spilling-into-wellington-stream-since-pipes-incorrectly-laid-in-subdivision-eight-years-ago| title= Wastewater spilling into Wellington stream since pipes incorrectly laid in subdivision eight years ago| work= Stuff| date=11 March 2020|accessdate=16 Apr 2020 | archive-url= http://web.archive.org/web/20200416022804/https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/120187481/wastewater-spilling-into-wellington-stream-since-pipes-incorrectly-laid-in-subdivision-eight-years-ago| archive-date=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n====Illegal discharge from Porirua treatment plant====\nIn October 2018, a series of errors and omissions in the management of the Porirua wastewater treatment plant led to a spill of approximately 5000 cubic metres of wastewater and solids from the outfall into a small bay adjacent to Titahi Bay beach.  In a subsequent hearing in the Environment Court in September 2019, Wellington Water was fined $65,000 for the illegal discharge.\n<ref>{{cite news| last= Boyack | first= Nicholas |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/environment/115781832/wellington-water-fined--67500-for-illegal-discharge-into-sea-near-titahi-bay| title= Wellington Water fined $67,500 for illegal discharge into sea near Titahi Bay| work= Stuff| date=13 September 2019 |accessdate=15 April 2020 | archive-url= http://web.archive.org/web/20200415013049/https://www.stuff.co.nz/environment/115781832/wellington-water-fined--67500-for-illegal-discharge-into-sea-near-titahi-bay | archive-date=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n====Pipeline collapse in Dixon St====\nOn 20 December 2019, a wastewater pipe built in the 1930\u2019s collapsed beneath the intersection of Willis and Dixon Streets in the central business district, leading to the diversion of untreated wastewater into [[Wellington harbour]] at an initial rate of up to 100 litres a second.\nThe broken pipe serves much of the central city, taking wastewater to the interceptor (or main trunk sewer), that leads to the Moa Point wastewater treatment plant.  The public were warned not to swim in the inner harbour, but local iwi placed a [[r\u0101hui]] on the entire Wellington harbour.\n<ref name=\u201ddixon\u201d>{{cite news| author=RNZ |url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=12295880| title= Sewage going into Wellington harbour after pipe collapse|work= NZ Herald| date=20 December 2019|accessdate=14 April 2020 |archive-url= http://web.archive.org/web/20200416023233/https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=12295880| archive-date=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAn emergency above-ground pipe was placed along Upper Willis street \u2013 closing it to all traffic  \u2013 to bypass the failed underground pipe while permanent repairs were made. The swimming restriction on the whole of Wellington Harbour was lifted on 26 December. However, the area of the inner harbour from the [[Whairepo Lagoon]] entrance past the dive platform to the Clyde Quay wharf remained off-limits because of a \u201cseparate network issue\u201d.  \n<ref> {{cite news| |url= http://wellington.scoop.co.nz/?p=124862/| title= Harbour swimming ban lifted \u2013 but not everywhere|work= Scoop| date=27 December 2019|accessdate=14 April 2020 | archive-url= http://web.archive.org/web/20200416023400/http://wellington.scoop.co.nz/?p=124862%2F| archive-date=16 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\nWillis Street was eventually re-opened at the end of March 2020, after the permanent replacement had been installed beneath the road, and the temporary above-ground pipe removed.\n<ref> {{cite news| |url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=12295880| title= Willis Street in Wellington to reopen after pipe replaced |work= Stuff| date=27 March 2020|accessdate=14 April 2020 | archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200416023251/https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=12295880 | archive-date= 16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Failure of sludge pipeline beneath Mt Albert====\nIn January 2020, there was a failure of pipelines carrying sludge pumped at high pressure from the Moa Point treatment plant to the landfill at Carey\u2019s Gully.  The pipelines are 9&nbsp;km long and are about 25 years old.  There are two in parallel allowing one to operate while maintenance can occur on the other pipe.  In this incident both pipes failed at the same time.  \n\nTo avoid discharging the sludge into the ocean, a fleet of sewage trucks was mobilized to carry about one million litres of sludge a day to the dewatering plant at Carey\u2019s Gully. Up to 150 round trips each day were required, with trucks sometimes operating around the clock to keep up with the volume. \n\nThe break in the pipelines was located 200&nbsp;m inside a sewage tunnel beneath Mt Albert, making repairs a significant challenge. The repair solution required the manufacture in Germany of a custom-made polyester woven liner.  This liner was winched from one end of each pipe to the other, and then expanded to essentially act as a new pipeline within the old one.  Specialists from the manufacturer flew to New Zealand to assist in the installation, but were required to spend 14 days in isolation because of the border restrictions imposed in response to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in New Zealand|COVID-19 pandemic]].\n<ref>{{cite news| last= Thomas | first= Rachel |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/news/national/408078/broken-mt-albert-sewer-tunnel-pipe-costly-effort-to-divert-millions-of-litres-of-sludge| title= Broken Mt Albert sewer tunnel pipe: Costly effort to divert millions of litres of sludge| work= RNZ| date=24 January 2020 |accessdate=15 April 2020 | archive-url= http://web.archive.org/web/20200415014537/https://www.rnz.co.nz/news/national/408078/broken-mt-albert-sewer-tunnel-pipe-costly-effort-to-divert-millions-of-litres-of-sludge | archive-date=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite news |last=Campbell|first=Georgina|url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=12318739| title= Coronavirus: Major Wellington wastewater pipe repairs delayed| work= NZ Herald| date=21 March 2020 |accessdate=15 April 2020 | archive-url= http://web.archive.org/web/20200415035134/https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=12318739 | archive-date=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite news|url=http://wellington.scoop.co.nz/?p=127088 | title= Six German experts will fix broken sludge pipeline next month | work= Scoop| date=5 April 2020|accessdate=15 April 2020 | archive-url= http://web.archive.org/web/20200415021810/http://wellington.scoop.co.nz/?p=127088| archive-date=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n====South Wairarapa====\nAlmost half a million litres of partially and fully treated wastewater was discharged into the [[Ruamahanga River]] near Martinborough in two incidents in January 2020, as a result of issues at a treatment plant. Under suitable conditions, discharging fully treated wastewater to the river is a consented activity.  However, when the river level is low, as in this case, this type of discharge is a breach of the resource consent.\n<ref>{{cite news |last= Anselm|first= Marcus|date= 18 January 2020|title= Water problems continue in south|url= https://times-age.co.nz/water-problems-continue-in-south/|work= Wairarapa Times-Age|location= |access-date= 12 April 2020|archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200411214833/https://times-age.co.nz/water-problems-continue-in-south/|archive-date=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite news |last= Campbell|first= Georgina|date= 31 January 2020|title= Second wastewater discharge into Wairarapa river this year raises concerns|url= https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=12305059 |work= NZ Herald|location= |access-date= 12 April 2020|archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200411214943/https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=12305059|archive-date=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Water in New Zealand]]\n* [[Water supply and sanitation in New Zealand]]\n* [[Water purification]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.wellingtonwater.co.nz// Wellington Water]\n* [https://www.dia.govt.nz/Three-waters-review Three Waters Review] at the Department of Internal Affairs\n* [https://www.waternz.org.nz/  Water New Zealand (New Zealand Water and Wastes Association)]\n* [https://www.gw.govt.nz/history-of-our-water-supply History of our water supply] at the Greater Wellington Regional Council\n* [http://www.gw.govt.nz/assets/council-publications/Regional%20Parks_20011127_163445.pdf Wonderful Water Walks \u2013 A History of Water Supply Dams in the Wellington Region] at the Greater Wellington Regional Council\n\n[[Category:Water supply and sanitation in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Wellington Region]]\n", "name_user": "Marshelec", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eWastewater treatment", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Water_supply_and_sanitation_in_the_Wellington_region"}
{"title_page": "Sand Springs, Oklahoma", "text_new": "{{short description|City in Osage, Creek, and Tulsa counties, Oklahoma, United States}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                     = Sand Springs, Oklahoma\n| settlement_type          = [[City]]\n| image_skyline            = \n| image_caption            = \n| image_blank_emblem       = Sand Springs logo.png\n| nickname                 = \n| motto                    = \n| image_map                = Tulsa County Oklahoma incorporated and unincorporated areas Sand Springs highlighted.svg\n| mapsize                  = 250px\n| map_caption              = Location within [[Tulsa County, OK|Tulsa County]] and [[Oklahoma]]\n| pushpin_map              = USA\n| pushpin_map_caption      = Location in the United States\n| coordinates              = {{coord|36|8|23|N|96|6|32|W|region:US-OK|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type         = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n| subdivision_name         = United States\n| subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n| subdivision_name1        = [[Oklahoma]]\n| subdivision_type2        = [[List of counties in Oklahoma|Counties]]\n| subdivision_name2        = [[Tulsa County, Oklahoma|Tulsa]], [[Osage County, Oklahoma|Osage]], [[Creek County]]\n| established_date         = 1912\n| government_type          = [[City Council]]\n| leader_title             = [[Mayor]]\n| leader_name              = Mike Burdge\n| area_total_km2           = 54.20\n| area_total_sq_mi         = 20.92\n| area_land_km2            = 50.19\n| area_land_sq_mi          = 19.38\n| area_water_km2           = 4.00\n| area_water_sq_mi         = 1.54\n| elevation_m              = 240\n| elevation_ft             = 670\n| population_total         = 18906\n| population_as_of         = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n| population_density_km2   = 396.40\n| population_density_sq_mi = 1026.68\n| population_metro         = \n| population_note          = \n| timezone                 = [[North American Central Time Zone|CST]]\n| utc_offset               = -6\n| timezone_DST             = [[North American Central Time Zone|CDT]]\n| utc_offset_DST           = -5\n| postal_code_type         = [[ZIP code]]\n| postal_code              = 74063\n| area_code                = [[area codes 539 and 918|539/918]]\n| blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n| blank_info               = 40-65300<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2008-01-31|title=U.S. Census website}}</ref>\n| blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n| blank1_info              = 1097783<ref name=\"GR3\">{{cite web|url=http://geonames.usgs.gov|accessdate=2008-01-31|title=US Board on Geographic Names|publisher=[[United States Geological Survey]]|date=2007-10-25|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120212191832/http://geonames.usgs.gov/|archivedate=2012-02-12}}</ref>\n| website                  = {{URL|http://www.sandspringsok.org/}}\n|pop_est_as_of = 2018\n|pop_est_footnotes = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2018CenPopScriptOnlyDirtyFixDoNotUse\"/>\n|population_est = 19897\n|unit_pref = Imperial\n|area_footnotes = <ref name=\"CenPopGazetteer2016\">{{cite web|title=2018 U.S. Gazetteer Files|url=https://www2.census.gov/geo/docs/maps-data/data/gazetteer/2018_Gazetteer/2018_gaz_place_40.txt|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=Feb 12, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Sand Springs''' is a city in [[Osage County, Oklahoma|Osage]], [[Creek County|Creek]], and [[Tulsa County, Oklahoma|Tulsa]] counties in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Oklahoma]]. A western suburb of [[Tulsa, Oklahoma|Tulsa]], it is located predominantly in Tulsa County. The population was 18,906 in the 2010 U. S. Census, an increase of 8.3 percent from 17,451 at the [[United States Census, 2000|2000 census]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://censusviewer.com/city/OK/Sand+Springs|title=Sand Springs, OK Population - Census 2010 and 2000 Interactive Map, Demographics, Statistics, Quick Facts - CensusViewer|website=censusviewer.com|accessdate=24 April 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180424123654/http://censusviewer.com/city/OK/Sand+Springs|archivedate=24 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe city was founded in 1911, by [[philanthropist]] [[Charles Page]], a wealthy businessman in Oklahoma. He envisioned Sand Springs as a haven for orphans and widows.  He helped found and develop Sand Springs as a model city that included all components of a total community.<ref name=\"EOHC-SS\">[http://www.okhistory.org/publications/enc/entry.php?entry=SA017 Carl N. Gregory, \"Sand Springs\", ''Encyclopedia of Oklahoma History and Culture''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402133246/http://www.okhistory.org/publications/enc/entry.php?entry=SA017 |date=2015-04-02 }}, Accessed May 6, 2011.</ref>\n\nPage bought 160 acres of land in Tulsa County, Oklahoma in 1908, intending to build a home for orphan children. The first 27 children, who had been abandoned by the Hook & Anchor Orphanage in Tulsa,<!-- what does this mean? they threw the orphans out? --> were housed in a tent. This was soon replaced by a frame building large enough to house 50 children.\n\nPage decided to form a model community, to be called Sand Springs, on land west of the children's home. He offered free land to any person who wished to move there, and a $20,000 bonus (the amount varied and he also offered free utilities) to companies that would relocate there. In 1911, Page created the [[Sand Springs Railway]], an interurban connecting Sand Springs to Tulsa. The townsite was laid out the same year.<ref name = \"EOHC-SS\"/> Sand Springs was incorporated as a city in 1912, with a population of 400.<ref name=\"Davenport\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tulsaokhistory.com/cities/sandsprings.html|title=History of Sand Springs, OK|website=www.tulsaokhistory.com|accessdate=24 April 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107112750/http://www.tulsaokhistory.com/cities/sandsprings.html|archivedate=7 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 1911 Page also built the Sand Springs Power Plant, on the southeast corner of Main Street and Morrow Road. It anchored an area that Page intended to use for industrial development. Several significant additions were made to the facility, and it was the sole source of electric power for Sand Springs until 1947.<ref>National Register of Historic Places Registration Form. \"Sand Springs Power Plant.\"</ref>\n\nSome of the earliest manufacturing industries were: Kerr Glass Manufacturing; Commander Mills, Kerr, Hubbard and Kelley Lamp, and Chimney; Southwest Box Company; and Sinclair Prairie Refining Company. Medical and social welfare institutions other than the Sand Springs Home included the Oakwood Sanitorium for nervous and mental diseases, Poole Hospital, the Salvation Army Maternity Home, and the Sand Springs School for the Deaf.<ref name = \"Davenport\" /> Sand Springs became a center of glass production in Oklahoma. Kerr Glass Manufacturing moved to Sand Springs from Chicago in 1913. It and the Alexander H. Kerr company, which made fruit jars, were the only glass companies remaining in business as recently as 1955.<ref name=\"EOHC-Glass\">[http://digital.library.okstate.edu/encyclopedia/entries/G/GL002.html Everett, Dianna. \"Glass Manufacturing\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110609161551/http://digital.library.okstate.edu/encyclopedia/entries/G/GL002.html |date=2011-06-09 }}, ''Encyclopedia of Oklahoma History and Culture''.</ref>\n\nThe Children's Home is still operating. What used to be the Widows Colony now accepts single mothers with two or more children.\n\nAn EF2 tornado hit Sand Springs on March 25, 2015, killing one resident, injuring 30 citizens, and damaging 50 mobile homes.<ref>https://www.weather.gov/oun/tornadodata-county-ok-tulsa</ref>\n\nOn November 26, 2018, Clyde Boyd Middle School had a [[Carbon Monoxide]] leak. The leak started sometime around the morning. Between 11:15 and 12:58, five students went homesick. And between 1:15 to 1:35, seven more students got sick.<ref>https://www.newson6.com/story/39546855/middle-school-students-treated-after-sand-springs-carbon-monoxide-leak</ref> Around 2:27, an announcement on the intercom told all the students to \"go to the new gym\". Many students went to the hospital from [[Carbon Monoxide Poisoning]]. \"There was no evidence of the presence of carbon monoxide in the 6th Grade Center\". Over 50 students were sent to nearby hospitals. The school didn't have carbon monoxide detectors at the time which the district says \"it'll resolve\". The School was closed for several days while they fixed the problem. <ref>https://www.newson6.com/story/39553912/sand-springs-school-still-closed-after-carbon-monoxide-leak</ref> \nThe district has now installed [[carbon monoxide detectors]].\n\n==Geography==\nSand Springs is located at {{coord|36|8|23|N|96|6|32|W|type:city}} (36.1398102, -96.1088911).<ref>{{GNIS|1092617}}</ref> According to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the city has a total area of 21.0&nbsp;square miles (54.3&nbsp;km\u00b2), of which, 18.7&nbsp;square miles (48.4&nbsp;km\u00b2) of it is land and 2.3&nbsp;square miles (5.9&nbsp;km\u00b2) of it (10.84%) is water. The one-way driving distance between Sand Springs and Tulsa (downtown to downtown) is about {{convert|7|miles|km}}. It is roughly located in the western section of [[Tulsa County]] and the Southern section of [[Osage County, Oklahoma|Osage County]] and has a small sliver of it within [[Creek County|Creek County's Northern western border]].<ref>https://www.openstreetmap.org/relation/184998#map=15/36.0745/-96.2046</ref><ref>https://ok.postcodebase.com/city/SAND%20SPRINGS</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1920= 4067\n|1930= 6674\n|1940= 6137\n|1950= 6994\n|1960= 7754\n|1970= 10555\n|1980= 13121\n|1990= 15346\n|2000= 17451\n|2010= 18906\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=19897\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018CenPopScriptOnlyDirtyFixDoNotUse\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=June 4, 2019}}</ref>\n|footnote=<ref name = \"EOHC-SS\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.census.gov/popest/data/cities/totals/2011/tables/SUB-EST2011-03-40.csv|title=Archived copy|accessdate=2017-12-07|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160203042832/http://www.census.gov/popest/data/cities/totals/2011/tables/SUB-EST2011-03-40.csv|archivedate=2016-02-03 }}</ref>\n}}\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name=\"GR2\" /> of 2000, there were 17,451 people, 6,564 households, and 4,870 families residing in the city. The [[population density]] was 934.2 people per square mile (360.7/km\u00b2). There were 6,979 housing units at an average density of 373.6 per square mile (144.3/km\u00b2). The racial makeup of the city was 85.85% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 1.85% [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], 7.13% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 0.44% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 0.02% [[Pacific Islander (U.S. Census)|Pacific Islander]], 0.47% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 4.25% from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 2.06% of the population.\n\nThere were 6,564 households out of which 38.1% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 58.3% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 12.3% had a female householder with no husband present, and 25.8% were non-families. 22.7% of all households were made up of individuals and 10.2% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.59 and the average family size was 3.05.\n\nIn the city, the population was spread out with 28.4% under the age of 18, 8.3% from 18 to 24, 28.9% from 25 to 44, 22.2% from 45 to 64, and 12.2% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 35 years. For every 100 females, there were 92.7 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 87.0 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the city was $40,380, and the median income for a family was $47,258. Males had a median income of $38,120 versus $25,373 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the city was $18,193. About 6.7% of families and 9.1% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 11.6% of those under age 18 and 7.6% of those age 65 or over.\n\n==Economy==\nThe economy of Sand Springs is largely focused on promoting small businesses. It has a very active chamber of commerce.\n\nAccording to the ''Encyclopedia of Oklahoma History & Culture'', the most significant businesses in 2000 were: Webco Industries, Sheffield Steel Corporation, Rader Diagnostic Center, Smith-Fibercast, Cust-O-Fab, Piping Companies Incorporated, and Baker Petrolite.<ref name = \"EOHC-SS\"/>\n\n==Historical Sites==\n{{main| National Register of Historic Places listings in Tulsa County, Oklahoma}} \nThe following are NRHP-listed sites in Sand Springs:\n*Fort Arbuckle Site, a/k/a Old Fort Arbuckle (west of Sand Springs)\n*Page Memorial Library (6 E. Broadway)\n*Sand Springs Power Plant (221 S.Main St.)\n\n==Education==\nThe Sand Springs Public School District is the largest employer in the city.  It contains five elementary schools, two middle schools, and three High Schools (two public and one private). It has a groundbreaking early childhood program.\n* [[Charles Page High School]]\n* [[Clyde Boyd Middle School]]\n* [[Central Ninth Grade Center]]\n* [[Angus Valley Elementary School]]\n* [[Harry T. Pratt Elementary School]]\n* [[Limestone Elementary School]]\n* [[Garfield Elementary School (Sand Springs, Oklahoma)|Garfield Elementary School]]\n* [[Northwoods Elementary School]]\n* Sixth Grade Center\n* Early Childhood Center\n* Page Academy (alternative)\n\nThere are also four private Christian schools in Sand Springs.\n* Amazing Grace Christian Academy\n* Heritage Baptist School\n* Landmark Christian Academy<ref>https://www.greatschools.org/oklahoma/sand-springs/3539-Landmark-Christian-Academy/</ref>\n* Moriah Christian Academy<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.MoriahChristianAcademy.com|title=Moriahchristianacademy.com|website=www.moriahchristianacademy.com|accessdate=24 April 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180416055846/http://moriahchristianacademy.com/|archivedate=16 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Media==\nSand Springs has one print newspaper, the [http://sandspringsleader.com ''Sand Springs Leader'']. It is published weekly on Thursday.\n\nOn April 21, 2015, the ''[[Tulsa World]]'' announced that its parent company BH Media,<ref>[http://www.bhmginc.com/ BH Media]</ref> a division of [[Berkshire Hathaway]], the Omaha-based investment holding company led by billionaire [[Warren Buffett]], had purchased several suburban newspapers, including the ''Sand Springs Leader''.<ref>[http://www.tulsaworld.com/business/employment/bh-media-group-buys-local-weeklies-tulsa-business-and-legal/article_3981761a-b40c-5fd3-8759-4898875c2e3f.html \"Media Group Buys Local Weeklies\"], ''[[Tulsa World]]''</ref><ref>[http://www.tulsaworld.com/opinion/editorials/tulsa-world-editorial-seven-local-newspapers-join-bh-media-family/article_dad541fd-9898-5de3-864e-23b818d6538d.html Opinion: \"Seven Local Newspapers Join BH Media Family\"], ''[[Tulsa World]]''</ref>\n\nSand Springs also has an online-only news source, ''Sandite Pride News'',<ref>[http://www.SanditePride.com ''Sandite Pride News'']</ref> which specializes in Sand Springs sports coverage.\n\n==Notable people==\n<!-- Include only people with existing WP article; must show connection to Sand Springs -->\n* [[Jerry Adair]] (1936\u20131987), professional baseball player<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.baseball-almanac.com/players/player.php?p=adairje01|title= Jerry Adair Stats|work= Baseball Almanac|accessdate= November 21, 2012|url-status= live|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20121024213933/http://www.baseball-almanac.com/players/player.php?p=adairje01|archivedate= October 24, 2012}}</ref>\n* [[Michael Bowie]] (b. 1991), professional football player and 2013 Super Bowl winner<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.washingtonpost.com/fb/playerstats.asp?id=26865|title=Football - NFL - Player Stats - Michael Bowie |website=The Washington Post |accessdate=24 April 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150908034814/http://stats.washingtonpost.com/fb/playerstats.asp?id=26865|archivedate=8 September 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Woody Crumbo]] (1912\u20131989), [[Aboriginal American|American Indian]] artist, [[flautist]], and dancer\n* [[Daton Fix]] (b. 1998), four-time undefeated state wrestling champion, national champion, Pan-American champion, Junior World Champion, Junior Olympic Silver Medalist, and Big 12 Champion.\n* [[Neal Hallford]] (b. 1966), [[game designer]], author, and film producer\n* [[Sam Harris (singer)|Sam Harris]] (b. 1961), Tony-nominated actor and singer who was Male Vocalist champion of the first season of ''[[Star Search]]''\n* [[Marques Haynes]] (1926\u20132015), [[Harlem Globetrotters]] player<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.okhistory.org/publications/enc/entry.php?entry=HA055|title=Haynes, Marques(1926- )|publisher=Encyclopedia of Oklahoma History & Culture|accessdate=November 21, 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402155842/http://www.okhistory.org/publications/enc/entry.php?entry=HA055|archivedate=April 2, 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Charles Page]] (1860\u20131926), [[oilman]], founder of Sand Springs\n* [[Cindy Pickett]] (b. 1947), actress\n* [[William R. Pogue]] (1930\u20132014), [[Skylab]] astronaut, author, and pilot\n* [[Robert D. Simms]] (1926\u20132008), native of Sand Springs, attorney, judge, Associate Justice of Oklahoma Supreme Court\n* [[Mae Young]] (1923\u20132014), professional wrestler<ref>{{cite web |author=Ryan Nation |date=March 27, 2008 |title=HOFer Mae Young vows to keep wrestling |url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/WrestleMania24/2008/03/27/5124611.html |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130101030256/http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/WrestleMania24/2008/03/27/5124611.html |archive-date=1 January 2013 |work=Slam! Wrestling |publisher=[[Canoe.ca|Canadian Online Explorer]] |access-date=29 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.sandspringsok.org/ City of Sand Springs]\n\n{{Osage County, Oklahoma}}\n{{Tulsa County, Oklahoma}}\n{{Tulsa metro}}\n{{NRHP in Tulsa County}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Cities in Tulsa County, Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:Cities in Osage County, Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:Cities in Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:Tulsa metropolitan area]]\n[[Category:Populated places on the Arkansas River]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1911]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|City in Osage and Tulsa counties, Oklahoma, United States}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                     = Sand Springs, Oklahoma\n| settlement_type          = [[City]]\n| image_skyline            = \n| image_caption            = \n| image_blank_emblem       = Sand Springs logo.png\n| nickname                 = \n| motto                    = \n| image_map                = Tulsa County Oklahoma incorporated and unincorporated areas Sand Springs highlighted.svg\n| mapsize                  = 250px\n| map_caption              = Location within [[Tulsa County, OK|Tulsa County]] and [[Oklahoma]]\n| pushpin_map              = USA\n| pushpin_map_caption      = Location in the United States\n| coordinates              = {{coord|36|8|23|N|96|6|32|W|region:US-OK|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type         = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n| subdivision_name         = United States\n| subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n| subdivision_name1        = [[Oklahoma]]\n| subdivision_type2        = [[List of counties in Oklahoma|Counties]]\n| subdivision_name2        = [[Tulsa County, Oklahoma|Tulsa]], [[Osage County, Oklahoma|Osage]], [[Creek County]]\n| established_date         = 1912\n| government_type          = [[City Council]]\n| leader_title             = [[Mayor]]\n| leader_name              = Mike Burdge\n| area_total_km2           = 54.20\n| area_total_sq_mi         = 20.92\n| area_land_km2            = 50.19\n| area_land_sq_mi          = 19.38\n| area_water_km2           = 4.00\n| area_water_sq_mi         = 1.54\n| elevation_m              = 240\n| elevation_ft             = 670\n| population_total         = 18906\n| population_as_of         = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n| population_density_km2   = 396.40\n| population_density_sq_mi = 1026.68\n| population_metro         = \n| population_note          = \n| timezone                 = [[North American Central Time Zone|CST]]\n| utc_offset               = -6\n| timezone_DST             = [[North American Central Time Zone|CDT]]\n| utc_offset_DST           = -5\n| postal_code_type         = [[ZIP code]]\n| postal_code              = 74063\n| area_code                = [[area codes 539 and 918|539/918]]\n| blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n| blank_info               = 40-65300<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2008-01-31|title=U.S. Census website}}</ref>\n| blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n| blank1_info              = 1097783<ref name=\"GR3\">{{cite web|url=http://geonames.usgs.gov|accessdate=2008-01-31|title=US Board on Geographic Names|publisher=[[United States Geological Survey]]|date=2007-10-25|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120212191832/http://geonames.usgs.gov/|archivedate=2012-02-12}}</ref>\n| website                  = {{URL|http://www.sandspringsok.org/}}\n|pop_est_as_of = 2018\n|pop_est_footnotes = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2018CenPopScriptOnlyDirtyFixDoNotUse\"/>\n|population_est = 19897\n|unit_pref = Imperial\n|area_footnotes = <ref name=\"CenPopGazetteer2016\">{{cite web|title=2018 U.S. Gazetteer Files|url=https://www2.census.gov/geo/docs/maps-data/data/gazetteer/2018_Gazetteer/2018_gaz_place_40.txt|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=Feb 12, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Sand Springs''' is a city in [[Osage County, Oklahoma|Osage]] and [[Tulsa County, Oklahoma|Tulsa]] counties in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Oklahoma]]. A western suburb of [[Tulsa, Oklahoma|Tulsa]], it is located predominantly in Tulsa County. The population was 18,906 in the 2010 U. S. Census, an increase of 8.3 percent from 17,451 at the [[United States Census, 2000|2000 census]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://censusviewer.com/city/OK/Sand+Springs|title=Sand Springs, OK Population - Census 2010 and 2000 Interactive Map, Demographics, Statistics, Quick Facts - CensusViewer|website=censusviewer.com|accessdate=24 April 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180424123654/http://censusviewer.com/city/OK/Sand+Springs|archivedate=24 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe city was founded in 1911, by [[philanthropist]] [[Charles Page]], a wealthy businessman in Oklahoma. He envisioned Sand Springs as a haven for orphans and widows.  He helped found and develop Sand Springs as a model city that included all components of a total community.<ref name=\"EOHC-SS\">[http://www.okhistory.org/publications/enc/entry.php?entry=SA017 Carl N. Gregory, \"Sand Springs\", ''Encyclopedia of Oklahoma History and Culture''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402133246/http://www.okhistory.org/publications/enc/entry.php?entry=SA017 |date=2015-04-02 }}, Accessed May 6, 2011.</ref>\n\nPage bought 160 acres of land in Tulsa County, Oklahoma in 1908, intending to build a home for orphan children. The first 27 children, who had been abandoned by the Hook & Anchor Orphanage in Tulsa,<!-- what does this mean? they threw the orphans out? --> were housed in a tent. This was soon replaced by a frame building large enough to house 50 children.\n\nPage decided to form a model community, to be called Sand Springs, on land west of the children's home. He offered free land to any person who wished to move there, and a $20,000 bonus (the amount varied and he also offered free utilities) to companies that would relocate there. In 1911, Page created the [[Sand Springs Railway]], an interurban connecting Sand Springs to Tulsa. The townsite was laid out the same year.<ref name = \"EOHC-SS\"/> Sand Springs was incorporated as a city in 1912, with a population of 400.<ref name=\"Davenport\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tulsaokhistory.com/cities/sandsprings.html|title=History of Sand Springs, OK|website=www.tulsaokhistory.com|accessdate=24 April 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107112750/http://www.tulsaokhistory.com/cities/sandsprings.html|archivedate=7 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 1911 Page also built the Sand Springs Power Plant, on the southeast corner of Main Street and Morrow Road. It anchored an area that Page intended to use for industrial development. Several significant additions were made to the facility, and it was the sole source of electric power for Sand Springs until 1947.<ref>National Register of Historic Places Registration Form. \"Sand Springs Power Plant.\"</ref>\n\nSome of the earliest manufacturing industries were: Kerr Glass Manufacturing; Commander Mills, Kerr, Hubbard and Kelley Lamp, and Chimney; Southwest Box Company; and Sinclair Prairie Refining Company. Medical and social welfare institutions other than the Sand Springs Home included the Oakwood Sanitorium for nervous and mental diseases, Poole Hospital, the Salvation Army Maternity Home, and the Sand Springs School for the Deaf.<ref name = \"Davenport\" /> Sand Springs became a center of glass production in Oklahoma. Kerr Glass Manufacturing moved to Sand Springs from Chicago in 1913. It and the Alexander H. Kerr company, which made fruit jars, were the only glass companies remaining in business as recently as 1955.<ref name=\"EOHC-Glass\">[http://digital.library.okstate.edu/encyclopedia/entries/G/GL002.html Everett, Dianna. \"Glass Manufacturing\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110609161551/http://digital.library.okstate.edu/encyclopedia/entries/G/GL002.html |date=2011-06-09 }}, ''Encyclopedia of Oklahoma History and Culture''.</ref>\n\nThe Children's Home is still operating. What used to be the Widows Colony now accepts single mothers with two or more children.\n\nAn EF2 tornado hit Sand Springs on March 25, 2015, killing one resident, injuring 30 citizens, and damaging 50 mobile homes.<ref>https://www.weather.gov/oun/tornadodata-county-ok-tulsa</ref>\n\nOn November 26, 2018, Clyde Boyd Middle School had a [[Carbon Monoxide]] leak. The leak started sometime around the morning. Between 11:15 and 12:58, five students went homesick. And between 1:15 to 1:35, seven more students got sick.<ref>https://www.newson6.com/story/39546855/middle-school-students-treated-after-sand-springs-carbon-monoxide-leak</ref> Around 2:27, an announcement on the intercom told all the students to \"go to the new gym\". Many students went to the hospital from [[Carbon Monoxide Poisoning]]. \"There was no evidence of the presence of carbon monoxide in the 6th Grade Center\". Over 50 students were sent to nearby hospitals. The school didn't have carbon monoxide detectors at the time which the district says \"it'll resolve\". The School was closed for several days while they fixed the problem. <ref>https://www.newson6.com/story/39553912/sand-springs-school-still-closed-after-carbon-monoxide-leak</ref> \nThe district has now installed [[carbon monoxide detectors]].\n\n==Geography==\nSand Springs is located at {{coord|36|8|23|N|96|6|32|W|type:city}} (36.1398102, -96.1088911).<ref>{{GNIS|1092617}}</ref> According to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the city has a total area of 21.0&nbsp;square miles (54.3&nbsp;km\u00b2), of which, 18.7&nbsp;square miles (48.4&nbsp;km\u00b2) of it is land and 2.3&nbsp;square miles (5.9&nbsp;km\u00b2) of it (10.84%) is water. The one-way driving distance between Sand Springs and Tulsa (downtown to downtown) is about {{convert|7|miles|km}}. It is roughly located in the western section of [[Tulsa County]] and the Southern section of [[Osage County, Oklahoma|Osage County]] and has a small sliver of it within [[Creek County|Creek County's Northern western border]].<ref>https://www.openstreetmap.org/relation/184998#map=15/36.0745/-96.2046</ref><ref>https://ok.postcodebase.com/city/SAND%20SPRINGS</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1920= 4067\n|1930= 6674\n|1940= 6137\n|1950= 6994\n|1960= 7754\n|1970= 10555\n|1980= 13121\n|1990= 15346\n|2000= 17451\n|2010= 18906\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=19897\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018CenPopScriptOnlyDirtyFixDoNotUse\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=June 4, 2019}}</ref>\n|footnote=<ref name = \"EOHC-SS\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.census.gov/popest/data/cities/totals/2011/tables/SUB-EST2011-03-40.csv|title=Archived copy|accessdate=2017-12-07|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160203042832/http://www.census.gov/popest/data/cities/totals/2011/tables/SUB-EST2011-03-40.csv|archivedate=2016-02-03 }}</ref>\n}}\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name=\"GR2\" /> of 2000, there were 17,451 people, 6,564 households, and 4,870 families residing in the city. The [[population density]] was 934.2 people per square mile (360.7/km\u00b2). There were 6,979 housing units at an average density of 373.6 per square mile (144.3/km\u00b2). The racial makeup of the city was 85.85% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 1.85% [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], 7.13% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 0.44% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 0.02% [[Pacific Islander (U.S. Census)|Pacific Islander]], 0.47% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 4.25% from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 2.06% of the population.\n\nThere were 6,564 households out of which 38.1% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 58.3% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 12.3% had a female householder with no husband present, and 25.8% were non-families. 22.7% of all households were made up of individuals and 10.2% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.59 and the average family size was 3.05.\n\nIn the city, the population was spread out with 28.4% under the age of 18, 8.3% from 18 to 24, 28.9% from 25 to 44, 22.2% from 45 to 64, and 12.2% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 35 years. For every 100 females, there were 92.7 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 87.0 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the city was $40,380, and the median income for a family was $47,258. Males had a median income of $38,120 versus $25,373 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the city was $18,193. About 6.7% of families and 9.1% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 11.6% of those under age 18 and 7.6% of those age 65 or over.\n\n==Economy==\nThe economy of Sand Springs is largely focused on promoting small businesses. It has a very active chamber of commerce.\n\nAccording to the ''Encyclopedia of Oklahoma History & Culture'', the most significant businesses in 2000 were: Webco Industries, Sheffield Steel Corporation, Rader Diagnostic Center, Smith-Fibercast, Cust-O-Fab, Piping Companies Incorporated, and Baker Petrolite.<ref name = \"EOHC-SS\"/>\n\n==Historical Sites==\n{{main| National Register of Historic Places listings in Tulsa County, Oklahoma}} \nThe following are NRHP-listed sites in Sand Springs:\n*Fort Arbuckle Site, a/k/a Old Fort Arbuckle (west of Sand Springs)\n*Page Memorial Library (6 E. Broadway)\n*Sand Springs Power Plant (221 S.Main St.)\n\n==Education==\nThe Sand Springs Public School District is the largest employer in the city.  It contains five elementary schools, two middle schools, and three High Schools (two public and one private). It has a groundbreaking early childhood program.\n* [[Charles Page High School]]\n* [[Clyde Boyd Middle School]]\n* [[Central Ninth Grade Center]]\n* [[Angus Valley Elementary School]]\n* [[Harry T. Pratt Elementary School]]\n* [[Limestone Elementary School]]\n* [[Garfield Elementary School (Sand Springs, Oklahoma)|Garfield Elementary School]]\n* [[Northwoods Elementary School]]\n* Sixth Grade Center\n* Early Childhood Center\n* Page Academy (alternative)\n\nThere are also four private Christian schools in Sand Springs.\n* Amazing Grace Christian Academy\n* Heritage Baptist School\n* Landmark Christian Academy<ref>https://www.greatschools.org/oklahoma/sand-springs/3539-Landmark-Christian-Academy/</ref>\n* Moriah Christian Academy<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.MoriahChristianAcademy.com|title=Moriahchristianacademy.com|website=www.moriahchristianacademy.com|accessdate=24 April 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180416055846/http://moriahchristianacademy.com/|archivedate=16 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Media==\nSand Springs has one print newspaper, the [http://sandspringsleader.com ''Sand Springs Leader'']. It is published weekly on Thursday.\n\nOn April 21, 2015, the ''[[Tulsa World]]'' announced that its parent company BH Media,<ref>[http://www.bhmginc.com/ BH Media]</ref> a division of [[Berkshire Hathaway]], the Omaha-based investment holding company led by billionaire [[Warren Buffett]], had purchased several suburban newspapers, including the ''Sand Springs Leader''.<ref>[http://www.tulsaworld.com/business/employment/bh-media-group-buys-local-weeklies-tulsa-business-and-legal/article_3981761a-b40c-5fd3-8759-4898875c2e3f.html \"Media Group Buys Local Weeklies\"], ''[[Tulsa World]]''</ref><ref>[http://www.tulsaworld.com/opinion/editorials/tulsa-world-editorial-seven-local-newspapers-join-bh-media-family/article_dad541fd-9898-5de3-864e-23b818d6538d.html Opinion: \"Seven Local Newspapers Join BH Media Family\"], ''[[Tulsa World]]''</ref>\n\nSand Springs also has an online-only news source, ''Sandite Pride News'',<ref>[http://www.SanditePride.com ''Sandite Pride News'']</ref> which specializes in Sand Springs sports coverage.\n\n==Notable people==\n<!-- Include only people with existing WP article; must show connection to Sand Springs -->\n* [[Jerry Adair]] (1936\u20131987), professional baseball player<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.baseball-almanac.com/players/player.php?p=adairje01|title= Jerry Adair Stats|work= Baseball Almanac|accessdate= November 21, 2012|url-status= live|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20121024213933/http://www.baseball-almanac.com/players/player.php?p=adairje01|archivedate= October 24, 2012}}</ref>\n* [[Michael Bowie]] (b. 1991), professional football player and 2013 Super Bowl winner<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.washingtonpost.com/fb/playerstats.asp?id=26865|title=Football - NFL - Player Stats - Michael Bowie |website=The Washington Post |accessdate=24 April 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150908034814/http://stats.washingtonpost.com/fb/playerstats.asp?id=26865|archivedate=8 September 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Woody Crumbo]] (1912\u20131989), [[Aboriginal American|American Indian]] artist, [[flautist]], and dancer\n* [[Daton Fix]] (b. 1998), four-time undefeated state wrestling champion, national champion, Pan-American champion, Junior World Champion, Junior Olympic Silver Medalist, and Big 12 Champion.\n* [[Neal Hallford]] (b. 1966), [[game designer]], author, and film producer\n* [[Sam Harris (singer)|Sam Harris]] (b. 1961), Tony-nominated actor and singer who was Male Vocalist champion of the first season of ''[[Star Search]]''\n* [[Marques Haynes]] (1926\u20132015), [[Harlem Globetrotters]] player<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.okhistory.org/publications/enc/entry.php?entry=HA055|title=Haynes, Marques(1926- )|publisher=Encyclopedia of Oklahoma History & Culture|accessdate=November 21, 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402155842/http://www.okhistory.org/publications/enc/entry.php?entry=HA055|archivedate=April 2, 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Charles Page]] (1860\u20131926), [[oilman]], founder of Sand Springs\n* [[Cindy Pickett]] (b. 1947), actress\n* [[William R. Pogue]] (1930\u20132014), [[Skylab]] astronaut, author, and pilot\n* [[Robert D. Simms]] (1926\u20132008), native of Sand Springs, attorney, judge, Associate Justice of Oklahoma Supreme Court\n* [[Mae Young]] (1923\u20132014), professional wrestler<ref>{{cite web |author=Ryan Nation |date=March 27, 2008 |title=HOFer Mae Young vows to keep wrestling |url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/WrestleMania24/2008/03/27/5124611.html |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130101030256/http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/WrestleMania24/2008/03/27/5124611.html |archive-date=1 January 2013 |work=Slam! Wrestling |publisher=[[Canoe.ca|Canadian Online Explorer]] |access-date=29 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.sandspringsok.org/ City of Sand Springs]\n\n{{Osage County, Oklahoma}}\n{{Tulsa County, Oklahoma}}\n{{Tulsa metro}}\n{{NRHP in Tulsa County}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Cities in Tulsa County, Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:Cities in Osage County, Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:Cities in Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:Tulsa metropolitan area]]\n[[Category:Populated places on the Arkansas River]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1911]]\n", "name_user": "Jerry Steinfield", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixed up some information of the location", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sand_Springs,_Oklahoma"}
{"title_page": "Shambhala", "text_new": "{{short description|Mythical kingdom in Tibetan Buddhism}}\n{{for|the Buddhist practice community|Shambhala Buddhism}}\n{{for|the town in China|Shambala, Xiangcheng County, Sichuan}}\n{{contains Tibetan text}}\nIn  [[Tibetan Buddhism|Tibetan Buddhist]] tradition, '''Shambhala''' ({{lang-sa|\u0936\u092e\u094d\u092d\u0932}} ''{{IAST|\u015aambhala}}'',<ref name=MW>\n''\u015aambhala'', also ''Sambhala'', is the name of a town   between the Rathapr\u0101 and Ganges rivers,  identified by some with [[Sambhal]] in Uttar Pradesh.\nIn the [[Purana]]s, it is named as the place where [[Kalki]], the last incarnation of Vishnu, is to appear (Monier-Williams, ''Sanskrit-English Dictionary'', 1899).</ref> also spelled ''Shambala'' or ''Shamballa''; {{bo|t=\u0f56\u0f51\u0f7a\u0f0b\u0f60\u0f56\u0fb1\u0f74\u0f44|w=Bde'byung}}; {{zh|c=\u9999\u5df4\u62c9|p=Xi\u0101ngb\u0101l\u0101}}) is a mythical kingdom.\nShambhala  is mentioned in the ''[[Kalachakra|Kalachakra Tantra]]''.<ref>{{cite book|author=Alf Hiltebeitel|title=Rethinking India's Oral and Classical Epics|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uV-RrRoMzbgC|year=1999|publisher=University of Chicago Press|isbn=978-0-226-34050-0|pages=217\u2013218}}</ref><ref>The Tantra by Victor M. Fic, Abhinav Publications, 2003, p.49.</ref> \n<!-- and the ancient [[Zhangzhung]] texts of western Tibet.{{cn}}-->\nThe [[Bon]] scriptures speak of a closely related land called [[Tagzig Olmo Lung Ring]].<ref>The Bon Religion of Tibet by Per Kav\u01e3rne, Shambhala, 1996</ref>\n\nThe Sanskrit name is taken from the name of a city mentioned in the [[Hinduism|Hindu]] [[Purana]]s, probably in reference to [[Sambhal]] in Uttar Pradesh.\nThe mythological relevance of the place originates with a prophecy in ''[[Vishnu Purana]]'' (4.24) according to which Shambhala will be the birthplace of [[Kalki]], the final incarnation of [[Vishnu]], who will usher in a new Age ([[Satya Yuga]]).<ref name=MW/><ref name=Hindu>{{cite book|last=LePage|first=Victoria|title=Shambhala: The Fascinating Truth Behind the Myth of Shangri-La|year=1996|publisher=Quest Books|isbn=9780835607506|pages=125\u2013126|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oUIum8H_9qgC}}</ref>\n\n== Kalachakra tantra==\n[[File:Rigdan Tagpa.jpg|thumb|right|220 px|Manju\u015br\u012bk\u012brti, [[Kings of Shambhala|King of Shambhala]]]]\n{{main|Kalachakra}}\n{{see|Kings of Shambhala}}\n\nThe Shambhala narrative is found in the ''Kalachakra tantra'', a text of the group of the [[Anuttarayoga Tantra]]s.\nKalachakra Buddhism was presumably introduced to Tibet still in the 11th century, the epoch of the [[Tibetan calendar|Tibetan Kalachakra calendar]]. The oldest known teachers of Kalachakra are [[Dolpopa Sherab Gyaltsen]] (d. 1361) and [[Buton Rinchen Drub]] (d. 1364).\n\nIn the narrative, king Manju\u015br\u012bk\u012brti is said to have been born in 159 BC and ruled over a kingdom of 300,510 followers of the [[Mlechha]] religion, some of whom worshipped the Sun. He is said to have expelled 20,000 people from his domain who clung to 'Surya Samadhi' (solar worship) rather than convert to Kalachakra (Wheel of Time) Buddhism. <!--These expelled Rishis, seers, sages and saints, who had realized truth and eternal knowledge exclaimed, \"We want to remain true to our Sun-Chariot. We do not wish to give up our belief system to change to another.\" -->\nAfter realizing these were the wisest and best of his people and how much he was in need of them, he later asked them to return, and some did. \nThose who did not return are said to have set up the city of Shambhala. \nManju\u015br\u012bk\u012brti initiated the preaching of the ''Kalachakra'' teachings in order to try to convert those who returned and were still under his rule. In 59 BC he abdicated his throne to his son, Pu\u1e47\u1e0d\u0101rika, and died soon afterward, entering the [[Sambhogakaya]] of Buddhahood.<ref>Das, Sarat Chandra (1882). ''Contributions to the Religion and History of Tibet'', in ''Journal of the Asiatic Society of Bengal'', Vol. LI. Reprint: Manjushri Publishing House, Delhi. 1970, pp. 81\u20132.</ref><ref>Edwin Bernbaum \"The Way to Shambhala: A Search for the Mythical Kingdom Beyond the Himalayas\" 1980 & Albert Gr\u00fcnwedel \"Der Weg nach Shambhala\" 1915</ref>\n\nThe Kalachakra tantra prophesies that when the world declines into war and greed, and all is lost, the 25th Kalki king will emerge from Shambhala with a huge army to vanquish Dark Forces and usher in a worldwide [[Golden Age]]. \nThis final battle is prophesied for the year [[25th century|2424 or 2425]] (in the 5,104th year after the [[Gautama_Buddha#Mahaparinirvana_(death)|death of Buddha]]).<ref> Alexander Berzin, ''Taking the Kalachakra Initiation''  (1997), p. 33.\nLubosh Belka, \"The Shambhala Myth in Buryatia and Mongolia\", in: Tomasz Gacek, Jadwiga Pstrusi\u0144ska (eds.), ''Proceedings of the Ninth Conference of the European Society for Central Asian Studies'', Cambridge Scholars Publishing (2009), pp. 19-30 \n([https://books.google.ch/books?id=afQZBwAAQBAJ&pg=PA20 p. 20f]).</ref>\n\n==Western reception==\nTibet and Tibetan Buddhism  were largely unknown in the West prior to the beginning of the 20th century.<ref>Lopez, Donald S. Jr. ''Prisoners of Shangri~La, Tibetan Buddhism and the West'', The University of Chicago Press, 1998</ref> The name itself, however, was reported as early as the 17th century, by way of  [[Est\u00eav\u00e3o Cacella]], the [[Portugal|Portuguese]] [[Catholic missions|missionary]] who had heard about Shambhala (transcribed as  ''Xembala''), and thought it was another name for [[Cathay]] or China.  Cacella in 1627  headed to [[Tashilhunpo]], the seat of the [[Panchen Lama]] and, discovering his mistake, returned to India.<ref>Bernbaum, Edwin. (1980). ''The Way to Shambhala'', pp. 18-19. Reprint: (1989). Jeremy P. Tarcher, Inc., Los Angeles. {{ISBN|0-87477-518-3}}.</ref>\n\nThe Hungarian scholar [[S\u00e1ndor K\u0151r\u00f6si Csoma]], writing in 1833, provided the first geographic account of \"a fabulous country in the north...situated between 45' and 50' north latitude\".{{cn|date=October 2019}}\n\n===Theosophy===\nDuring the late 19th century, [[Theosophy (Blavatskian)|Theosophical Society]] co-founder [[Helena Blavatsky]] alluded to the Shambhala myth. Blavatsky, who claimed to be in contact with a [[Great White Brotherhood|Great White Lodge]] of Himalayan Adepts, mentions Shambhala in several places, but without giving it especially great emphasis.\n\nLater [[esotericism|esoteric]] writers further emphasized and elaborated on the concept of a hidden land inhabited by a [[Masters of the Ancient Wisdom|hidden mystic brotherhood]] whose members labor for the good of humanity. [[Alice A. Bailey]] claims Shamballa (her spelling) is an extra-dimensional or spiritual reality on the [[etheric plane]], a spiritual centre where the governing [[deity]] of [[Earth]], [[Sanat Kumara]], dwells as the highest [[Avatar]] of the Planetary [[Logos]] of Earth, and is said to be an expression of the Will of God.<ref>Bailey, Alice A, ''A Treatise on Cosmic Fire'' 1932 Lucis Trust. 1925, p 753</ref>\n\n===Expeditions and location hypotheses===\n[[Nicholas Roerich|Nicholas]] and [[Helena Roerich]] led a 1924\u20131928 expedition aimed at Shambhala.<ref>Archer, Kenneth. ''Roerich East & West''. Parkstone Press 1999, p.94</ref>\n\nInspired by [[Theosophy (disambiguation)|Theosophical]] lore and several visiting Mongol lamas, [[Gleb Bokii]], the chief Bolshevik [[cryptographer]] and one of the bosses of the [[Soviet secret police]], along with his writer friend Alexander Barchenko, embarked on a quest for Shambhala, in an attempt to merge Kalachakra-tantra and ideas of Communism in the 1920s. Among other things, in a secret laboratory affiliated with the secret police, Bokii and Barchenko experimented with Buddhist spiritual techniques to try to find a key for engineering perfect communist human beings.<ref name=\"Znamenski\">Znamenski (2011)</ref> They contemplated a special expedition to Inner Asia to retrieve the wisdom of Shambhala \u2013 the project fell through as a result of intrigues within the Soviet intelligence service, as well as rival efforts of the [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Soviet Union)|Soviet Foreign Commissariat]] that sent its own expedition to Tibet in 1924.\n\nFrench Buddhist [[Alexandra David-N\u00e9el]] associated Shambhala with [[Balkh]] in present-day Afghanistan, also offering the Persian ''Sham-i-Bala'', \"elevated candle\" as an etymology of its name.<ref>David-N\u00e9el, A. ''[[Les Nouvelles litt\u00e9raires]]'' ;1954, p.1</ref> \nIn a similar vein, the [[Gurdjieff]]ian [[J. G. Bennett]] published speculation that Shambalha was ''Shams-i-Balkh'', a [[Bactria]]n sun temple.<ref>Bennett, J.G: \"Gurdjieff: Making a New World\". Bennett notes [[Idries Shah]] as the source of the suggestion.</ref>\n\n=== In popular culture ===\nShambhala may have been the inspiration for [[Shangri-La]], a paradise on Earth hidden in a Tibetan valley, which features in the 1933 novel ''[[Lost Horizon]]'' by British author [[James Hilton (novelist)|James Hilton]].<ref name=\"Wood11\">{{cite news|last1=Wood|first1=Michael|title=BBC - History - Ancient History in depth: Shangri-La|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/history/ancient/cultures/shangri_la_01.shtml|accessdate=28 February 2018|work=BBC|date=17 February 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, the mythical city was depicted in the critically-acclaimed action-adventure video game [[Uncharted 2: Among Thieves]]. The linear story game follows treasure hunter [[Nathan Drake (character)|Nathan Drake]] (whom the player controls) in search of the lost city.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Tagzig Olmo Lung Ring]]\n*[[Shangri-La]]\n*[[Sagala]]\n*[[Lost city]]\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Refbegin|30em}}\n* Rock opera [http://szambalia.pl/ \"Szambalia\"] (\"Shambhala\") (2014). Official premiere in Poland, Warsaw (24.06.2014)\n* Rock song \"Halls of Shambala\" by [[B. W. Stevenson]], covered and popularized by the rock band [[Three Dog Night]] [[Shambala (song)]]\n* [[Alexander Berzin (scholar)|Berzin, Alexander]] (2003). Study Buddhism. ''[http://studybuddhism.com/en/advanced-studies/history-culture/shambhala/mistaken-foreign-myths-about-shambhala Mistaken Foreign Myths about Shambhala]''.\n* Martin, Dean. (1999). \"'Ol-mo-lung-ring, the Original Holy Place.\" In: ''Sacred Spaces and Powerful Places In Tibetan Culture: A Collection of Essays''. (1999) Edited by Toni Huber, pp.&nbsp;125\u2013153. The Library of Tibetan Works and Archives, Dharamsala, H.P., India. {{ISBN|81-86470-22-0}}.\n* [[Meyer, Karl Ernest]] and [[Brysac, Shareen Blair]] (2006) ''Tournament of Shadows: The Great Game And the Race for Empire in Central Asia'' {{ISBN|0-465-04576-6}}\n* Bernbaum, Edwin. (1980). ''The Way to Shambhala: A Search for the Mythical Kingdom Beyond the Himalayas''. Reprint: (1989) St. Martin's Press, New York. {{ISBN|0-87477-518-3}}.\n* Jeffrey, Jason. [http://www.newdawnmagazine.com/articles/mystery_of_shambhala_part_one.html Mystery of Shambhala]  in ''New Dawn'', No. 72 (May\u2013June 2002).\n* [[Chogyam Trungpa|Trungpa, Chogyam]]. ''Shambhala: The Sacred Path of the Warrior''. [[Shambhala Publications]]. {{ISBN|0-87773-264-7}}\n* Znamenski, Andrei. (2011). ''Red Shambhala: Magic, Prophecy, and Geopolitics in the Heart of Asia''. Quest Books, Wheaton, IL (2011) {{ISBN|978-0-8356-0891-6}}.\n*\"Tibetan Buddhist Atrocities and Propaganda.\" Dr. S. D'Montford. \"Tibetan Buddhist Atrocities and Propaganda.\" Happy Medium Publishing. Sydney. 2004\n* [[Charles Allen (writer)|Allen, Charles]]. (1999). ''The Search for [[Shangri-La]]: A Journey into Tibetan History''. Little, Brown and Company. Reprint: Abacus, London. 2000. {{ISBN|0-349-11142-1}}.\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=ZlBbBgAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=stalin+furious+buryat+ungern&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj1vfv5pInKAhXDVyYKHeYgDjEQ6AEIJTAA#v=onepage&q&f=false Znamenski, Andrei.] ''[https://www.amazon.com/dp/0835608913 Red Shambhala: Magic, Prophecy, and Geopolitics in the Heart of Asia]''. Wheaton, IL: Quest Books, 2011. {{ISBN|978-0-8356-0891-6}}\n* Martin, Dan. (1999). \"'Ol-mo-lung-ring, the Original Holy Place.\" In: ''Sacred Spaces and Powerful Places In Tibetan Culture: A Collection of Essays''. (1999) Edited by Toni Huber, pp.&nbsp;125\u2013153. The Library of Tibetan Works and Archives, Dharamsala, H.P., India. {{ISBN|81-86470-22-0}}.\n* Symmes, Patrick. (2007).  \"The Kingdom of the Lotus\" in ''[[Outside (magazine)|Outside]]'', 30th Anniversary Special Edition, pp.&nbsp;148\u2013187. Mariah Media, Inc., Red Oak, Iowa.\n* Meurois, Daniel et Anne Givaudan (1987). \u00ab Le Voyage a Shambhalla. Un p\u00e8lerinage vers soi\u00a0\u00bb Ed. Le Passe-Monde.\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Commonscatinline}}\n\n{{Buddhism topics}}\n\n[[Category:Locations in Buddhist mythology]]\n[[Category:Mythological kingdoms, empires, and countries]]\n[[Category:Tibetan Buddhism]]\n[[Category:Theosophy]]\n[[Category:Shambhala Vision]]\n[[Category:Mythological places]]\n[[Category:Pure lands]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Mythical kingdom in Tibetan Buddhism}}\n{{for|the Buddhist practice community|Shambhala Buddhism}}\n{{for|the town in China|Shambala, Xiangcheng County, Sichuan}}\n{{contains Tibetan text}}\nIn  [[Tibetan Buddhism|Tibetan Buddhist]] tradition, '''Shambhala''' ({{lang-sa|\u0936\u092e\u094d\u092d\u0932}} ''{{IAST|\u015aambhala}}'',<ref name=MW>\n''\u015aambhala'', also ''Sambhala'', is the name of a town   between the Rathapr\u0101 and Ganges rivers,  identified by some with [[Sambhal]] in Uttar Pradesh.\nIn the [[Purana]]s, it is named as the place where [[Kalki]], the last incarnation of Vishnu, is to appear (Monier-Williams, ''Sanskrit-English Dictionary'', 1899).</ref> also spelled ''Shambala'' or ''Shamballa''; {{bo|t=\u0f56\u0f51\u0f7a\u0f0b\u0f60\u0f56\u0fb1\u0f74\u0f44|w=Bde'byung}}; {{zh|c=\u9999\u5df4\u62c9|p=Xi\u0101ngb\u0101l\u0101}}) is a mythical kingdom.\nShambhala  is mentioned in the ''[[Kalachakra|Kalachakra Tantra]]''.<ref>{{cite book|author=Alf Hiltebeitel|title=Rethinking India's Oral and Classical Epics|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uV-RrRoMzbgC|year=1999|publisher=University of Chicago Press|isbn=978-0-226-34050-0|pages=217\u2013218}}</ref><ref>The Tantra by Victor M. Fic, Abhinav Publications, 2003, p.49.</ref> \n<!-- and the ancient [[Zhangzhung]] texts of western Tibet.{{cn}}-->\nThe [[Bon]] scriptures speak of a closely related land called [[Tagzig Olmo Lung Ring]].<ref>The Bon Religion of Tibet by Per Kav\u01e3rne, Shambhala, 1996</ref>\n\nThe Sanskrit name is taken from the name of a city mentioned in the [[Hinduism|Hindu]] [[Purana]]s, probably in reference to [[Sambhal]] in Uttar Pradesh.\nThe mythological relevance of the place originates with a prophecy in ''[[Vishnu Purana]]'' (4.24) according to which Shambhala will be the birthplace of [[Kalki]], the final incarnation of [[Vishnu]], who will usher in a new Age ([[Satya Yuga]]).<ref name=MW/><ref name=Hindu>{{cite book|last=LePage|first=Victoria|title=Shambhala: The Fascinating Truth Behind the Myth of Shangri-La|year=1996|publisher=Quest Books|isbn=9780835607506|pages=125\u2013126|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oUIum8H_9qgC}}</ref>\n\n== Kalachakra tantra==\n[[File:Rigdan Tagpa.jpg|thumb|right|220 px|Manju\u015br\u012bk\u012brti, [[Kings of Shambhala|King of Shambhala]]]]\n{{main|Kalachakra}}\n{{see|Kings of Shambhala}}\n\nThe Shambhala narrative is found in the ''Kalachakra tantra'', a text of the group of the [[Anuttarayoga Tantra]]s.\nKalachakra Buddhism was presumably introduced to Tibet still in the 11th century, the epoch of the [[Tibetan calendar|Tibetan Kalachakra calendar]]. The oldest known teachers of Kalachakra are [[Dolpopa Sherab Gyaltsen]] (d. 1361) and [[Buton Rinchen Drub]] (d. 1364).\n\nIn the narrative, king Manju\u015br\u012bk\u012brti is said to have been born in 159 BC and ruled over a kingdom of 300,510 followers of the [[Mlechha]] religion, some of whom worshipped the Sun. He is said to have expelled 20,000 people from his domain who clung to 'Surya Samadhi' (solar worship) rather than convert to Kalachakra (Wheel of Time) Buddhism. <!--These expelled Rishis, seers, sages and saints, who had realized truth and eternal knowledge exclaimed, \"We want to remain true to our Sun-Chariot. We do not wish to give up our belief system to change to another.\" -->\nAfter realizing these were the wisest and best of his people and how much he was in need of them, he later asked them to return, and some did. \nThose who did not return are said to have set up the city of Shambhala. \nManju\u015br\u012bk\u012brti initiated the preaching of the ''Kalachakra'' teachings in order to try to convert those who returned and were still under his rule. In 59 BC he abdicated his throne to his son, Pu\u1e47\u1e0d\u0101rika, and died soon afterward, entering the [[Sambhogakaya]] of Buddhahood.<ref>Das, Sarat Chandra (1882). ''Contributions to the Religion and History of Tibet'', in ''Journal of the Asiatic Society of Bengal'', Vol. LI. Reprint: Manjushri Publishing House, Delhi. 1970, pp. 81\u20132.</ref><ref>Edwin Bernbaum \"The Way to Shambhala: A Search for the Mythical Kingdom Beyond the Himalayas\" 1980 & Albert Gr\u00fcnwedel \"Der Weg nach Shambhala\" 1915</ref>\n\nThe Kalachakra tantra prophesies that when the world declines into war and greed, and all is lost, the 25th Kalki king will emerge from Shambhala with a huge army to vanquish Dark Forces and usher in a worldwide [[Golden Age]]. \nThis final battle is prophesied for the year [[25th century|2424 or 2425]] (in the 5,104th year after the [[Gautama_Buddha#Mahaparinirvana_(death)|death of Buddha]]).<ref> Alexander Berzin, ''Taking the Kalachakra Initiation''  (1997), p. 33.\nLubosh Belka, \"The Shambhala Myth in Buryatia and Mongolia\", in: Tomasz Gacek, Jadwiga Pstrusi\u0144ska (eds.), ''Proceedings of the Ninth Conference of the European Society for Central Asian Studies'', Cambridge Scholars Publishing (2009), pp. 19-30 \n([https://books.google.ch/books?id=afQZBwAAQBAJ&pg=PA20 p. 20f]).</ref>\n\n==Western reception==\nTibet and Tibetan Buddhism  were largely unknown in the West prior to the beginning of the 20th century.<ref>Lopez, Donald S. Jr. ''Prisoners of Shangri~La, Tibetan Buddhism and the West'', The University of Chicago Press, 1998</ref> The name itself, however, was reported as early as the 17th century, by way of  [[Est\u00eav\u00e3o Cacella]], the [[Portugal|Portuguese]] [[Catholic missions|missionary]] who had heard about Shambhala (transcribed as  ''Xembala''), and thought it was another name for [[Cathay]] or China.  Cacella in 1627  headed to [[Tashilhunpo]], the seat of the [[Panchen Lama]] and, discovering his mistake, returned to India.<ref>Bernbaum, Edwin. (1980). ''The Way to Shambhala'', pp. 18-19. Reprint: (1989). Jeremy P. Tarcher, Inc., Los Angeles. {{ISBN|0-87477-518-3}}.</ref>\n\nThe Hungarian scholar [[S\u00e1ndor K\u0151r\u00f6si Csoma]], writing in 1833, provided the first geographic account of \"a fabulous country in the north...situated between 45' and 50' north latitude\".{{cn|date=October 2019}}\n\n===Theosophy===\nDuring the late 19th century, [[Theosophy (Blavatskian)|Theosophical Society]] co-founder [[Helena Blavatsky]] alluded to the Shambhala myth. Blavatsky, who claimed to be in contact with a [[Great White Brotherhood|Great White Lodge]] of Himalayan Adepts, mentions Shambhala in several places, but without giving it especially great emphasis.\n\nLater [[esotericism|esoteric]] writers further emphasized and elaborated on the concept of a hidden land inhabited by a [[Masters of the Ancient Wisdom|hidden mystic brotherhood]] whose members labor for the good of humanity. [[Alice A. Bailey]] claims Shamballa (her spelling) is an extra-dimensional or spiritual reality on the [[etheric plane]], a spiritual centre where the governing [[deity]] of [[Earth]], [[Sanat Kumara]], dwells as the highest [[Avatar]] of the Planetary [[Logos]] of Earth, and is said to be an expression of the Will of God.<ref>Bailey, Alice A, ''A Treatise on Cosmic Fire'' 1932 Lucis Trust. 1925, p 753</ref>\n\n===Expeditions and location hypotheses===\n[[Nicholas Roerich|Nicholas]] and [[Helena Roerich]] led a 1924\u20131928 expedition aimed at Shambhala.<ref>Archer, Kenneth. ''Roerich East & West''. Parkstone Press 1999, p.94</ref>\n\nInspired by [[Theosophy (disambiguation)|Theosophical]] lore and several visiting Mongol lamas, [[Gleb Bokii]], the chief Bolshevik [[cryptographer]] and one of the bosses of the [[Soviet secret police]], along with his writer friend Alexander Barchenko, embarked on a quest for Shambhala, in an attempt to merge Kalachakra-tantra and ideas of Communism in the 1920s. Among other things, in a secret laboratory affiliated with the secret police, Bokii and Barchenko experimented with Buddhist spiritual techniques to try to find a key for engineering perfect communist human beings.<ref name=\"Znamenski\">Znamenski (2011)</ref> They contemplated a special expedition to Inner Asia to retrieve the wisdom of Shambhala \u2013 the project fell through as a result of intrigues within the Soviet intelligence service, as well as rival efforts of the [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Soviet Union)|Soviet Foreign Commissariat]] that sent its own expedition to Tibet in 1924.\n\nFrench Buddhist [[Alexandra David-N\u00e9el]] associated Shambhala with [[Balkh]] in present-day Afghanistan, also offering the Persian ''Sham-i-Bala'', \"elevated candle\" as an etymology of its name.<ref>David-N\u00e9el, A. ''[[Les Nouvelles litt\u00e9raires]]'' ;1954, p.1</ref> \nIn a similar vein, the [[Gurdjieff]]ian [[J. G. Bennett]] published speculation that Shambalha was ''Shams-i-Balkh'', a [[Bactria]]n sun temple.<ref>Bennett, J.G: \"Gurdjieff: Making a New World\". Bennett notes [[Idries Shah]] as the source of the suggestion.</ref>\n\n=== In popular culture ===\nShambhala may have been the inspiration for [[Shangri-La]], a paradise on Earth hidden in a Tibetan valley, which features in the 1933 novel ''[[Lost Horizon]]'' by British author [[James Hilton (novelist)|James Hilton]].<ref name=\"Wood11\">{{cite news|last1=Wood|first1=Michael|title=BBC - History - Ancient History in depth: Shangri-La|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/history/ancient/cultures/shangri_la_01.shtml|accessdate=28 February 2018|work=BBC|date=17 February 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, the mythical city was depicted in the critically-acclaimed action-adventure video game [[Uncharted 2: Among Thieves]]. The linear story game follows treasure hunter [[Nathan Drake]] (whom the player controls) in search of the lost city.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Tagzig Olmo Lung Ring]]\n*[[Shangri-La]]\n*[[Sagala]]\n*[[Lost city]]\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Refbegin|30em}}\n* Rock opera [http://szambalia.pl/ \"Szambalia\"] (\"Shambhala\") (2014). Official premiere in Poland, Warsaw (24.06.2014)\n* Rock song \"Halls of Shambala\" by [[B. W. Stevenson]], covered and popularized by the rock band [[Three Dog Night]] [[Shambala (song)]]\n* [[Alexander Berzin (scholar)|Berzin, Alexander]] (2003). Study Buddhism. ''[http://studybuddhism.com/en/advanced-studies/history-culture/shambhala/mistaken-foreign-myths-about-shambhala Mistaken Foreign Myths about Shambhala]''.\n* Martin, Dean. (1999). \"'Ol-mo-lung-ring, the Original Holy Place.\" In: ''Sacred Spaces and Powerful Places In Tibetan Culture: A Collection of Essays''. (1999) Edited by Toni Huber, pp.&nbsp;125\u2013153. The Library of Tibetan Works and Archives, Dharamsala, H.P., India. {{ISBN|81-86470-22-0}}.\n* [[Meyer, Karl Ernest]] and [[Brysac, Shareen Blair]] (2006) ''Tournament of Shadows: The Great Game And the Race for Empire in Central Asia'' {{ISBN|0-465-04576-6}}\n* Bernbaum, Edwin. (1980). ''The Way to Shambhala: A